{"title_page": "Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies", "text_new": "{{short description|UK governmental advisory body}}\nThe '''Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies''' ('''SAGE''') is a UK governmental advisory body that advises central government in emergencies. It is usually chaired by the UK's [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]].<ref name=gov.uk>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/scientific-advisory-group-for-emergencies-sage|title=Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies (SAGE)|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/perspective/2014/uk-response-fukushima-and-anglo-japanese-relations|title=The UK Response to Fukushima and Anglo-Japanese Relations|website=Science & Diplomacy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nDuring the COVID19 pandemic, SAGE was wrongly criticised for a lack of transparency.<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\">{{cite web |last1=Landler |first1=Mark |last2=Castle |first2=Stephen |title=The Secretive Group Guiding the U.K. on Coronavirus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/23/world/europe/uk-coronavirus-sage-secret.html |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Its list of members are not secret and are listed on public minutes of each meeting (members themselves are not prohibited from confirming their involvement),<ref name=\"bbc-cummings\"/> all meetings and recommendations are made public on the SAGE website.  During the 2020 COVID19 pandemic, [[Chris Whitty]], speaking to the [[Health and Social Care Committee]], said that SAGE was \"given quite clear advice from the [[Centre for the Protection of National Infrastructure]] basically based on the fact that SAGE is a sub-committee of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|Cobra]]\".<ref name=\"indep-sharman-sage\">{{cite web |last1=Sharman |first1=Jon |title=Publishing Sage membership would \u2018increase public confidence\u2019 in government, agrees Whitty |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-sage-evidence-chris-whitty-public-members-a9482941.html |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> [[Patrick Vallance]] argued in a letter to [[Parliament]] that scientists were protected by the anonymity from \"lobbying and other forms of unwanted influence\".<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\"/>\n\n== Outbreaks and pandemics ==\nSAGE has advised the government on a number of events, including:<ref name=gov.uk/>\n\n* the [[2009 flu pandemic]]\n* the [[2010 eruptions of Eyjafjallaj\u00f6kull]]\n* the 2011 [[Fukushima nuclear accident]]\n* the [[2013\u201314 United Kingdom winter floods]]\n* the [[2014 Ebola outbreak]]\n* the [[2015 Nepal earthquake]]\n* the [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]]\n* the potential catastrophic breach of [[Toddbrook reservoir]] in 2019\n* the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n== Members ==\n{{As of|2020|04}}, during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], members of the group included:<ref>{{Cite news|first=Ian |last=Sample|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/24/coronavirus-whos-who-on-secret-scientific-group-advising-uk-government-sage|title=Who's who on secret scientific group advising UK government?|date=2020-04-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n{{div col}}\n* Sir [[Patrick Vallance]]\n* Professor [[Chris Whitty]]\n* Professor [[Jonathan Van-Tam]]\n* Professor [[Stephen Powis]]\n* Professor [[Sharon Peacock]]\n* Professor [[Maria Zambon (scientist)|Maria Zambon]]\n* [[Meera Chand (Public Health England)|Meera Chand]]\n* Professor [[Charlotte Watts]]\n* Professor [[John Aston (statistician)|John Aston]]\n* Professor [[Angela McLean (mathematical biologist)|Angela McLean]]\n* Sir [[Ian Diamond]]\n* Professor [[Graham Medley]]\n* Professor [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Neil Ferguson]]\n* Professor [[John Edmunds (epidemiologist)|John Edmunds]]\n* [[James Rubin (psychologist)|James Rubin]]\n* Professor [[Brooke Rogers]]\n* Professor [[Peter Horby]]\n* Sir [[Jeremy Farrar]]\n* Professor [[Andrew Rambaut (molecular biologist)|Andrew Rambaut]]\n* [[Emma Reed (Department of Health and Social Care)|Emma Reed]]\n* Dr [[Edward Mullins]]\n* [[Dominic Cummings]]<ref name=\"guardian-sage-covid\">{{cite web |title=Revealed: Cummings is on secret scientific advisory group for Covid-19 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/24/revealed-dominic-cummings-on-secret-scientific-advisory-group-for-covid-19 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Warner (data scientist)|Ben Warner]]<ref name=\"guardian-sage-covid\"/>\n{{div col end}}\n\nVallance has written that SAGE includes scientists and experts from more than twenty separate institutions. SAGE also contains four expert groups which may each have as low as five and as many as over forty members.<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\"/>\n\nDominic Cummings was confirmed by [[Downing Street]] to have attended a 23 March meeting, but the government said Cummings was not a member of SAGE.<ref name=\"bbc-cummings\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Dominic Cummings attended meetings of key scientific group |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52421744 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[COBR]]\n* [[New and Emerging Respiratory Virus Threats Advisory Group]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/scientific-advisory-group-for-emergencies-sage}}\n\n{{Science and technology in the United Kingdom}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Science and technology in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Emergency management in the United Kingdom]]\n\n\n{{UK-gov-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|UK governmental advisory body}}\nThe '''Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies''' ('''SAGE''') is a UK governmental advisory body that advises central government in emergencies. It is usually chaired by the UK's [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]].<ref name=gov.uk>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/scientific-advisory-group-for-emergencies-sage|title=Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies (SAGE)|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/perspective/2014/uk-response-fukushima-and-anglo-japanese-relations|title=The UK Response to Fukushima and Anglo-Japanese Relations|website=Science & Diplomacy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nSAGE has been criticised for a lack of transparency.<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\">{{cite web |last1=Landler |first1=Mark |last2=Castle |first2=Stephen |title=The Secretive Group Guiding the U.K. on Coronavirus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/23/world/europe/uk-coronavirus-sage-secret.html |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Its list of members is secret (though members themselves are not prohibited from confirming their involvement),<ref name=\"bbc-cummings\"/> and its meetings and recommendations are not made public. [[Chris Whitty]], speaking to the [[Health and Social Care Committee]], said that SAGE was \"given quite clear advice from the [[Centre for the Protection of National Infrastructure]] basically based on the fact that SAGE is a sub-committee of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|Cobra]]\".<ref name=\"indep-sharman-sage\">{{cite web |last1=Sharman |first1=Jon |title=Publishing Sage membership would \u2018increase public confidence\u2019 in government, agrees Whitty |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-sage-evidence-chris-whitty-public-members-a9482941.html |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> [[Patrick Vallance]] argued in a letter to [[Parliament]] that scientists were protected by the anonymity from \"lobbying and other forms of unwanted influence\".<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\"/>\n\n== Outbreaks and pandemics ==\nSAGE has advised the government on a number of events, including:<ref name=gov.uk/>\n\n* the [[2009 flu pandemic]]\n* the [[2010 eruptions of Eyjafjallaj\u00f6kull]]\n* the 2011 [[Fukushima nuclear accident]]\n* the [[2013\u201314 United Kingdom winter floods]]\n* the [[2014 Ebola outbreak]]\n* the [[2015 Nepal earthquake]]\n* the [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]]\n* the potential catastrophic breach of [[Toddbrook reservoir]] in 2019\n* the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n== Members ==\n{{As of|2020|04}}, during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], members of the group included:<ref>{{Cite news|first=Ian |last=Sample|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/24/coronavirus-whos-who-on-secret-scientific-group-advising-uk-government-sage|title=Who's who on secret scientific group advising UK government?|date=2020-04-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n{{div col}}\n* Sir [[Patrick Vallance]]\n* Professor [[Chris Whitty]]\n* Professor [[Jonathan Van-Tam]]\n* Professor [[Stephen Powis]]\n* Professor [[Sharon Peacock]]\n* Professor [[Maria Zambon (scientist)|Maria Zambon]]\n* [[Meera Chand (Public Health England)|Meera Chand]]\n* Professor [[Charlotte Watts]]\n* Professor [[John Aston (statistician)|John Aston]]\n* Professor [[Angela McLean (mathematical biologist)|Angela McLean]]\n* Sir [[Ian Diamond]]\n* Professor [[Graham Medley]]\n* Professor [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Neil Ferguson]]\n* Professor [[John Edmunds (epidemiologist)|John Edmunds]]\n* [[James Rubin (psychologist)|James Rubin]]\n* Professor [[Brooke Rogers]]\n* Professor [[Peter Horby]]\n* Sir [[Jeremy Farrar]]\n* Professor [[Andrew Rambaut (molecular biologist)|Andrew Rambaut]]\n* [[Emma Reed (Department of Health and Social Care)|Emma Reed]]\n* Dr [[Edward Mullins]]\n* [[Dominic Cummings]]<ref name=\"guardian-sage-covid\">{{cite web |title=Revealed: Cummings is on secret scientific advisory group for Covid-19 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/24/revealed-dominic-cummings-on-secret-scientific-advisory-group-for-covid-19 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Warner (data scientist)|Ben Warner]]<ref name=\"guardian-sage-covid\"/>\n{{div col end}}\n\nVallance has written that SAGE includes scientists and experts from more than twenty separate institutions. SAGE also contains four expert groups which may each have as low as five and as many as over forty members.<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\"/>\n\nDominic Cummings was confirmed by [[Downing Street]] to have attended a 23 March meeting, but the government said Cummings was not a member of SAGE.<ref name=\"bbc-cummings\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Dominic Cummings attended meetings of key scientific group |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52421744 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[COBR]]\n* [[New and Emerging Respiratory Virus Threats Advisory Group]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/scientific-advisory-group-for-emergencies-sage}}\n\n{{Science and technology in the United Kingdom}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Science and technology in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Emergency management in the United Kingdom]]\n\n\n{{UK-gov-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SeekTheTruthUK", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Removed political bias)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_Advisory_Group_for_Emergencies"}
{"title_page": "AMC Ambassador", "text_new": "{{short description|Large-sized cars produced by American Motors Corporation}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name           = AMC Ambassador\n| image          = 1958 Ambassador 4-d hardtop wagon 1.JPG\n| caption        = 1958 Ambassador hardtop station wagon\n| interior image = 1967 Ambassador 990 4-d aqua pa-s.jpg\n| interiorcaption= 1967 Ambassador 990 sedan\n| predecessor    = [[Nash Ambassador]]\n| successor      = [[AMC Matador]]\n| aka            = {{unbulleted list | Ambassador by Rambler | American Motors Ambassador <ref name=\"1970_brochure\">{{cite web|url= http://www.lov2xlr8.no/brochures/misc/70_2.html |title=1970 American Motors Ambassador sales brochure |page=2 |publisher=lov2xlr8.no |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> | Rambler Ambassador | IKA Ambassador }}\n| manufacturer   = [[American Motors Corporation]] (AMC)\n| assembly       = {{unbulleted list | [[Kenosha Engine|Kenosha Factory]], [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]], [[United States|U.S.]] | [[Australia]] ([[Australian Motor Industries|AMI]])<ref name=\"Neasmith\">{{cite journal|first=Bruce |last=Neasmith |title=AMC Rambler in Australia Part 1 |journal=Restored Cars |issue=177 |date=July\u2013August 2006 |pages=39, 40, & 69}}</ref> | [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina]] ([[Industrias Kaiser Argentina|IKA]]) | [[Costa Rica]] (ECASA)<ref name=\"CostaRica\"/> | [[Monterrey, Mexico]] (Planta REO)}}\n| layout         = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel drive layout|FR layout]]\n| production     = 1957\u20131974\n| model_years    = 1958\u20131974\n| class          = [[Mid-size car|Mid-size]]/[[Full-size car|Full-size]]\n}}\n\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=horizontal |image1=OriAMClogo.png |width1=100 |image2 =1967 Ambassador 990 4-d aqua pa-t.jpg\n| width2=150 |footer=Ambassador emblem (1958\u20131961) and name badge (1967\u20131973) }}\n\nThe '''Ambassador''' is a [[Full-size car|full-size]] [[automobile]] manufactured and marketed by [[American Motors|American Motors Corporation]] (AMC) from 1957-1974 over eight generations, in two-and four-door sedan, two-door hardtop, station wagon and convertible body styles. \n\nWhen discontinued, ''Ambassador'' had been the longest continuously-used car nameplate, from 1927-1974,<ref>{{cite web |last=Fitzgerald |first=Craig |title=1957 Nash Ambassador Country Club |url= https://www.hemmings.com/blog/article/1957-nash-ambassador-country-club/ |publisher=Hemmings Classic Car |accessdate=20 August 2019 |date=November 2008 |quote=Nash had been utilizing the Ambassador model name continuously since 1927, and American Motors would continue to use it until 1974.}}</ref> in automotive history.<ref>{{cite web |title=1965 AMC Ambassador |url= https://www.conceptcarz.com/z28735/amc-ambassador.aspx |website=conceptcarz.com |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> The ''Ambassador'' nameplate was used variously as the '''Ambassador V-8 by Rambler''', '''Rambler Ambassador''', and finally '''AMC Ambassador.''' Previously, the nameplate [[Nash Ambassador|Ambassador]] applied to [[Nash Motors|Nash's]] full-size cars. The nameplate referred to a trim level between 1927 and 1931.\n\nAmbassadors were manufactured in [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]] as well as at AMC's [[Brampton Assembly]] in Brampton, Ontario from 1963 to 1966. [[Australian Motor Industries]] (AMI) assembled Ambassadors from [[knock-down kit]]s with [[right-hand drive]] from 1961 to 1963. The U.S. fifth generation Ambassadors were manufactured by [[Industrias Kaiser Argentina]] (IKA) in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina]] from 1965 to 1972, as well as assembled by ECASA in [[Costa Rica]] from 1965 to 1970. Planta REO assembled first-generation Ambassadors in Mexico at its Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n plant. Fifth and seventh generation Ambassadors were modified into custom stretch [[limousine]]s in Argentina and the U.S.\n\n== Development ==\nFollowing [[George W. Mason]]'s unexpected death in the fall of 1954, [[George W. Romney|George Romney]] (whom Mason had been grooming as his eventual successor), succeeded him as president and CEO of the newly formed American Motors. Romney recognized that to be successful in the postwar marketplace, an automobile manufacturer would have to be able to produce and sell cars in sufficient volume to [[Amortization (business)|amortize]] the high cost of tooling. Toward that end, he set out to increase AMC's market share with its Rambler models that were selling in [[market segment]] in which the domestic Big Three ([[General Motors]], [[Ford Motor Company]], and [[Chrysler]]) automakers did not yet compete. While development of a redesigned 1958 Nash Ambassador, based on a stretched and reskinned 1956 Rambler [[Coachwork|body]] was almost complete, AMC's [[Automotive design|designers]] were also working on a retrimmed [[Hudson Motor Car Company|Hudson]] equivalent, called '''Rebel''', to offer Hudson [[Car dealership|dealers]].\n\nHowever, as sales of the large-sized [[Nash Ambassador]] and [[Hudson Hornet]] models slowed, it became clear to Romney that consumer confidence in the historic Nash and Hudson nameplates had collapsed. Reluctantly, he decided that 1957 would be the end of both nameplates, and the company would concentrate on the new Rambler line, which was registered as a separate [[marque]] for 1957.\n\nThe market positioning meant that \"the AMC Ambassador was a car with no real competitors throughout most of the sixties\" because it was viewed as a luxury-type car and could be put against the higher end large-sized models from the domestic Big Three automakers, but the Ambassador was more of a midsized car.<ref>{{cite book |last=Flory, Jr. |first=J. \u201cKelly\u201d |title=American Cars, 1973-1980: Every Model, Year by Year |date=2012 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786456369 |page=2 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1DiNAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=the+AMC+Ambassador+was+a+car+with+no+real+competitors+throughout+most+of+the+sixtie |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== First generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image        = Rambler Ambassador (3893707660).jpg\n| caption      = 1958 Ambassador V8, Custom sedan\n| model_years  = 1958\u20131959\n| aka          = Ambassador V8 by Rambler\n| name         = First generation\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[hardtop]] sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 4-door [[hardtop]] station wagon }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|117|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| transmission = 3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| engine       = {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]]\n}}\n\n=== 1958 ===\n[[File:1958 Ambassador 4-d hardtop.jpg|thumb|right|1958 Ambassador Custom hardtop sedan with [[continental tire]] ]]\n[[File:1958 Ambassador 4-d hardtop wagon 2.JPG|thumb|right|Ambassador hardtop (pillarless) Cross Country station wagon]]\n\nAmerican Motors planned to produce a stretched a {{convert|117|in|0|adj=on}} [[wheelbase]] version of the Rambler platform for Nash dealers to be the new Nash Ambassador, and another for Hudson dealers. Shortly before committing to production of the new long-wheelbase versions of the Hudson and the Nash, CEO Romney decided to abandon the Nash and Hudson marques.\n\nDespite the fact that the Nash and Hudson names were canceled, work on the car itself continued, and American Motors introduced debuted in the fall of 1957, the 1958 \"Ambassador V-8 by Rambler\" on a {{convert|117|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase. Its features included a {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] (equipped with a 4-barrel [[carburetor]] and dual exhausts and rated at {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|360|lb\u00b7ft|N\u00b7m}} of torque) mated to a [[BorgWarner]] supplied 3-speed [[automatic transmission]] with push button gear selection.\n\nIn 1956, AMC first produced its own V8, a modern overhead valve V8 displacing {{convert|250|CID|L|1|abbr=on}}, with a forged steel crank shaft, which when equipped with a 4-barrel carburetor was rated at {{convert|215|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}. In 1957, AMC bored and stroked the 250 CID V8 to {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} displacement which when offered in the [[Rambler Rebel]] used solid lifters and Bendix electronic fuel injection was rated at {{convert|288|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn 1958, the Ambassador was equipped with a hydraulic lifter version of AMC's 327 CID V8 rated at {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}. Although AMC's 327 CID V8 shares its displacement with the Chevrolet small-block, AMC's 327 came out six years before Chevrolet first offered its 327 in 1962.\n\nThe Ambassador was available in a body style exclusive to its line, a pillarless [[hardtop]] '''Cross Country''' [[station wagon]]. The 1958 Ambassador was offered in a single high level trim level and came equipped with such luxury items as electric clock, twin front and rear ashtrays, Nash tradition \"deep coil\" spring suspension front and rear, split back reclining front seats that fold down into a bed, as well as upscale fabrics for the interior.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-24-25 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816085955/http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-24-25 |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nManagement had found that the public associated the Rambler name with small economy cars, and did not want the upscale nature of the new Ambassador to be so closely associated with Rambler's favorable, but economical image. Therefore, a decision was made that the larger Ambassador would be marketed as the '''Ambassador V-8 by Rambler''' in order to identify it with the Rambler name's burgeoning success, but to indicate an air of exclusivity by showing it to be a different kind of vehicle. However, the car wore \"Rambler Ambassador\" badges on its front fenders.\n\nThe 1958 Ambassador is a substantially longer car than the {{convert|108|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase [[Rambler Six]] and [[Rambler Rebel|Rebel V8]], although both lines shared the same basic body, styling, and visual cues. However, all of the Ambassador's extra {{convert|9|in|mm|spell=in}} of wheelbase (and, therefore, overall length) were added ahead of the cowl, meaning that the passenger compartment had the same volume as the smaller Ramblers. The Ambassadors came with plusher interior and exterior trims while the front end incorporated the Rebel \"V-Line\" grille from the prototype Hudson model. Through effective [[market segment]]ation, the Ambassador was [[Positioning (marketing)|positioned]] to compete with the larger models offered by other automakers.\n\nModel identification was located on the car's front fenders and deck lid. '''Super''' trim level Ambassadors featured painted side trim in a color that complemented the body color; '''Custom''' models featured a silver [[anodized aluminum]] panel on sedans and vinyl woodgrain decals on station wagons. Ambassador body styles included a four-door sedan and a [[hardtop]] sedan, a four-door pillared station wagon, and the aforementioned hardtop station wagon, a body style that first saw duty as an industry first in the 1956 [[Nash Rambler|Nash and Hudson Rambler]] line, on which all of the 1958 Ramblers were based.\n\nThe Ambassador had an excellent power-to-weight ratio for its time and provided spirited performance with [[0 to 60 mph]] (0 to 97&nbsp;km/h) times of less than 10-seconds, and low 17-second times through a quarter-mile (402&nbsp;m) [[dragstrip]]. It could be equipped with a [[limited slip differential]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-20-21 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816065829/http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-20-21 |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> as well as power brakes, power steering, power windows, and [[air conditioning]]. Numerous safety features (such as deep-dished steering wheels and padded dash boards) came standard, while lap [[seat belt]]s were optional.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-10-11 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816065347/http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-10-11 |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== 1959 ===\nFor 1959, the Ambassador received a revised grille, side trim, and redesigned rear door skins that swept into the [[Car tailfin|tailfin]]s instead of terminating at the C-pillar. [[Scotchlite]] reflectors were also added to the rear of the tailfins to increase visibility at night. Front and rear bumpers were over 20% thicker, and featured recessed center sections to protect [[license plates]]. Adjustable headrests were now available as an option for the front seats, an industry first. [[American Motors Corporation|AMC]] touted the added comfort the headrests provided, as well as their potential for reducing [[whiplash (medicine)|whiplash]] injuries in the event of a rear-end collision. Other changes included the activation of the starter through the neutral pushbutton (on automatic transmission equipped cars), and the addition of an optional \"Powr-Saver\" engine fan, which featured a [[Fan clutch|fluid-filled clutch]] for quieter high-speed operation.\n\nThe 1959 model year also saw the addition of an optional \"Air-Coil Ride\" [[air suspension]] system, utilizing air bags installed within the rear coil springs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1959_AMC/1959_Rambler_Wagons/1959-Rambler-Wagons-05 |title=1959 Rambler Wagons brochure |publisher=oldcarbrochures.org |accessdate=23 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522175749/http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1959_AMC/1959_Rambler_Wagons/1959-Rambler-Wagons-05 |archivedate=May 22, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref> An engine-driven [[Gas compressor|compressor]], reservoir, and ride-height control valve comprised the rest of the system, but as other automakers discovered, the troublesome nature of air-suspension outweighed its benefits. [[American Motors Corporation|AMC]] discontinued the unpopular option at the end of the model year.\n\nAmbassador sales improved considerably over 1958, reaching an output of 23,769; nearly half of which were '''Custom''' four-door sedans. Much rarer was the hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were built.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Second generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image        = 1960 AMC Rambler Ambassador sedan green NJ.jpg\n| caption      = 1960 Ambassador V8 by Rambler\n| model_years  = 1960\u20131961\n| aka          = Rambler Ambassador\n| name         = Second generation\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[hardtop]] sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 4-door [[hardtop]] station wagon }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|117|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]]\n}}\n\n=== 1960 ===\n1960 saw the Ambassador lineup totally reskinned, wearing new fenders, hood, deck lid, door skins, roofline, grille, taillights, bumpers, windshield, and backlight. Significant were the lower hood line, lower windshield cowl, simplified side trim, egg crate grill, while the tailfins were reduced in height and were canted to either side making for a modern and integrated appearance. The overall effect was rather fresh, as the new roof had a lower, lighter look, to complement the lower fins and grille.\n\nAll Ambassadors came equipped with the American Motors {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]], but for the first time it was available in two versions. First was the original {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}, {{convert|360|lb\u00b7ft|N\u00b7m|abbr=on}} of torque, performance version equipped with the 4-barrel carburetor and a 9.7:1 compression ratio, which required premium fuel, and a second economy version running on regular gasoline making {{convert|250|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}, {{convert|340|lb\u00b7ft|N\u00b7m|abbr=on}} of torque, equipped with a 2-barrel carburetor and an 8.7:1 compression ratio.\n\nAmbassadors now came with a unique compound curved windshield that cut into the roof. This improved visibility, did away with the \u201cknee knocker\u201d dogleg design of AMC's first generation wrap-around windshield, and resulted in an even stiffer unitized structure. The 1960 Ambassador had a low cowl which with the compound windshield afforded excellent visibility. The Ambassador was offered in higher end Custom or entry level Super trim levels. All 1960 Ambassadors came with a new instrument cluster under a padded cowl, as well as illuminated controls for lights, wipers, fan, and defrost functions. The 1960 Ambassadors continued with an enclosed drive shaft (torque tube) and coil springs at all four corners, although the suspension was revised resulting in better handling. The top-of-the-line Ambassador models came standard with individual \"airliner\" reclining front seats that now had even more luxurious fabrics than in previous years.\n\nThe Ambassador was the only American midsize, luxury high-performance car offered in 1960. The 1960 Ambassador came in 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]], 4-door pillarless hardtop, 4-door [[station wagon]], and a 4-door pillarless ([[hardtop]]) station wagon. Equipped with the 270&nbsp;horsepower 327&nbsp;cu&nbsp;in V8, and the Borg Warner pushbutton-operated 3-speed planetary gear and torque converter automatic transmission, the Ambassadors reached {{convert|60|mph|km/h|0}} in just over 9 seconds and passed the quarter-mile in 17 seconds.\n\n=== 1961 ===\n[[File:1961 Rambler Ambassador Custom blue-fl.jpg|thumb|left|1961 Rambler Ambassador Custom]]\n[[File:1961 AMC Rambler Ambassador 4-door pink rear.JPG|thumb|right|1961 Rambler Ambassador sedan]]\n\nThe 1961 Ambassador continued the previous year's {{convert|117|in|mm|0|adj=on}} basic [[Unit body|unitized platform]], but received an unusual new front-end styling that was overseen by AMC's in-house design department headed by [[Edmund E. Anderson|Edmund Anderson]]. The new face consisted of a trapezoid grille and headlights that floated in a body-colored panel, while the front fenders arched downward and forward of the leading edge of the hood. Different from anything else on the market, AMC's marketing department promoted the look as \"European.\" While the new look was meant to distinguish the Ambassador from the lower-priced Ramblers, it was neither a consumer success nor well received in the automotive press. Overall sales fell as the entire industry was experiencing a [[recession]]. The hardtop sedan and wagon models did not return for 1961.\n\nStandard was the {{convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 with a [[Manual transmission#Synchronized transmission|synchromesh manual transmission]]. Optional was the {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} \"power pack\" version with dual exhaust system featuring new ceramic-coated [[muffler]]s guaranteed for the life of the car.<ref>{{cite journal| title=Ambassador V-8 has changed appearance|journal=Popular Mechanics |volume=114 |issue=5 |page=90 |date=November 1960 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=9tsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA88-IA1&lpg=PA88-IA1&dq=Ambassador+shows+a+considerably+face+smaller+grille+curved-down+1961 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Third generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image        = 1962 Rambler Ambassador 2-door sedan Kenosha green-f.jpg\n| caption      = 1962 Rambler Ambassador\n| model_years  = 1962\n| aka          = Rambler Ambassador\n| name         = Third generation\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 2-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|108|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]]\n}}\n\n=== 1962 ===\nBy the 1962 model year, the Ambassador's chassis was in its fifth season on the market. And while Rambler sales had been good enough for third place in industry sales (behind [[Chevrolet]] and [[Ford]]), AMC's management was working on a revolutionary and somewhat costly design set to debut for the 1963 model year. In the meantime, American Motors needed to save money, and since the Ambassador's sales had fallen in 1961, it was decided that the car would be downsized for 1962 to share its body, windshield and {{convert|108|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase with its [[Rambler Classic|Classic]] line mate. Accordingly, the car was marketed as a '''Rambler Ambassador'''.\n\nThe 1962 Ambassador received a new front end that was very similar to the 1961\u201362 Classic's, but with a crosshatch design, recessed center section, and '''Ambassador''' lettering. New, rectangular taillights were seen at the ends of restyled rear fenders, which lost their fins entirely. Exterior trim was reshuffled, and a new 2-door pillared sedan debuted. A new '400' trim line was added at the top of the line, with Super and Custom models remaining. The Ambassador offered even more luxurious interiors, perhaps to make up for the fact that it now shared its wheelbase with the Rambler Classic. The 400 could be had with vinyl [[bucket seat]]s, headrests, and color coordinated shag carpets.\n\nThe only available engine was AMC's {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} OHV V8, in either the regular fuel, 2-barrel carburetor and 8.7:1 compression ratio, {{convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} version or the premium gasoline, 4-barrel version with 9.7:1 compression ratio, {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} version. The 1962 Ambassador came with a dual chamber [[master brake cylinder]] that separated the front and rear brakes so that in the event of the failure of one chamber some braking function would remain. This design was offered by only a few cars at that time. The 1962 models were equipped with \"Walker\" (brand) flow-through mufflers. The {{convert|108|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase 1962 Ambassador was lighter than its {{convert|117|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase predecessors and when equipped with the {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8, it was a spirited performer.\n\nThe 1962, {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 Ambassador for the first time used the same {{convert|108|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase structure as did the 1957 Rambler Rebel which was also equipped with an earlier solid lifter version of the AMC 327. The 1957 Rambler Rebel equipped with a 3-speed column mounted manual transmission, was the quickest 4-door sedan made in the United States, achieving {{convert|0|to|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} [[acceleration]] in just over 7 seconds, making it faster than the Hemi [[Chrysler 300 letter series|Chrysler 300C]], the [[DeSoto Adventurer]], the Dodge D500, the Plymouth Fury, and the Chevrolet fuel-injected 283.<ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide''|title=1957-1960 Rambler Rebel |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1957-1960-rambler-rebel1.htm |date=22 August 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The 1962 Ambassador was available with a 3-speed manual transmission and being basically the same vehicle, should also reach 60&nbsp;mph about as quickly as did the 1957 Rambler Rebel.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Fourth generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1963\u20131964\n| image        = File:1963 Rambler Ambassador 880 sedan gold-white K-f.jpg\n| caption      = 1963 Rambler Ambassador 880 Sedan\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 2-door [[coupe]] (1963) | 4-door sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 2-door [[hardtop]] (1964) }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|112|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|188.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width        = {{convert|71.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height       = {{convert|55.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]]\n| name         = Fourth generation\n}}\n\n=== 1963 ===\n[[File:1963 Rambler Ambassador 990 Sedan.jpg|thumb|left|1963 Rambler Ambassador 990 Sedan]]\nIn 1962 Romney left AMC to run for [[Governor of Michigan|Governor]] of [[Michigan]], a position that he won. The automaker's new president, [[Roy Abernethy]], who was responsible for the increasing sales under Romney, reacted to the mounting competition (in 1963 AMC built as many cars as they had in 1960, but overall total car sales had increased so much that it gave AMC only sixth place in production; the same output in 1960 had put them third) in a logical way: \"Let's get rid of this Romney image.\"<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964\">{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1963-1964 AMC/Rambler Ambassador & Classic, page 1|date=21 November 2007 |publisher=HowStuffWorks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1963-1964-amc-rambler-ambassador-classic.htm |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nA completely redesigned larger Rambler lineup appeared. The new cars continued the philosophy in building smaller cars than its larger \"Big Three\" competitors that also had a high degree of interchangeability in parts to keep tooling costs and production complexity to a minimum. The company, which pioneered \"styling continuity\", introduced all-new styling for the 1963 model year Ambassadors and claimed that these were \"functional changes .... not change just for the sake of change.\"<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\">{{cite journal|url= http://www.automotive-fleet.com/channel/operations/article/story/1962/10/styling-conformity-marks-the-1963s-last-year-s-functional-changes-expanded.aspx |title=Styling Conformity Marks the 1963s; Last Year's Functional Changes Expanded |date=October 1962 |journal=Automotive Fleet |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The Ambassadors featured a {{convert|4|in|mm|0|adj=on}} longer wheelbase, but were {{convert|1.2|in|mm|0|adj=on}} shorter due to reduced front and rear body overhangs, as well as a {{convert|3|in|mm|0|adj=on}} drop in overall height.\n\nDesigned by [[Richard A. Teague]], the 1963 Ambassador's shape was much tighter, cleaner, and smoother, with almost all of its parts interchangeable between it and the new Classic.<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964_1\">{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1963-1964 AMC/Rambler Ambassador & Classic, page 2 |date=21 November 2007 |publisher=HowStuffWorks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1963-1964-amc-rambler-ambassador-classic1.htm |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> All Ambassadors used unitized structure instead of the more rattl-prone, traditional body-on-frame construction which was still the industry standard.<ref name=\"DrivingGeorgeRomney\">{{cite magazine|url= http://www.motortrend.com/classic/features/1402_driving_george_romney_1964_rambler_classic_550/mercedes_benz_sedan.html |title=Driving George Romney's 1964 Rambler Classic 550 Two-Door Sedan - Michigan Governor George Romney Stayed Humble in his 1964 Rambler |first=Richard |last=Truesdell |date=14 February 2014 |magazine=Motor Trend |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> In 1963, AMC's new {{convert|112|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} wheelbase cars (Ambassadors and Classics) used a revolutionary method of unit construction which has since been almost universally adopted by automobile manufacturers. AMC Ambassador and Classics used outerpanels stamped from single sheet metal panels which included both door frames and outer rocker panels. This resulted in an extremely rigid and rattle-free structure, better fit of doors into frames, production cost savings and reduced noise, vibration and harshness. The \"uniside\" structure was superior to the conventional production methods in which multiple smaller pieces were welded together.<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://amcrc.com/aug05feature.html |last=Isbrandt |first=Ralph H. |title=Rambler Engineering |journal=Motor Trend |date=February 1963 |publisher=AMCRC |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> There were 30% fewer parts and the result was greater structural rigidity, quieter car operation, and an overall weight reduction of about {{convert|150|lb|kg|0|abbr=off}}.<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\"/>\n\nCurved side glass and [[push-button]] door handles were new and costly upgrades, but contributed to the new Rambler's handsome, elegant, and modern Mercedes-like bodyside styling, by adding greater elegance in detail. At the time, curved side glass was used only in much more expensive luxury cars, but increased interior room and visibility, as well as reducing wind noise and improved proportions and styling of the cars.<ref name=\"DrivingGeorgeRomney\"/> The Ambassador also featured a squared-off [[Ford Thunderbird|Thunderbird]]-type roofline.<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\"/> The front end featured a forward-thrusting upper and lower ends with a vertical bar \"electric shaver\" chrome grille insert. The Ambassador's grille was differentiated from the Classic's grille by its use of the Ambassador name in script in the small horizontal bar between the upper and lower grille sections. Round quad headlights were slightly recessed in chrome bezels mounted side-by-side within the grille at its outermost edges. Overall, the new Ambassadors were described by the staff of ''Automotive Fleet'' magazine as \"probably the finest looking cars ever produced by American Motors.\"<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\"/>\n\nAmbassadors once again came in 2-door [[coupe]], 4-door sedan, and 4-door wagon body styles, but new trim lines debuted. A \"Mercedes-like three-number model designation was developed\" with the '''800''' as the Ambassador's base line (replacing the previous year's Super model) for the police, taxi, and fleet market, a '''880''' model (in place of the Custom), and the up level '''990''' trim (replacing the previous 400 models).<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964_1\"/>\n\nThe 1963 Ambassadors were offered only with the {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8, in either {{convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} 2-barrel or {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} 4-barrel versions. AMC's smaller {{convert|287|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine was only offered in the Classic line. The automatic transmission was controlled by a steering column mounted lever, replacing the previous pushbutton system. Maintenance was reduced with service intervals of the front wheel bearings increased from {{convert|12000|-|25000|mi|km|0|abbr=off}}, the recommended engine oil change was at {{convert|4000|mi|km|0|abbr=off}}, and all Ambassador models included an [[Alternator (automotive)|alternator]] and an [[Voltage regulator|electronic voltage regulator]] as standard equipment.<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\"/>\n\nSales were brisk, and the redesign was billed a success, with ''[[Motor Trend]]'' Magazine bestowing '''[[Motor Trend Car of the Year|Car of the Year]]''' status on the entire 1963 Rambler line, including the Ambassador. The marketing formula for the Ambassador generated record sales for the model with buyers favoring more luxury and features as evidenced by the Ambassador 990 models outselling the 880 versions by nearly 2-to-1, while the base 800 model had a total of only 43 two-door sedans built.<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964_1\"/> The automaker did not have the resources of GM, Ford, and Chrysler, nor the sales volume to spread out its new model tooling and advertising costs over large production volumes; however, Richard Teague \"turned these economical cars into smooth, streamlined beauties with tons of options and V-8 pep.\"<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1963-1964 AMC/Rambler Ambassador & Classic Specifications |date=21 November 2007 |publisher=HowStuffWorks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1963-1964-amc-rambler-ambassador-classic2.htm |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 1964 ===\nThe 1964 model year introduced minor trim changes and new options. The \"electric-shaver\" grille on the 1963 model was replaced with a flush-mounted design, and the engine and transmission options were widened. A two-door [[hardtop]] body style called '''990-H''' was added for the first time since 1957. Base 880 and the 880 models were dropped from the line.\n\nThe 1964 Ambassadors featured the {{convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} 2-barrel {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 as standard, with the 4-barrel {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} version as optional. The automaker did not offer a 4-speed manual transmission to compete with the sporty mid-size V8 offerings from Ford or GM. Instead, AMC offered its innovative \u201cTwin-Stick\u201d manual transmission. The \"Twin stick\" option consisted a three-speed manual transmission, operated by one of the two console mounted \"sticks\" in conjunction with an overdrive unit that was controlled by the second \"stick\" in both 2nd and 3rd gears. This gave the driver the option of using five forward gears. One magazine noted the Twin-Stick, {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} Ambassador was heading for a sub 16-second quarter-mile when they blew up the clutch.\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:1964 Ambassador 2-d white f.jpg|1964 Rambler Ambassador\nFile:1964 Ambassador 2-d white r.jpg|1964 Rambler Ambassador\nFile:1964 Ambassador 2-d white i.jpg|1964 Rambler Ambassador interior with \"Twin-Stick\" transmission\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Fifth generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1965\u20131966\n| image        = 1965 AMC Ambassador black 2door-HT in NJ.JPG\n| caption      = 1965 Rambler Ambassador 990 2-door hardtop\n| aka          = Rambler Ambassador<br/>AMC Ambassador\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 2-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 2-door [[hardtop]] | 2-door [[convertible]] }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|116|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|200|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC Straight-6 engine|I6]] | {{convert|287|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] | {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 }}\n| name         = Fifth generation\n| transmission = {{unbulleted list | 3-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 3-speed with [[Overdrive (mechanics)|overdrive]] | \"Twin-Stick\" on console (1965) | 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] (1966) | 3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] | 3-speed \u201cShift-Command\u201d on console }}\n}}\n\n=== 1965 ===\n\nNo matter how much success the new Ramblers achieved in the marketplace, Roy Abernethy was not completely satisfied. Using the experience he gained as an outstanding salesman as a guide, Abernethy closely looked at the direction that American Motors' competition was going and decided that the company would be much more successful if its products competed more directly with the Big Three. He would achieve this by pushing all AMC vehicles further upmarket among the various [[market segment]]s, shaking off the company's economy car image, and offering vehicles once again in all three major American car size classes: compact, intermediate, and full-size. The American and Classic were strong competitors in the former two segments, so for the 1965 model year, he set his sights on turning the Ambassador into a proper full-size car by stretching the Classic's wheelbase and giving it much different styling. The general sizes of automobiles at that time were based on industry standard wheelbase lengths, rather than on the vehicle's interior and cargo space. The 1965 Ambassador represented a fundamental shift in corporate ideology, a shift away from primarily fuel-efficient vehicles, to bigger, faster, and potentially more profitable cars.<ref name=\"gunn65-66\">{{cite web |last=Gunn |first=Malcolm |title=Fine Lines: 1965\u20131966 AMC Ambassador |publisher=auto123 |url= http://www.auto123.com/en/car-reviews/used/fine-lines-1965-1966-amc-ambassador?model=AMBASSADOR&artid=66071&pg=1 |date=23 July 2008 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Ambassador rode the same platform as its 1963\u201364 forebears, the 1965 models looked all-new. American Motors' designer [[Richard A. Teague]] styled the 1965 Ambassador with panache and gave the car an overall integrated look.<ref name=\"Vance65-66\">{{cite web |last=Vance |first=Bill |title=Motoring Memories: AMC Ambassador, 1965\u20131966 |publisher=Autos Canada |url= http://www.autos.ca/classic-cars/motoring-memories-amc-ambassador-1965-1966 |date=17 March 2006 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> ''[[Motor Trend]]'' magazine agreed, calling it a \"strikingly handsome automobile.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' | title=Design of the 1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador2.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Built on a {{convert|116|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase {{convert|4|in|mm|spell=in}} longer than the Classic, Teague extended the beltline level from the stacked quad headlights to the vertical taillights. The new Ambassadors were as attractive as anything built by AMC's Detroit-based competitors, and with a list price of around $3,000, few could quibble about the cost of ownership.<ref name=\"gunn65-66\"/> New disc brakes with a power brakes were optional.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/AMC/1965_AMC/1965_Rambler_Ambassador_Brochure/1965%20Rambler%20Ambassador-12.html|title=1965 Rambler Ambassador brochure |publisher=Oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Ambassador received longer, squared-off rear fenders with vertical wrap-around taillights, taller [[decklid]], squared off rear bumper mounted low, and squarer rear wheel arches. At the front, the Ambassador again sparked minor controversy with its new vertically stacked quad headlights, which were slightly recessed in their bezels, as they flanked an all-new horizontal bar grille. This new wall-to-wall grille projected forward, horizontally, in the center, to create an effect somewhat opposite to 1963's grille treatment. The front end design provided a bold, rugged appearance.<ref name=\"Vance65-66\"/>\n\nOnce again, the Ambassador\u2019s entire extra wheelbase was ahead of the cowl, meaning that interior volume was the same as the intermediate-sized Classic. Another new body style debuted in the Ambassador lineup for 1965: an attractive new convertible offered as part of the 990 series. This was the first time a [[convertible (car)|convertible]] was offered in the Ambassador line since 1948. All Ambassador body styles (except the 990-H coupe) offered seating for six passengers, with coupes and convertibles having the option of buckets seats with center console and floor shifter. The Ambassador 990-H was an up-scale two-door hardtop model, available only in 5-passenger form.\n[[File:1965 Ambassador 990 convertible yellow pb-rr.jpg|thumb|left|1965 Ambassador 990 convertible]]\nAmbassadors also saw an expanded list of trim lines, convenience options, and engine choices. The 990 and 990-H models were back, while 880 models were the new economy leaders in the 1965 Ambassador line, but even the $2,512 price for the two-door sedan was not attractive compared to the models with better trim, buckets seats, and special interiors.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador: Creating the early Rambler Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador1.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Ambassadors came standard with AMC's new {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC Straight-6 engine|Inline-6 engine]], which was the first time since 1956 that an Ambassador was available with six cylinders. Far more popular in the Ambassador, however, were the two time-tested {{convert|287|and|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine]]s.<ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador: The 1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador's amenities |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url = http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador3.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Motors' management decided that the Ambassador could once again accept a standard six-cylinder engine, since its full-size competitors (e. g. [[Chevrolet|Bel Air]] and [[Chevrolet Impala|Impala]], Ford Custom 500 and [[Ford Galaxie|Galaxie]], as well as [[Plymouth Fury]]) came with six-cylinder engines as standard equipment. They therefore appealed to a wider range of customers than the Ambassador was getting. Also, since the Classic was now smaller and styled differently, the Ambassador [[Straight-6|six-cylinder]] would not threaten to cannibalize Classic 6 sales, which were the company's sales volume leaders. The changes were on target as sales of the repositioned Ambassador more than tripled.\n\n''Motor Trend'' magazine tested an Ambassador convertible with a Twin-Stick overdrive transmission and found it commendably economical, averaging {{convert|16.4|mpgus|L/100 km mpgimp|abbr=on}} over {{convert|1000|mi}} run, and noting that ... \"Traveling comfort was the Ambassador's biggest selling point, along with its exceptionally powerful [[Bendix Corporation|Bendix]] duo-servo drum brakes ...With the thin bucket seats that recline, driver and passengers can enjoy a high degree of riding comfort... Many passers-by commented on the car's good looks... Our summary: a nice, comfortable, quiet, well built family automobile that rather neglects the performance market.\"<ref name=page4>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador4.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n=== 1966 ===\n[[File:1966 AMC Ambassador DPL NJ-show.jpg|thumb|1966 hardtops featured a formal roof design \u2013 DPL model]]\n[[File:1966 AMC Ambassador red convertible in MD.JPG|thumb|1966 AMC Ambassador 990 convertible]]\n[[File:1966 Ambassador 990 wagon azrr.jpg|thumb|1966 Ambassador 990 Cross Country wagon]]\n\nFor 1966, minor changes greeted the Ambassador range. The V-shaped horizontal louver spanned unbroken between the headlamps and the effect was continued with twin rectangular trim pieces attached to the side of the front fenders at their leading edges by the headlamps. The effect was repeated in the new vertical wraparound taillamps with the top-line models receiving a twin set of horizontal ribbed moldings across the back of the trunk lid that simulated the look of the front grille. Hardtop coupes received a redesigned roofline that was angular in appearance with an angle cut rear side windows and rectangular rear window. The backlight no longer curved and wrapped slightly around the C-pillars. The changes made for a more \"formal\" [[notchback]] look that was popular at the time.\n\nStation wagons also received a new roof (that did not have as pronounced dip over the rear cargo area) as well as a redesigned tailgate and optional [[Woodie (car body style)#Simulated woodgrain|simulated woodgrain]] exterior side panels. Available with two-rows of seats with a standard bottom hinged tailgate with electric, fully retracting rear window or with an optional rear-facing third row that featured a left side hinged rear door, with a regular exterior door handle on the right side. All station wagons carried a '''Cross Country''' badge.\n\nThe 880 served as the base model line. The two-door sedan was the price leader at $2,404, but finished with the least sales for the model year.<ref name=\"stuff-performance\">{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador Performance Statistics |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador5.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The more popular and better trimmed 990 models were available in sedan, wagon, hardtop, and convertible versions.<ref name=\"stuff-performance\"/> Options included a vinyl roof, wire wheel covers, AM/FM radio, adjustable steering wheel, and cruise control. A new luxury '''DPL''' (short for \"Diplomat\"<ref name=page4/>) two-door hardtop debuted at the top of the range.\n\nThe DPL included special lower body side trim, numerous standard convenience items such as reclining [[bucket seat]]s upholstered in brocade fabrics or optional vinyl. An optional interior trim featured [[houndstooth]] fabric and included two throw pillows. The DPL model was aimed to compete with the new, more upscale trimmed [[Plymouth Fury|Plymouth VIP]], [[Ford LTD (North America)|Ford LTD]], [[Chevrolet Caprice]] and [[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]].<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=4SUDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=Caprice+LTD+VIP+DPL |page=79 |title=The 1966 cars |journal=Popular Science |first=Jan P. |last=Norbye |date=October 1965 |volume=187 |issue=4 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} I6, as well as the {{convert|287|and|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8s remained in the line, but transmission selections now included a new console mounted four-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]. Most Ambassadors continued to be ordered with [[automatic transmission]]s.\n\n''Motor Trend'' magazine tested a 1966 DPL equipped with a 327 engine that \"definitely has snap we hadn't felt before\" and even with an automatic transmission experienced \"healthy wheelspin from both rear wheels [because of the Twin-Grip limited slip differential]... Subtle changes in this year's suspension, which include longer shocks and different springs, have a pronounced effect on the way the car feels and handles. Most welcome is the improved steering response. The car has a new feet-on-the-ground feeling, and body lean seems to have been reduced. The ride remains very good... As before, the interior's the outstanding feature of the Ambassador. Its quality is such that other luxury cars, even higher priced ones, could well imitate it...\"<ref name=page4/>\n\nPerhaps the biggest change, however, was that the Ambassador lost its historic Rambler nameplate, as the car was now marketed as the \"American Motors Ambassador\" or \"AMC Ambassador\". Abernethy was again responsible for this marketing move, as he attempted to move the stylish new Ambassador even further upmarket. To him, that meant that the Rambler name, and its economy car image would be eschewed to give the car a clean slate in a market that was turning away from economy and toward V8 performance. The evidence suggests that Abernethy was on the right track with moving the Ambassador upscale to compete with other manufacturers' luxury models as sales of the AMC's flagship jumped from 18,647 in 1964 to over 64,000 in 1965, and then in 1966 they went to more than 71,000.<ref name=\"Vance65-66\"/> Although the Ambassador accounted for a mere fraction of total passenger car sales in the U.S., it was an important step in bringing the AMC's products in line with what the consumer of the day wanted.<ref name=\"gunn65-66\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Sixth generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1967\u20131968\n| image        = 1967 Ambassador DPL conv top-up-winter-WV.jpg\n| caption      = 1967 AMC Ambassador DPL convertible\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 2-door [[sedan (automobile)]] (1967 only) | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 2-door [[hardtop]] [[coup\u00e9|coupe]] | 2-door [[convertible]] (1967 only) }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|118|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|202.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC Straight-6 engine|I6]] | {{convert|290|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] | {{convert|343|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 }}\n| transmission = {{unbulleted list | 3-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 3-speed with [[Overdrive (mechanics)|overdrive]] | 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 3-speed [[BorgWarner]] [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] | 3-speed \u201cShift-Command\u201d on center floor console }}\n| name         = Sixth generation\n}}\n\n=== 1967 ===\nAmerican Motors introduced a completely restyled longer, lower, and wider Ambassador for the 1967 model year, now riding on a {{convert|118|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase, or {{convert|2|in|mm|spell=in}} longer than before. The Ambassador's platform was {{convert|4|in|mm|spell=in}} longer than the new [[AMC Rebel|Rambler Rebel's]] {{convert|114|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase. The Ambassador was positioned in the standard-size category, against traditional big cars such as [[Ford Galaxie]], [[Chevrolet Impala]], and [[Plymouth Fury]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador1.htm|title=1967\u20131968 AMC Ambassador|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |date=11 October 2007 |publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The convertible was offered again\u2014this time in DPL trim\u2014for 1967; but it would be the final year with only 1,260 built. It featured an all new \"split stack\" folding mechanism with concealed side rails that did not intrude into the backseat area, thus offering room for three adult passengers in the rear.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967_AMC_Data_Book/1967-AMC-Data-Book-048 |title=1967 AMC Data Book |page=48 |publisher=oldcarbrochures.org |accessdate=23 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140427010415/http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967_AMC_Data_Book/1967-AMC-Data-Book-048 |archivedate=April 27, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe car once again looked completely new, with a more rounded appearance that sported sweeping rooflines, \"[[Coke bottle styling|coke-bottle]]\" fenders, greater glass area, and a recessed grille that bowed forward less than that of the 1965\u201366 models. Taillights were wider, rectangular, and divided by one central vertical bar. ''Motor Trend'' magazine described the all-new styling of the new Ambassador as \u201cattractive\u201d and \u201cmore graceful and easier on the eye in \u201967.\u201d<ref name=\"full\">{{cite journal |title=Full-Size American Motors |journal=Motor Trend |date=November 1966 |page=90 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:1967 Ambassador 990 4-d aqua pa-i.jpg|thumb|left|1967 Ambassador 990 standard interior]]\n[[File:1967 AMC Ambassador DPL yellow.JPG|thumb|left|1967 Ambassador DPL hardtop with satin chrome trim]]\nThe 880 two-door sedans featured the identical roofline as the [[hardtop]]s, but had slim [[Pillar (car)|B-pillars]] that gave them a more open-air coupe appearance and were marketed as \"Sports Sedans.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=1967 Ambassador brochure |url= http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967%20Ambassador%20Brochure/image11.html |website=Old Car Brochures |accessdate=4 November 2019 |page=11}}</ref> The 880 was also available in 4-door sedan and station wagon version, but more popular were the better equipped and more upscale 990 models in 4-door sedan, station wagon, and 2-door hardtop body styles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Car of the Week: 1967 AMC Ambassador convertible |url=https://www.oldcarsweekly.com/collector-cars/60s-cars/car-of-the-week-1967-amc-ambassador-convertible |publisher=Old Cars Weekly |date=21 December 2010 |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> Adding more elegance to DPL two-door hardtops and convertibles was an optional was a \"Satin-Chrome\" finish (paint code P-42) for the lower body side replacing the standard full-length stainless steel rocker moldings. A black or white vinyl cover was optional on 990 and DPL sedans and hardtops. The 990 '''Cross Country''' station wagons were available with [[3M]]'s \"dinoc\" simulated wood-grain body side panels trimmed in a slim stainless steel frame.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967_AMC_Data_Book/1967-AMC-Data-Book-073 |title=1967 AMC Data Book |page=73 |publisher=oldcarbrochures.org |accessdate=23 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114344/http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967_AMC_Data_Book/1967-AMC-Data-Book-073 |archivedate=August 26, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[fastback]] [[AMC Marlin|Marlin]] two-door [[hardtop]] that was previously built on the Rambler Classic platform in 1965 and 1966, was continued for 1967, but was now based on the larger Ambassador platform.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=McCourt |first=Mark J. |title=1967 AMC Marlin |url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/article/1967-amc-marlin-2/ |magazine=Hemmings Motor News |date=July 2013 |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> It featured the Ambassador's front end, longer hood, and luxury appointments with an even longer fastback roofline than the previous version.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strohl |first1=Daniel |title=Trawling for Success \u2013 1967 AMC Marlin |url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/article/trawling-for-success-1967-amc-marlin/ |publisher=Hemmings Classic Car |date=August 2007 |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe full-sized Ambassador featured a lengthy list of standard features and options.<ref>{{cite web |last=Litwin |first=Matthew |title=1967 AMC Ambassador DPL |url= https://www.hemmings.com/blog/article/1967-amc-ambassador-dpl/ |website=www.hemmings.com |publisher=Hemmings Motor News |date=January 2008 |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> The interiors \"rival more expensive cars for luxury and quality, yet are durable enough to take years of normal wear.\"<ref name=\"full\" /> The premium materials and fittings included wood-grain trim, and even an optional \"Custom\" package with special upholstery and two matching pillows. Ambassador DPL hardtops included reclining [[bucket seat]]s with a center armrest between them (with a center cushion for a third occupant or a floor console with gear selector), as well as a foldaway center armrest for the rear seat. The new safety-oriented instrument panel grouped all gauges and controls in front of the driver, with the rest of the [[dashboard]] pushed forward and away from the passengers. Focusing on safety, there were now no protruding knobs, the steering column was designed to collapse under impact, and the steering wheel was smaller than previous Ambassadors.<ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1967 AMC Ambassador Styling |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador2.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe long-lived \"GEN-1\" family of [[AMC V8 engine]]s was replaced by an all-new line of {{convert|290|and|343|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} engines that debuted for 1966 in the [[Rambler American]]. These V8s were an all-new design featuring thin-wall-casting block, heads, and manifold.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sessler |first=Peter C. |title=Ultimate American V-8 Engine Data Book, 2nd Edition |date=2010 |publisher=MotorBooks International |isbn=9781610592321 |page=227 |edition=Second |chapter-url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eT7LT69STO0C&pg=PA227 |accessdate=4 November 2019 |chapter=24}}</ref> With a 4-barrel [[carburetor]] and dual exhaust, the 343&nbsp;V8 produced {{convert|280|bhp|abbr=on}} at 4800 rpm and {{convert|365|lb.ft|N\u00b7m|0}} of torque at 3000 rpm. The old [[torque tube]] design was eliminated by a new four-link, trailing-arm rear suspension system providing a more comfortable [[coil spring]] ride.<ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' | title=1967 AMC Ambassador Engineering |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador3.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Motors promoted the new 1967 Ambassador as an \"uncompromising automobile with the [[red carpet]] ride\" in print advertisements,<ref>{{cite journal|author=American Motors|title=Ambassador, The Red Carpet Ride|journal=Life|date=February 10, 1967|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eFYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA57&dq=uncompromising+automobile+with+the+red+carpet+ride&q |page=57 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> as well as in an innovative TV commercial.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ross |first=Wallace A. |title=Best TV Commercials of the Year, Volume 2 |publisher=Hastings House |year=1967 |page=13 }}</ref> Unfortunately, sales of the redesigned models were disappointing, due to customer confusion caused by the entire company's abrupt upmarket push, which seemed uncomfortably \"me too\" to the traditional domestic [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three]]'s customers, and they also alienated American Motors' loyal buyer base. Abernethy's ideas of entering new markets were not working.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' | title=1967\u20131968 AMC Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> These strategy changes resulted in a new round of financial problems for American Motors. Because of this, Abernathy was released from AMC by its board of directors later that year, and was replaced by William V. Luneberg and [[Roy D. Chapin, Jr.]]\n\n=== 1968 ===\n[[File:1968 Ambassador SST 4-d green pa-s.jpg|thumb|right|1968 AMC Ambassador SST sedan]]\n[[File:1968 AMC Ambassador yellow 2-door.jpg|thumb|right|1968 AMC Ambassador hardtop coupel]]\n\nFor the 1968 model year, a new SST trim line was placed above the now mid-line DPL trim for the Ambassador. American Motors was a pioneer in the field of [[air conditioning]] through its Kelvinator refrigerator division, and AMC's marketing chief Bill McNealy wanted to make the Ambassador stand out in a crowded market segment and decided to add greater distinction to the Ambassador line by making the [[Weather Eye#All-Weather Eye|All Weather]] [[Automobile air conditioning|A/C system]] as standard equipment.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=_Vb0AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=marketing+chief+Bill+McNealy+was+searching+for+a+way+to+make+Ambassador+stand+out+in+a+crowded+market |page=99 |title=American Motors Corporation: the rise and fall of America's last independent automaker |first=Patrick R. |last=Foster |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2013 |accessdate=3 November 2014|isbn=9781610588584 }}</ref> This was the first time any volume car manufacturer had done so, something that even [[Cadillac]] and [[Lincoln (automobile)|Lincoln]] had not offered on their luxury cars \u2013 although some of them were priced at more than twice as much as Ambassador. While all Ambassadors came with air conditioning as standard, consumers could order the car without air as a \"delete option\" and decrease the price by $218.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=VAcEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25&dq=1968+Ambassador+air+conditioning+standard |page=25 |title=The 1968 cars |journal=Changing Times - Kiplinger's Personal Finance |date=December 1967 |volume=21 |issue=12 |accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> As AMC pointed out in their advertising campaign for the Ambassador, the only other major automaker that offered air conditioning as standard equipment in 1968 was [[Rolls-Royce (car)|Rolls-Royce]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z0ReBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA221&lpg=PA221&dq=1968,+American+Motors+rocked+the+industry+by+offering+air+conditioning+as+standard+equipment+on+its+Ambassador |page=221 |title=Cool: how air conditioning changed everything |first=Salvatore |last=Basile |publisher=Fordham University Press |year=2014 |isbn=9780823261765 |quote= 1968, American Motors rocked the industry by offering air conditioning as standard equipment on its Ambassador... |accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nDue to slow sales, both the convertible and the pillared coupe models were dropped from the line, leaving the 990 hardtop coupe and sedan, DPL hardtop coupe, sedan, and wagon, and new '''SST''' hardtop coupe and sedan in the Ambassador line. The [[Personal luxury car|personal luxury]] fastback Marlin was also discontinued to make way for the smaller new [[AMC Javelin]] in the [[pony car]] segment. The top-of-the line 1968 Ambassador SST version was \"especially appealing\" and \"a very luxurious package\" with standard V8 power, air conditioning, expensive upholstery, individual reclining front seats, wood-look interior trim, upgraded exterior trim, as well as numerous conveniences such as an electric clock and a headlights-on buzzer.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1968 AMC Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador5.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:1968 AMC Ambassador DPL station wagon FL-fl.jpg|thumb|left|1968 AMC Ambassador DPL wagon]]\nStyling changes were minor. Taillights were now recessed in body-color bezels that were divided by a single central horizontal bar. Front headlight bezels were now made of nylon and similarly body colored.<ref name=\"ps-october67\">{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1SoDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA118&lpg=PA118&dq=What's+new+at+American+Motors+outside+door+handles |page=118 |title=What's new at American Motors |journal=Popular Science |date=October 1967 |volume=191 |issue=4 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> A new injection molded ABS plastic grille was dominated by a horizontal bar that extended forward in the center from the sides, while its outline had squared off edges that wrapped forward into the inner headlight extensions.<ref name=\"ps-october67\"/> Fender-mounted marker lights were added at the front and rear as standard equipment, as the U.S. [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA) regulations mandated their application (along with seat belts beginning January 1, 1968) to all passenger cars sold in the United States for 1968.\n\nHowever, AMC's most enduring styling feature debuted on the Ambassador for 1968, as flush-mounted paddle-style door handles replaced the former push-button units on all American Motors cars, save the [[Rambler American]].<ref name=\"ps-october67\"/> The practical and \"disarmingly simple design\" predated safety-related mandates and industry norms.<ref name=\"paddling\">{{cite magazine|url= http://www.hemmings.com/hmn/stories/2010/07/01/hmn_feature21.html |title=Paddling for Life Itself - a timeless American Motors part that outlasted its maker |magazine=Hemmings Motor News |date=July 2010 |first=Jim |last=Donnelly |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The interior locking was no longer by the traditional windowsill pushbutton, but a lever set into the armrest.<ref name=\"paddling\"/>\n\nFront-wheel alignment was made easier with and with greater accuracy by moving the camber adjustment from the upper to the lower control arm on the [[double wishbone suspension]], and the [[caster angle]] adjustments also moved from the upper control arm to the drag strut. At midyear, AMC's new top engine, the [[AMC AMX|AMX]] {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} {{convert|315|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] became an option in the Ambassador line, bringing the total engine options up to four.\n\nIn June 1967, American Motors started a new advertising campaign created by [[Mary Wells Lawrence]] of Wells, Rich, and Greene marketing agency. The US$12 million AMC account was high-profile assignment and helped established the agency as innovative and daring in its approach.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Irreverence at American | journal=Time |date=22 November 1967 |url= http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,837337,00.html |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The new advertising violated the convention of not attacking the competition, and AMC's campaigns became highly controversial.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Belliveau |first=Nancy | title=Sledge-hammer Sell |journal=Life |date=27 October 1967 |pages=104\u2013106 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SEkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA101&dq=AMC+Wells,+Rich,+and+Greene |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The publicity worked with AMC's total retail sales improving 13% for the fiscal year, but 1968 Ambassador numbers were slightly down.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1967\u20131968 AMC Ambassador Specifications |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador6.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Seventh generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1969\u20131973\n| image        = 1969 AMC Ambassador SST sedan green-e.jpg\n| caption      = 1969 AMC Ambassador SST 4-door sedan\n| class        = [[Full-size car|Full-size]]\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 2-door hardtop [[coupe]] }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|122|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|206.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} (1969) | {{convert|208|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} (1970) | {{convert|210.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} (1971\u201372) | {{convert|212.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} (1973) }}\n| engine       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Straight-six engine|I6]] | {{convert|258|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} I6 | {{convert|290|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] | {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|343|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 }}\n| name         = Seventh generation\n| aka          = {{unbulleted list | American Motors Ambassador <ref name=\"1970_brochure\"/> | Rambler Ambassador <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/American-Motors-Rambler-Rebel-Ambassador-1970-UK-Market-Sales-Brochure-/181058740695?pt%3DUK_CarParts_Vehicles_Manuals_Litterature_ET%26hash%3Ditem2a27f121d7 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6SNNzBa3m?url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/American-Motors-Rambler-Rebel-Ambassador-1970-UK-Market-Sales-Brochure-/181058740695?pt=UK_CarParts_Vehicles_Manuals_Litterature_ET&hash=item2a27f121d7 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 6, 2014 |title=Rambler Rebel & Ambassador 1970 UK Market Sales Brochure |publisher=ebay.com |accessdate=15 September 2014 }}</ref> }}\n}}\n\n=== 1969 ===\n[[File:AMC Ambassador Hardtop ca 1969 in Vlaams-Brabant.JPG|thumb|left|1969 Ambassador hardtop in Belgium]]\n[[File:1969 AMC Ambassador SST sedan green-i.jpg|thumb|left|1969 Ambassador sedan standard interior]]\n\nIn 1969, the Ambassador received a major restyling, with a {{convert|4|in|0|adj=on}} gain in overall length and wheelbase. The {{convert|122|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase was accompanied by an increase in front and rear track from {{convert|58.5|to|60|in|mm|0|}}.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=G9QDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=Styling+changes+fore+and+aft+mark+the+new+Ambassador |pages=99 & 101 |title=Family cars: the '69 cars |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=October 1968 |volume=130 |issue=4 |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The front end appearance was revised with new quad headlight clusters mounted horizontally in a new molded plastic grille. The grille itself was blackout with a chrome horizontal bar that connected the headlight clusters. The hood was redesigned to accommodate the grille's raised center portion, and it faintly recalled [[Packard|Packard's]] classic grille/hood combination. [[Richard A. Teague]], AMC's Vice President of Styling, had worked at the luxury car manufacturer before joining AMC. Parking lights were rectangular and mounted horizontally in recessed wells in the front bumper, just beneath each set of headlights. The entire front fascia leaned forward slightly to lend an air of forward motion to the car's appearance.\n\nAt the rear, ribbed rectangular taillights were mounted inboard the Ambassadors rearward-thrusting rear fenders. Square ribbed marker lights of similar height were mounted at the trailing edge of each fender side. The deck lid had a slightly higher lift over. The base and DPL models had no decorative panel connecting the taillights while the top-line SST versions featured a panel painted red to match the taillights. Station wagons saw vertical wraparound taillights replacing the previous \"hooded\" units, which were not visible from the side. The 1969 AMC Ambassador was a smooth, powerful, well-proportioned sedan that did not look like anything else on the road.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1967, 1968, 1969 AMC Ambassador Specifications \u2013 page 2 |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1969-amc-ambassador2.htm |date=26 November 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe interiors were upgraded and a new deeply hooded dashboard clustered instruments and controls in front of the driver. There was an increased emphasis on luxury-type trim and features. The base model two-door hardtop was dropped for 1969.\n\nThe 1969 Ambassador stressed luxury, with the marketing tagline developed by [[Mary Wells Lawrence]] at the Wells Rich Greene agency, tying the car's value, \"It will remind you of the days when money really bought something.\"<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CyBFAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA102&dq=1969+Ambassador+It+will+remind+you+of+the+days+when+money+really+bought+something |page=102 |title=American Motors Corporation: The Rise and Fall of America's Last Independent |first=Patrick R. |last=Foster |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2013 |isbn=9780760344255 |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The combination of rich velour upholstery, individually adjustable reclining seats, standard air conditioning, and the longer wheelbase were highlighted in advertisements with Ambassador's posh\"[[limousine]]\" ride at an economical price. One aspect of this new advertising theme included many AMC dealers inviting prospective customers to call and request a \"demonstration ride\", in which a uniformed chauffeur would arrive at the prospect's home and drive them around in an Ambassador SST sedan. AMC's efforts worked, and Ambassador sales shot up again.\n\n[[File:1969 AMC Ambassador limousine in Wisconsin sideR.JPG|thumb|left|1969 Ambassador Royale Stretch Limo by Armbruster/Stageway. Car wears Ambassador SST trim.]]\nNot only did AMC promote the 1969 Ambassador as having a \"limousine\" ride and deluxe appointments, but Chicago [[Vehicle leasing|auto leasing]] executive, Robert Estes, had the Armbruster/Stageway Company<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.coachbuilt.com/bui/a/armbruster/armbruster.htm |last=Theobald |first=Mark|title=Armbruster & Co.; Armbruster / Stageway |publisher=Coachbuilt.com |year=2004 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> convert Ambassadors into real {{convert|24|ft|m|adj=on}} limousines riding on a {{convert|158|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase. Known as the '''Royale Stretch Limo''', one was owned by the State of [[Wisconsin]] as the official vehicle for Governor [[Warren Knowles]]. The conversions were unusual in that they did not keep the stock rear doors\u2014as is typical in most limos. The back doors were welded shut and the Ambassadors were lengthened by inserting a section just behind the original [[Pillar (car)|B-pillar]] that had an entirely new central door in this center making a large opening for entry and egress. {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on|spell=In}} steel \"I-beams\" bridge the expanse created by stretch. Power comes from the \"[[AMC AMX|AMX]]\" {{convert|315|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine backed with the BorgWarner automatic transmission and a \"Twin-Grip\" [[limited-slip differential]] with 3.15 gears.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Strohl |first=Daniel |title=1969 AMC Ambassador Limousine |journal=Hemmings Classic Car |url= http://www.hemmings.com/hcc/stories/2008/10/01/hmn_feature15.html |date=October 2008 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom their experience with supplying the U.S Postal Service with over 3700 right-hand drive Ambassadors in 1968, American Motors thereafter exported fully assembled RHD Ambassadors from the United States to right-hand drive foreign markets, including the United Kingdom, Australia, and New Zealand.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== 1970 ===\n[[File:1970 AMC Ambassador SST hardtop yellow-black K-s.jpg|thumb|1970 Ambassador SST 2-door hardtop]]\nFor the 1970 model year, the rear half of Ambassador hardtop coupes and sedans was treated to an overhaul that was also shared by the intermediate 1970 [[AMC Rebel]]. On hardtop coupes, this restyling resulted in a sloping roofline that saw upswept reverse-angle quarter windows. The belt line kicked up at the point the hardtop's rear windows swept upward, and tapered back to the fender end, meeting a new loop-type rear bumper.\n\nOn sedans, the roof line showed a slimmer C-pillar, squared-off rear door windows, and met a belt line that kicked up beneath the trailing edge of each rear door window. The belt line tapered back to the same rear fascia as the hardtop coupe's. This rear fascia contained a new ribbed taillight lens that stretched wall-to-wall and included twin square white reverse light lenses in its center.\n\nStation wagons received no change to their rooflines, doors, and rear fascias. However, all Ambassadors received a new extruded aluminum grille at the front, featuring several widely spaced bright horizontal bars with one wide, body colored horizontal grille bar extending to each headlight cluster. The {{convert|290|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 was replaced for 1970 by a new {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine. This {{convert|210|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 4400 rpm and {{convert|305|lb.ft|N\u00b7m|0}} of torque at 2800 rpm was the standard engine on all DPL and SST models. The {{convert|343|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 was also supplanted by a {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} engine available in either 2-barrel, regular gasoline, or high-output, 4-barrel, premium fuel versions. The 4-barrel \"AMX\" {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine was optional, producing {{convert|325|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 3200 rpm and {{convert|420|lb.ft|N\u00b7m|0}} of torque at 3200 rpm.\n\n=== 1971 ===\n[[File:1971 AMC Ambassador 2-door hardtop coupe.JPG|thumb|left|1971 Ambassador hardtop with TurboCast II wheels from 1979\u201383]]\n[[File:1971 AMC Ambassador station wagon red with woodgrain side panels.JPG|thumb|left|1971 Ambassador station wagon]]\n\nFollowing the previous year's redesign, the 1971 Ambassadors received only minor changes and improvements. The marketing tag line for the year was the [[Underdog (competition)|underdog]] asking, \"If you had to compete with GM, Ford and Chrysler, what would you do?\"\u2014that was answered by AMC including more features, advantages, and benefits for buyers of its cars compared to the models from its much larger competitors. This was reflected by shuffling the Ambassador models for 1971 and by including more equipment in the standard feature list. The previously nameless base models were dropped, as the sedan-only DPL trim line was relegated to base model status, and a new top-line '''Brougham''' trim line was added above mid-line SST models. Both SST and Brougham models came as hardtop coupes, sedans, and wagons.\n\nThe DPL came with AMC's new {{convert|258|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} {{convert|150|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} Inline-6 with seven main bearings. All the SSTs and Broughams featured the {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine with {{convert|210|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} as standard. BorgWarner's \"Shift-Command\" automatic transmissions were standard equipment across the line. Two of AMC's {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} were optional; an 8.5:1 compression version with a two-barrel carburetor or a high-compression four-barrel V8 that required premium-fuel. The previous \"AMX 390\" V8 gave way to a new {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} {{convert|335|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} V8 as the top engine option.\n\nStyling changes consisted of a new fascia up front. It featured headlights contained in their own chrome pods separate from, but flanking the new grille with a bright rectangular surround, with rounded edges. The \"natural\" cast [[pot metal]] grille insert was recessed and featured a bright vertical bar pattern. A second set of parking lights was added outboard of the headlight clusters, and they were integrated into the fender extension to eliminate the need for separate front marker lights.\n\nTaillights on hardtop coupes and sedans still ran wall-to-wall, but the twin backup lights were moved from the center to further outboard\u2014approximately eight inches in from either fender side. Once again, the wagon received few changes at the rear, but added a new design for its optional woodgrain side trim, which filled in its upper bodysides. Its lower edge flowed downward aft of its peak at the leading edge above each front wheelhouse, in similar fashion to the [[Buick Skylark]]'s side \"sweepspear\" styling cue.\n\nAmbassador base models were offered to fleet buyers with various police, [[taxicab]], and other heavy-duty packages. Governments and police departments in the U.S. historically used standard-size, low-price line four-door sedans. Equipped with the 360 or 401<ref>{{cite web |last=Missouri State Highway Patrol |title=History of the Motor Equipment Division |year=2006 |url= http://www.mshp.dps.mo.gov/MSHPWeb/PatrolDivisions/MED/documents/HistoryofMED.pdf |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527114129/http://www.mshp.dps.mo.gov/MSHPWeb/PatrolDivisions/MED/documents/HistoryofMED.pdf |archivedate=May 27, 2010 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://greenfieldpolice.org/Patrol/Fleet/1971_Squad/1971_squad.html |title=1971 Greenfield Police patrol Ambassador |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20040704215728/http://www.greenfieldpolice.org/Patrol/Fleet/1971_Squad/1971_squad.html |archivedate=July 4, 2004 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> engines, the base Ambassadors saw use as [[Police vehicles in the United States and Canada|police cruisers]] and support vehicles.\n\n=== 1972 ===\n[[File:1972 AMC Ambassador Brougham sedan in burgundy at 2015 AMO meet-2.jpg|thumb|right|1972 Ambassador Brougham sedan]]\nMinor changes greeted 1972 Ambassadors, as AMC's biggest news for the year was the addition of the innovative '''AMC Buyer Protection Plan''', that included the industry's first 12-month or {{convert|12000|mi|km|adj=on}} bumper-to-bumper [[warranty]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Boone |first=Louis E. |last2=Kurtz |first2=David L. |title=Contemporary Business |publisher=Dryden Press |year=1976 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/contemporarybusi0000boon_h9i8/page/223 223\u2013224] |isbn=978-0-03-013651-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarybusi0000boon_h9i8/page/223 }}</ref> This was the first time an automaker promised to repair anything wrong with the car (except for [[tire]]s) and owners were provided with a [[toll-free telephone number]] to the company, as well as a free loaner car if a warranty repair took overnight. This backing also included mechanical upgrades to increase durability and quality, such as the standardization of electric windshield wipers on all model lines, replacing AMC's vacuum-powered units, as well as better interior trims. By focusing on quality, the smallest domestic automaker was profitable for 1972, earning US$30.2 million (the highest net profit achieved by AMC since 1964) on $4 billion in sales.\n\nThe base Ambassador DPL model was canceled, with three body styles now available in SST and Brougham trim. Fleet purchasers could order plain Ambassadors in Police Pursuit Vehicle (PPV) or Special Service Package (SSP) versions. A six-cylinder engine was no longer available; thus, Ambassador became a V8-only car for the first time since 1964. This made the Ambassador the only volume-produced American car that included air conditioning, power brakes, automatic transmission, and a V8 engine as standard equipment; all while being priced less than the Big Three's full-sized cars.<ref name=\"1972AMCphotos\">{{cite web|url= http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/AMC/1972_AMC/1972_Ambassador_Promo/1972%20Ambassador%20Promo-01.html |title=1972 AMC Ambassador press photos |date=1 September 1971 |work=The Old Car Manual Project |accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> The base engine was the {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} with two {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} or a {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} versions optional. The engines were designed to operate on regular grade, low-lead, or unleaded gasolines.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/AMC/1972_AMC/1972%20AMC%20Full%20Line%20Brochure/image13.html |title=1972 AMC Full Line brochure |page=25 |work=The Old Car Manual Project |accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> All were based on the engine designs responsible for AMC winning the 1971\u20131972 Trans-Am Series.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eT7LT69STO0C&pg=PA227&lpg=PA227&dq=That+basic+engine,+which+was+responsible+for+AMC+winning+the+1971\u20131972+Trans-Am+Series,+became+the+backbone+of |page=227 |title=Ultimate American V-8 Engine Data Book |edition=Second |first=Peter C. |last=Sessler |year=2010 |publisher=MBI Publishing |isbn=978-0-7603-3681-6 |accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> The Borg-Warner transmission was replaced by the \"Torque-Command\" ([[TorqueFlite]]) three-speed automatic sourced from [[Chrysler]].\n\nStyling changes on the 1972 Ambassador were limited to a new crosshatch [[Casting (metalworking)|cast metal]] grille with bright trim and new integrated fender extension mounted side marker lamps on the front. Brougham station wagons included a roof rack, rear air deflector, as well as 3M \"dinoc\" woodgrain trim on body sides and tailgate.<ref name=\"1972AMCphotos\"/>\n\nA ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'' magazine survey after driving a total of {{convert|1000000|mi|km|0}} found Ambassador owners were pleased with their cars, describing them to be \"very comfortable to drive and ride in\" with handling listed as a top \"specific like\" by half of the drivers.<ref name=\"1972amb\">{{cite journal| last=Lamm |first=Michael |title=American Motors' Guaranteed Car |journal=Popular Mechanics |pages=94\u2013194 |date=May 1972 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=StQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA94&dq=1972+AMC+Ambassador&q=1972%20AMC%20Ambassador |volume=137 |issue=5 |accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> A very high percentage (92%) would buy one again.<ref name=\"1972amb\"/> Although the Buyer Protection Plan was listed by only 8.5% as a reason to buy an Ambassador, owners valued the smaller AMC dealers that \"had more time to be courteous and to pay personal attention to customers.\"<ref name=\"1972amb\"/>\n\n=== 1973 ===\n[[File:1973 Ambassador 4-d 401.JPG|thumb|250px|1973 Ambassador Brougham sedan with {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8]]\nThe SST models were dropped from the line, as all 1973 Ambassadors now came in one high-level \"Brougham\" trim. Ten popular items including an [[AM broadcasting|AM]] radio, power disk brakes, tinted glass, and [[whitewall tire]]s were added to the already extensive standard equipment list that included air conditioning, V8 engine, and automatic transmission. The Ambassador line \"maintains its reputation as one of the industry's most completely equipped cars.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=vQEUAQAAMAAJ&q=1973,+AMC's+Ambassador+Brougham+series+maintains+its+reputation+as+one+of+the+industry's+most+completely+equipped+cars |page=80 |title=13 Models Offered by AMC for 1973 |journal=Michigan Manufacturer and Financial Record |date=1972 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Multiple improvements in quality were designed to reinforce the new \"Extended Buyer Protection Plan\" exclusive to AMC cars that provided complete maintenance coverage for two years or {{convert|24000|mi|km|0|}}.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=cKSqa8u3EIoC&pg=PA83&dq=American+Motors+1973+cars |pages=82\u201383 |title=American Motors Introduces the Extended Buyer Protection Plan\n|journal=Popular Science |date=March 1973 |volume=202 |issue=3 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> The automaker's marketing campaign shifted to stress quality in a \"we back them better because we build them better\" advertising with particular emphasis into the Hornet, Matador and Gremlin promotion, while the Ambassador received got individual support with the tagline \"you get standard equipment, the luxuries you'd normally have to pay extra for.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/?id=w7UqAQAAMAAJ&q=73+AMC+Marketing+to+stress+Quality,+Identity,+Image&dq=73+AMC+Marketing+to+stress+Quality,+Identity,+Image |page=18 |title=AMC Marketing to stress Quality, Identity, Image |date=2 August 1972 |journal=Automotive News |publisher=Crain Automotive Group |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=YAvgAAAAMAAJ&q=The+1973+Ambassador+is+the+only+full-size+car+that+comes+standard+with+air+conditioning,+automatic+transmissions+radio,+power+steering,+front+powerdisc+brakes,+tinted |page=76 |journal=Time |volume=101 |date=1973 |title=1973 Ambassador is the only full-size car that comes standard with (advertisement) |accessdate=6 July 2017|last1=Hadden |first1=Briton |last2=Luce |first2=Henry Robinson }}</ref> Model year production for AMC increased 25 percent, outperforming the industry average production increase by 75 percent, with only a slightly changed product in the showrooms.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/?id=PV1uzCfmJDgC&pg=PA24&dq=American+Motors+1973+cars |pages=24\u201330 |title=American Cars, 1973-1980: Every Model, Year by Year |first=J. Kelly |last=Flory |publisher=McFarland |year=2012 |isbn=9780786456369 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn range rationalization to a single trim available in two-door hardtop, four-door sedan, and station wagon body versions, the styling changes for the 1973 Ambassadors were minimal. Heftier front and rear [[Bumper (automobile)|bumpers]] were included to comply with new U.S. [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA) regulations that required all passenger cars to withstand a {{convert|5|mph|0|adj=on}} front and a {{convert|2.5|mph|0|adj=on}} rear impacts without damage to the engine, lights, and safety equipment. Ambassadors complied with the regulation by incorporating a stronger front bumper equipped with self-restoring telescoping shock-absorbers.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Lamm |first=Michael |title=AMC: Hornet hatchback leads the lineup |journal=Popular Mechanics |volume=138 |issue=4 |pages=118\u2013202 |date=October 1972 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=VNQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA118&dq=1973+AMC+Ambassador |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Designed to \"give\" as much as {{convert|3.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}, it jutted slightly forward from the front fascia and incorporated flexible trim matching the body paint. This bumper also featured a more prominent horizontal rubber guard at its upper portion near the grille, thus eliminating the need for a pair of vertical chrome bumper guards that was optional before. The rear bumper gained vertical black rubber bumper guards that also replaced a pair of similar and previously optional chrome bumper guards. The grille gained heavier horizontal bars and headlight bezels took on blackout trim in their recessed portions.\n\n== Eighth generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1974\n| image        = 1974 AMC Ambassador Brougham 4-door sedan beige.JPG\n| caption      = 1974 Ambassador Brougham sedan\n| class        = [[Full-size car|Full-size]]\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[station wagon]] }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|122|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|217.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] | {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 }}\n| transmission = 3-speed ''[[Torqueflite|Torque Command]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| name         = Eighth generation\n}}\n\n=== 1974 ===\n[[File:1974 AMC Ambassador sedan blue-white Kenosha-r.jpg|thumb|left|1974 AMC Ambassador sedan]]\n[[File:1974 AMC Ambassador sedan blue-white Kenosha-a.jpg|thumb|left|1974 AMC Ambassador sedan]]\n\nAmbassador sales had remained steady since 1970, despite the lack of major changes to the vehicle. 1974 models were stretched, {{convert|7|in|mm|spell=in}}, just as the 1973 [[1973 oil crisis|Arab Oil Embargo]] sparked nationwide gasoline rationing to accommodate energy absorbing bumpers.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Norbye |first=Jan P. |title=New bumpers have uniform height, take angle impacts |journal=Popular Science |pages=90\u201391 |date=October 1973 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lpiMSzja6W4C&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=New+bumpers+have+uniform+Ambassador |volume=203 |issue=4 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe 1974 Ambassador Brougham was no longer available as a 2-door (pillar-less) [[hardtop]], leaving the 4-door sedan and station wagon body styles. The hardtop's cancellation was due in part to low sales volume of the Ambassador 2-door versions, as well as the introduction of the 1974 [[AMC Matador|Matador coupe]] which received the ''[[Car and Driver]]'' \"Best Styled Car of 1974,\" featuring a long hood and short rear deck design that avoided (at least on introduction) period hallmarks such as imitation landau bars and opera lights.<ref>{{cite journal |title=none|journal=Car and Driver |date=November 1973 }}</ref>\n\nStyling changes for the Ambassador sedan and wagon included revised front fender caps on the same fenders used since 1969, and hood, grille, bumpers, rear fascia, instrument panel, interior trim, hood ornament, and a new font for the Ambassador nameplate. The grille showed off a new squared-off loop-type design surrounding the circular recessed quad headlights, and featured a forward-protruding center. The insert held a crosshatch pattern dominated by two thick horizontal bars that connected the headlight bezels and contained new parking lights between them. These parking lights had amber lenses, followed the grille protrusion forward, and were overlaid by the grille's crosshatch trim. Headlamp bezels were once again blacked out in their recessed areas. The new hood and front bumper followed the grille's central protrusion forward, giving the car a slight \"coffin nose\" look. The revised [[AMC Matador|Matador]] sedan saw a similar frontal treatment in 1974, but with a much more pronounced effect and with different single headlamp clusters, hood, and grille insert.\n\nAs with the new Matador sedan, the new rear bumper was much larger and backed by shock absorbers, as it was beefed up to comply with new [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] regulations for standardized front and rear bumpers on passenger cars that could sustain a {{convert|5|mph|0|adj=on}} impact with no damage. Sedan rear fenders received fiberglass caps that wrapped inward to create a recessed space that met a carryover [[decklid]]. In this space was mounted the new rectangular taillight housings, which featured taller white backup lights mounted inboard of the new taillights. The license plate moved from the rear bumper to the area between the new taillight assemblies, and the whole taillight and license plate system on the sedans was surrounded its own loop of chrome trim. Both Ambassador and Matador sedans shared the same rear end styling. \n\nThe cargo area and the rear design of station wagons remained similar to previous Ambassadors, save for a massive new bumper and revised taillamps. The wagon was available with two-row bench seats for six passengers or with a rear-facing third row for a total eight seat-belted passengers. All came with numerous practical, appearance, and comfort items as standard. These included a two-way opening tail gate: (1) hinged at the bottom for convenient loading or hauling long cargo and (2) hinged at the side to open as door for ease of entry and exit for passengers or cargo; wood grained [[Transparency (optics)|semi-transparent]] vinyl side and rear trim, a full-length [[roof rack]]; as well as a chrome and wood grain roof air deflector to help keep the tailgate window clean.\n\nPowertrain selections remained the same as in 1973, with only [[AMC V8 engine|V8 engines]] and automatic transmissions available. When ordered with a trailer package (special wiring harness with heavy-duty flasher and heavy-duty suspension with rear sway bar), the Ambassador was rated for up to {{convert|5000|lb|0|adj=on}} towing capacity.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schultz |first=Mort |title=Cars to take your rig in tow |journal=Popular Mechanics |pages=156\u2013157 |date=March 1974 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ddQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA156&dq=1974+AMC+Ambassador |volume=141 |issue=3 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Other increases for 1974 included a larger capacity fuel tank, {{convert|24.9|usgal|L impgal|0|abbr=on}}, and an alternator producing 62 [[ampere]]s. New sound insulation made the Ambassador even quieter. All came with a very lengthy list of standard equipment that was typically optional on competing makes. These included comfort items such as air conditioning, an AM radio, and vanity mirror to appearance enhancements such as [[pin striping]] and [[whitewall tire]]s.\n\nSales of all full-size vehicles, regardless of the automaker, fell significantly in 1974 as America's focus shifted to smaller cars. Ambassador sales were no different, and in June 1974, the final AMC Ambassador rolled off the [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]] assembly line, ending a nameplate that had been in continuous production in some form for 48 years.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==International markets==\n\n===Argentina===\n[[File:AutoantiguodesfileMDP5-9jul2016.jpg|thumb|right|Fifth U.S. generation Ambassador 990 built by IKA from 1965 to 1972]] \n'''Industrias Kaiser Argentina''' [[Industrias Kaiser Argentina|(IKA)]] produced the U.S. third, fourth, and fifth generation Ambassadors in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina]] from 1962 to 1972, and later available by special order through 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cocheargentino.com.ar/r/rambler.htm |title=IKA - Caracter\u00edsticas Classic Custom - Classic Custom De Luxe - Ambassador 440 |date=18 May 2009 |publisher=Coche Argentino |language=Spanish |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAssembly of IKA Ramblers began in 1962, with the Argentinean cars being the 1961 U.S. versions, but equipped with {{convert|226|cuin|L|2|abbr=on}} [[Continental Motors Company|Continental]] I6 engines producing {{convert|119|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 4000 rpm, along with a steering column mounted manual three-speed transmission. The Ambassador 440 was the top trim IKA model available only as a four-door sedan.\n\nThe completely new generation models by AMC in the U.S. for the 1963 model year was also replicated by IKA. The Ambassador sedan came only in 990 trim and it revolutionized the Argentine automotive market by introducing innovations that included power steering, power windows, and factory installed air conditioning.\n\n[[File:Presidential Rambler Ambassador.jpg|thumb|right|Presidential Rambler Ambassadors, produced in 1968 by [[Industrias Kaiser Argentina|IKA]] ]]\n\nThe Ambassador line was redesigned for 1965 in the U.S., as well as for Argentina. All IKA Rambler models now featured the {{convert|230.5|cuin|L|2|abbr=on}} [[overhead camshaft]] (OHC) straight-six \"[[Jeep Tornado engine|Tornado Interceptor]]\" engines producing {{convert|145|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 4200 rpm. They were originally developed by [[Kaiser Motors]] in the U.S. for the 1963 [[Jeep Gladiator]] pickups and [[Jeep Wagoneer|Wagoneer]] vehicles. The engine was now produced in Argentina and it increased the domestic (local sourced) content of IKA automobiles to lower taxes (tariffs).\n\nThe new IKA Ambassador 990 sedans were further upgraded to steering column mounted [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] four-speed manual transmissions, front disk brakes, front reclining bucket seats with center cushion and armrest, as well as the luxury features that included power windows and air conditioning.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://oldcarandtruckpictures.com/Argentina/Argentinajamc.html |title=Old Cars of Argentina Manufactured by Industrias Kaiser Argentina S.A. (IKA) |work=oldcarandtruckpictures.com |accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref> A road test by ''Revista Parabrisas'' described the 1965 IKA Rambler Ambassador 990 as \"soft, opulent, and smooth ride at all speeds... something big, luxurious and complete... the highest expression of comfort tested so far by the magazine.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://www.testdelayer.com.ar/pruebas/ika-rambler-ambassador.htm |title=IKA Rambler Ambassador 990 - 1965 - La m\u00e1s alta expresi\u00f3n del confort |journal=Revista Parabrisas |issue=59 |date=October 1965 |language=Spanish |publisher=testdelayer.com.ar |accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nStretch versions of the IKA Rambler Ambassador were used as official government [[limousine]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LfMk3dWPtDM |title=Per\u00f3n asume la presidencia 12 de octubre de 1973 |publisher=youtube |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The \"Presidential\" models featured a longer rear door and side window, as well as broader [[Pillar (car)|C-pillar]] with padded [[vinyl roof]] cover and a small rear window.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Australia===\n[[File:1970 AMC Ambassador Hardtop Coupe (21938581090).jpg|thumb|One of only 16 two-door hardtop factory-RHD Ambassadors brought into Australia in 1970]]\n[[Australian Motor Industries]] (AMI) obtained the rights to assemble and distribute Ramblers in 1960, and the 1961, 1962, and 1963 model year Ambassadors were built in [[Australia]].<ref>Rambler Models ''[[Truck & Bus Transportation]]'' August 1961 page 10</ref> The 1961 sedan, which was powered by a {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]], was the most powerful car being assembled in Australia at that time.<ref name=\"Neasmith\"/> [[Knock-down kit]]s featuring [[right-hand drive]] were shipped from Kenosha to AMI's facilities in [[Port Melbourne]]. The Australian-built Ambassadors included a significant percentage of \"local content\" to gain import [[tariff]] (tax) concessions by using parts and components (such as interiors and upholstery) that were sourced from Australian manufacturers. AMI's first year of production resulted in 65 registrations for 1961. Registrations of the 1963 model continued into 1964 for a total of 21 Ambassadors registered for 1964.\n\nAlthough not documented in any AMI records, according to Australian Rambler afficionados 20 right-hand drive 1970 Ambassadors were fully imported from Canada, apparently 16 two-door hardtops and 4 four-door sedans. One possible reason for this was that it may have been a holding action while AMI was preparing for assembly of the new 1970 Rebel. AMC had assembled over 3,700 RHD Rambler Ambassadors for the U.S Postal Service in 1967, so they were well experienced in making completed right-hand drive vehicles. All Australian factory-RHD 1970 Ambassadors came with automatic transmission with floor shift.<ref>https://www.gumtree.com.au/s-ad/benaraby/cars-vans-utes/rambler-ambassador/1242484069</ref>\n\nThe dash and instrument pack of the 1967 Ambassador which had been converted and used in the RHD Ambassadors assembled for the U.S Postal Service was thereafter used in all Australian and New Zealand-assembled Rambler Rebel and Matador models, and all RHD, U.S-built Rebel and Matadors for the United Kingdom.\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[File:1970 AMC Ambassador SST (14379718872).jpg|thumb|right|One of 12 factory-RHD 1970 Ambassadors for the New Zealand market ]]\n\nAmerican Motors motor vehicles were assembled in New Zealand by '''VW Motors''' at their Volkswagen plant in Otahuhu, Auckland from 1958 until 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/motoring/107503496/the-empty-halls-of-new-zealands-car-assembly-industry |title=The empty halls of New Zealand's car assembly industry |first=Todd |last=Niall |website=Stuff |date=6 October 2018 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> From 1964, AMC vehicles were assembled by '''Campbell Motor Industries''' (CMI) in Thames, [[North Island]]. CMI assembled the Rambler Classic and Rebel models from knock-down kits and also imported fully assembled factory-right-hand-drive vehicles direct from AMC. Although no Ambassadors were locally assembled by CMI, it is believed twelve 1970 factory-right-hand-drive Ambassadors were fully imported.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2011/10/12/boomerang-the-only-gremlin-exported-to-australia-returns-to-the-united-states/ |title=Boomerang: The only Gremlin exported to Australia returns to the United States (comments) |first=Lindsay |last=Mckenzie |date= July 2017 |publisher=Hemmings |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Costa Rica===\nRambler vehicles were marketed in [[Costa Rica]] since 1959 through '''Purdy Motor'''.<ref name=\"CostaRica\">{{cite web|url= http://amc.co.cr/index.htm |title=AMC American Motors Corporation, Costa Rica |publisher=amc.co.cr |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Ruhi\">{{cite web|url= http://kaizen-factor.com/ultimate-toyota-restoration-backstory/ |title=The Ultimate Toyota Restoration: The Backstory |first=Joaqu\u00edn |last=Ruhi |date=10 May 2014 |publisher=Kaizen Factor |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> New local content regulations enacted during the 1960s effectively required vehicles sold in those markets to be assembled from [[knock-down kit]]s.<ref name=\"Ruhi\"/> An assembly plant for Rambler and Toyota vehicles was established, '''ECASA''', and the first Ramblers were produced in Costa Rica by the end of 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://amc.co.cr/amc_costarica.htm |title= Timeline of American Motors in Costa Rica |publisher=amc.co.cr |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The company built Ambassadors and other AMC models through 1970, with Toyota increasing ownership of ECASA.<ref name=\"CostaRica\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.toyota-global.com/company/history_of_toyota/75years/data/automotive_business/sales/activity/latin_america/index.html |title=Activities by RegionLatin America |publisher=Toyota Motor |accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\nAmerican Motors first-generation Ambassadors were exported to Mexico in the first half of 1958 and assembled locally in the second half of the same year and 1959 under '''Planta Reo de M\u00e9xico''' based in Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n. The model was virtually restricted to the four-door hardtop sedan only. It was powered by the four-barrel {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine producing {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} coupled to a three-speed automatic transmission. The model became the marque's top-of-the-line product alongside the three versions of the midsize Rambler and Rambler American models. \n\nHowever, low sales figures alongside a deteriorating relationship between AMC and Planta REO lead to the cancellation of the contract in the second half of 1959. <ref>{{cite book|first=Douglas C. |last=Bennett |first2=Kenneth E. |last2=Sharpe |title=Transnational Corporations versus the State: The Political Economy of the Mexican Auto Industry |publisher=Princeton University Press |date=2014 |isbn=9780691022376}}</ref> American Motors once again exported its products into Mexico and a new local partner, Willys Mexicana that eventually would become '''Vehiculos Automotores Mexicanos''' [[Vehiculos Automotores Mexicanos|(VAM)]]. The agreement was signed in March 1960 and production began in Mexico City. \n\nThis meant the discontinuation of the Ambassador line in Mexico as the new operation had several priorities above offering a top-end luxury full-size car line. Aside from offering the already existing Jeep line, Willys Mexicana focused efforts on the compact Rambler American, which obtained a generation change just the next year, meaning a complete retooling of the Vallejo plant. In 1962, legal and industrial requirements in the country became stronger with the auto industry integration decree issued by president [[Adolfo L\u00f3pez Mateos]] in 1962. Among its mandates, it fully banned the importation of automobile engines. Willys Mexicana began building its own engine plant, which was achieved in November 1964. Once the Rambler American was consolidated in the Mexican market, Willys Mexicana opted to expand the product line by introducing the brand-new second generation Rambler Classic midsize model as a larger luxury counterpart to the economy compact American. Also in 1963, due to problems with WM's parent company (the SOMEX bank) as well as further requirements of the government auto industry decree, Willys Mexicana was reorganized into an entirely new company with expanded capital and direct investment from the Mexican government, Kaiser Willys, and American Motors. This resulted in the formation of Veh\u00edculos Automotores Mexicanos S.A. \n\nAfter the corporate transition process between 1960 and 1964 concluded, in which the Rambler marque under VAM surpassed the commercial results of its local predecessors Armadora Mexicana and Planta REO combined between 1950 and 1959, the company opted not to offer the Ambassador model. The Mexican market of the era was still relatively small and since the Ambassador shared mostly the same styling as the contemporary midsize model of the company, it was considered that internal competition would affect the sales of a simultaneous Rambler Classic/Ambassador line-up. Unlike the United States, which had a much larger and diverse market for two different car lines with the same styling, AMC could offer a strong difference between both models with the exclusive V8 engine for the Ambassador and the Classic being restricted to six cylinders only. This advantage did not exist in Mexico since VAM could only produce six cylinder engines in its Lerma plant and V8 engines could not be imported from AMC due to the ban of the 1962 decree. Instead, VAM opted to use the Rambler Classic as its most luxurious and flagship model, giving it the same treatment AMC put in the Ambassador model in the US and Canada. This would be passed on to the subsequent equivalent Rebel and Matador models produced under VAM. \n\nThe 1958\u20131959 Ambassador models represent the only chapter in this model's history to be present in Mexico. These were the only full-size American Motors products sold in the country alongside the second generation VAM Classic (Matador) models. Even more unique was the fact that it was a factory V8 model, the only one of its kind to ever be sold in Mexico belonging to American Motors.\n\n===United Kingdom===\nRambler Ambassadors were exported in limited numbers to the United Kingdom in factory right-hand-drive direct from AMC during the 1960s and up to its final year of 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/File:Im196610MotSC-RamblerMots.jpg |title=Image of Rambler Motors (AMC) Ltd. advertisement |website=www.gracesguide.co.uk |date=1967 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> They were imported by '''Rambler Motors (A.M.C) Ltd''' of Chiswick in West London which became a subsidiary of AMC in 1961.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Rambler_Motors |title=Rambler Motors |website=www.gracesguide.co.uk |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> The location had previously been used since 1926 for British assembly of Hudson, Essex, and Terraplane vehicles<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/april-1968/44/us-car-concessionaires-great-britain|title=U.S. Car Concessionaires in Great Britain |date=April 1968 |website=Motor Sport Magazine (Archive) |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> and later AMC's post-1954 Hudson, Nash and Rambler models. Ambassador models marketed in the UK were the Ambassador saloon (sedan), SST coupe, and station wagon. AMC vehicles were distributed by London distributors Clarke and Simpson Limited and were marketed as \"the only American car built with RHD.\"<ref>http://www.classiccarcatalogue.com/RAMBLER%201968.html</ref> As with all export markets UK models were marketed as \"Rambler\" even after the Rambler marque was dropped in the USA.\n\n== Epilogue ==\nBecause AMC was focusing its attentions on their newly acquired [[Jeep]] line, the redesigned 1974 Matador coupe, and the [[AMC Pacer]], which would debut in 1975, the company would not put forth the investment to continue the full-size Ambassador line after its 1974 redesign. Instead, the automaker upgraded the Matador sedan and wagon counterparts starting with the 1975 model year. The basic [[automobile platform]] was used by AMC since the 1967 model year, and the full-size automobile market segment was declining. American Motors strategy now aimed at smaller cars and sport-utility vehicles.\n\nHowever, the Ambassador basically continued as the similarly sized and styled [[AMC Matador|Matador]] sedans and wagons. From 1975 they became available in uplevel \"Brougham\" trim and assumed the model numbers of the previously equivalent Ambassadors.<ref>{{cite book |last=Flory, Jr. |first=J. \u201cKelly\u201d |title=American Cars, 1973-1980: Every Model, Year by Year |date=2012 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786456369 |page=223 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=yPwcDJ10TtAC&pg=PA223&dq=AMC+discontinued+the+Ambassador+line |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> The Matador was also offered in a unique top-of-the-line '''Barcelona''' four-door in its final year of production, 1978.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lamm |first1=Michael |title=Driving the '78 cars from American Motors |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=October 1977 |volume=148 |issue=4 |page=106, 178 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6uEDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA106&dq=Matador+Barcelona+sedan |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1978 AMC Full Line Brochure |url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.org/United%20States/AMC/1978_AMC/1978_AMC_Brochure/slides/1978_AMC-28.html |website=Old Car Brochures Project |pages=28\u201329, 32 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Foster |first=Patrick R. |title=AMC Cars: 1954\u20131987 An Illustrated History |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-58388-112-5 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Foster |first=Patrick R. |title=AMC Performance Cars: 1951\u20131983 Photo Archive |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-58388-127-9 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Foster |first=Patrick R. |title=American Motors \u2013 The Last Independent |publisher=Krause Publications |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-87341-240-7}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Foster |first=Patrick R. |title=1958\u20131962 Ambassador: A Rambler By Any Other Name |journal=Collectible Automobile |date=December 1992 |volume=9 |issue=6 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first=John |title=The Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946\u20131975 |publisher=Krause Publications |year=1987 | isbn=978-0-87341-096-0 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Mitchell |first=Larry G. |title=Illustrated AMC Buyer's Guide |publisher=Motorbooks |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-87938-891-1 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|AMC Ambassador}}\n* [http://www.AMCRC.com/ AMC Rambler Club]\n* [http://www.amonational.com/ American Motors Owners Association]\n* [http://www.nashcarclub.org/ Nash Car Club]\n* [http://www.americansportscars.com/healey.html Nash Healey History]\n* [http://www.nash-gb.com/ Nash in the UK]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101106220820/http://homepage.mac.com/christopher.z/hobby/67-Amb-1.html 1967 Ambassador information]\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=Rambler|model=Ambassador|Rambler Ambassador}}\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=AMC|model=Ambassador|AMC Ambassador}}\n\n{{American Motors}}\n{{amc Timeline}}\n\n[[Category:AMC vehicles|Ambassador]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Convertibles]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:Mid-size cars]]\n[[Category:Full-size vehicles]]\n[[Category:Limousines]]\n[[Category:Police vehicles]]\n[[Category:Taxicab vehicles]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:1960s cars]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1958]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Large-sized cars produced by American Motors Corporation}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name           = AMC Ambassador\n| image          = 1958 Ambassador 4-d hardtop wagon 1.JPG\n| caption        = 1958 Ambassador hardtop station wagon\n| interior image = 1967 Ambassador 990 4-d aqua pa-s.jpg\n| interiorcaption= 1967 Ambassador 990 sedan\n| predecessor    = [[Nash Ambassador]]\n| successor      = [[AMC Matador]]\n| aka            = {{unbulleted list | Ambassador by Rambler | American Motors Ambassador <ref name=\"1970_brochure\">{{cite web|url= http://www.lov2xlr8.no/brochures/misc/70_2.html |title=1970 American Motors Ambassador sales brochure |page=2 |publisher=lov2xlr8.no |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> | Rambler Ambassador | IKA Ambassador }}\n| manufacturer   = [[American Motors Corporation]] (AMC)\n| assembly       = {{unbulleted list | [[Kenosha Engine|Kenosha Factory]], [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]], [[United States|U.S.]] | [[Australia]] ([[Australian Motor Industries|AMI]])<ref name=\"Neasmith\">{{cite journal|first=Bruce |last=Neasmith |title=AMC Rambler in Australia Part 1 |journal=Restored Cars |issue=177 |date=July\u2013August 2006 |pages=39, 40, & 69}}</ref> | [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina]] ([[Industrias Kaiser Argentina|IKA]]) | [[Costa Rica]] (ECASA)<ref name=\"CostaRica\"/> | [[Monterrey, Mexico]] (Planta REO)}}\n| layout         = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel drive layout|FR layout]]\n| production     = 1957\u20131974\n| model_years    = 1958\u20131974\n| class          = [[Mid-size car|Mid-size]]/[[Full-size car|Full-size]]\n}}\n\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=horizontal |image1=OriAMClogo.png |width1=100 |image2 =1967 Ambassador 990 4-d aqua pa-t.jpg\n| width2=150 |footer=Ambassador emblem (1958\u20131961) and name badge (1967\u20131973) }}\n\nThe '''Ambassador''' is a [[Full-size car|full-size]] [[automobile]] manufactured and marketed by [[American Motors|American Motors Corporation]] (AMC) from 1957-1974 over eight generations, in two-and four-door sedan, two-door hardtop, station wagon and convertible body styles. \n\nWhen discontinued, ''Ambassador'' had been the longest continuously-used car nameplate, from 1927-1974,<ref>{{cite web |last=Fitzgerald |first=Craig |title=1957 Nash Ambassador Country Club |url= https://www.hemmings.com/blog/article/1957-nash-ambassador-country-club/ |publisher=Hemmings Classic Car |accessdate=20 August 2019 |date=November 2008 |quote=Nash had been utilizing the Ambassador model name continuously since 1927, and American Motors would continue to use it until 1974.}}</ref> in automotive history.<ref>{{cite web |title=1965 AMC Ambassador |url= https://www.conceptcarz.com/z28735/amc-ambassador.aspx |website=conceptcarz.com |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> The ''Ambassador'' nameplate was used variously as the '''Ambassador V-8 by Rambler''', '''Rambler Ambassador''', and finally '''AMC Ambassador.''' Previously, the nameplate [[Nash Ambassador|Ambassador]] applied to [[Nash Motors|Nash's]] full-size cars. The nameplate referred to a trim level between 1927 and 1931.\n\nAmbassadors were manufactured in [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]] as well as at AMC's [[Brampton Assembly]] in Brampton, Ontario from 1963 to 1966. [[Australian Motor Industries]] (AMI) assembled Ambassadors from [[knock-down kit]]s with [[right-hand drive]] from 1961 to 1963. The U.S. fifth generation Ambassadors were manufactured by [[Industrias Kaiser Argentina]] (IKA) in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina]] from 1965 to 1972, as well as assembled by ECASA in [[Costa Rica]] from 1965 to 1970. Planta REO assembled first-generation Ambassadors in Mexico at its Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n plant. Fifth and seventh generation Ambassadors were modified into custom stretch [[limousine]]s in Argentina and the U.S.\n\n== Development ==\nFollowing [[George W. Mason]]'s unexpected death in the fall of 1954, [[George W. Romney|George Romney]] (whom Mason had been grooming as his eventual successor), succeeded him as president and CEO of the newly formed American Motors. Romney recognized that to be successful in the postwar marketplace, an automobile manufacturer would have to be able to produce and sell cars in sufficient volume to [[Amortization (business)|amortize]] the high cost of tooling. Toward that end, he set out to increase AMC's market share with its Rambler models that were selling in [[market segment]] in which the domestic Big Three ([[General Motors]], [[Ford Motor Company]], and [[Chrysler]]) automakers did not yet compete. While development of a redesigned 1958 Nash Ambassador, based on a stretched and reskinned 1956 Rambler [[Coachwork|body]] was almost complete, AMC's [[Automotive design|designers]] were also working on a retrimmed [[Hudson Motor Car Company|Hudson]] equivalent, called '''Rebel''', to offer Hudson [[Car dealership|dealers]].\n\nHowever, as sales of the large-sized [[Nash Ambassador]] and [[Hudson Hornet]] models slowed, it became clear to Romney that consumer confidence in the historic Nash and Hudson nameplates had collapsed. Reluctantly, he decided that 1957 would be the end of both nameplates, and the company would concentrate on the new Rambler line, which was registered as a separate [[marque]] for 1957.\n\nThe market positioning meant that \"the AMC Ambassador was a car with no real competitors throughout most of the sixties\" because it was viewed as a luxury-type car and could be put against the higher end large-sized models from the domestic Big Three automakers, but the Ambassador was more of a midsized car.<ref>{{cite book |last=Flory, Jr. |first=J. \u201cKelly\u201d |title=American Cars, 1973-1980: Every Model, Year by Year |date=2012 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786456369 |page=2 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1DiNAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=the+AMC+Ambassador+was+a+car+with+no+real+competitors+throughout+most+of+the+sixtie |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== First generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image        = Rambler Ambassador (3893707660).jpg\n| caption      = 1958 Ambassador V8, Custom sedan\n| model_years  = 1958\u20131959\n| aka          = Ambassador V8 by Rambler\n| name         = First generation\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[hardtop]] sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 4-door [[hardtop]] station wagon }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|117|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| transmission = 3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| engine       = {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]]\n}}\n\n=== 1958 ===\n[[File:1958 Ambassador 4-d hardtop.jpg|thumb|right|1958 Ambassador Custom hardtop sedan with [[continental tire]] ]]\n[[File:1958 Ambassador 4-d hardtop wagon 2.JPG|thumb|right|Ambassador hardtop (pillarless) Cross Country station wagon]]\n\nAmerican Motors planned to produce a stretched a {{convert|117|in|0|adj=on}} [[wheelbase]] version of the Rambler platform for Nash dealers to be the new Nash Ambassador, and another for Hudson dealers. Shortly before committing to production of the new long-wheelbase versions of the Hudson and the Nash, CEO Romney decided to abandon the Nash and Hudson marques.\n\nDespite the fact that the Nash and Hudson names were canceled, work on the car itself continued, and American Motors introduced debuted in the fall of 1957, the 1958 \"Ambassador V-8 by Rambler\" on a {{convert|117|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase. Its features included a {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] (equipped with a 4-barrel [[carburetor]] and dual exhausts and rated at {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|360|lb\u00b7ft|N\u00b7m}} of torque) mated to a [[BorgWarner]] supplied 3-speed [[automatic transmission]] with push button gear selection.\n\nIn 1956, AMC first produced its own V8, a modern overhead valve V8 displacing {{convert|250|CID|L|1|abbr=on}}, with a forged steel crank shaft, which when equipped with a 4-barrel carburetor was rated at {{convert|215|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}. In 1957, AMC bored and stroked the 250 CID V8 to {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} displacement which when offered in the [[Rambler Rebel]] used solid lifters and Bendix electronic fuel injection was rated at {{convert|288|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nIn 1958, the Ambassador was equipped with a hydraulic lifter version of AMC's 327 CID V8 rated at {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}. Although AMC's 327 CID V8 shares its displacement with the Chevrolet small-block, AMC's 327 came out six years before Chevrolet first offered its 327 in 1962.\n\nThe Ambassador was available in a body style exclusive to its line, a pillarless [[hardtop]] '''Cross Country''' [[station wagon]]. The 1958 Ambassador was offered in a single high level trim level and came equipped with such luxury items as electric clock, twin front and rear ashtrays, Nash tradition \"deep coil\" spring suspension front and rear, split back reclining front seats that fold down into a bed, as well as upscale fabrics for the interior.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-24-25 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816085955/http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-24-25 |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nManagement had found that the public associated the Rambler name with small economy cars, and did not want the upscale nature of the new Ambassador to be so closely associated with Rambler's favorable, but economical image. Therefore, a decision was made that the larger Ambassador would be marketed as the '''Ambassador V-8 by Rambler''' in order to identify it with the Rambler name's burgeoning success, but to indicate an air of exclusivity by showing it to be a different kind of vehicle. However, the car wore \"Rambler Ambassador\" badges on its front fenders.\n\nThe 1958 Ambassador is a substantially longer car than the {{convert|108|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase [[Rambler Six]] and [[Rambler Rebel|Rebel V8]], although both lines shared the same basic body, styling, and visual cues. However, all of the Ambassador's extra {{convert|9|in|mm|spell=in}} of wheelbase (and, therefore, overall length) were added ahead of the cowl, meaning that the passenger compartment had the same volume as the smaller Ramblers. The Ambassadors came with plusher interior and exterior trims while the front end incorporated the Rebel \"V-Line\" grille from the prototype Hudson model. Through effective [[market segment]]ation, the Ambassador was [[Positioning (marketing)|positioned]] to compete with the larger models offered by other automakers.\n\nModel identification was located on the car's front fenders and deck lid. '''Super''' trim level Ambassadors featured painted side trim in a color that complemented the body color; '''Custom''' models featured a silver [[anodized aluminum]] panel on sedans and vinyl woodgrain decals on station wagons. Ambassador body styles included a four-door sedan and a [[hardtop]] sedan, a four-door pillared station wagon, and the aforementioned hardtop station wagon, a body style that first saw duty as an industry first in the 1956 [[Nash Rambler|Nash and Hudson Rambler]] line, on which all of the 1958 Ramblers were based.\n\nThe Ambassador had an excellent power-to-weight ratio for its time and provided spirited performance with [[0 to 60 mph]] (0 to 97&nbsp;km/h) times of less than 10-seconds, and low 17-second times through a quarter-mile (402&nbsp;m) [[dragstrip]]. It could be equipped with a [[limited slip differential]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-20-21 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816065829/http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-20-21 |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> as well as power brakes, power steering, power windows, and [[air conditioning]]. Numerous safety features (such as deep-dished steering wheels and padded dash boards) came standard, while lap [[seat belt]]s were optional.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-10-11 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816065347/http://oldcarbrochures.org/New-Brochures---July/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-Brochure/1958-X-Ray-Ambassador-10-11 |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== 1959 ===\nFor 1959, the Ambassador received a revised grille, side trim, and redesigned rear door skins that swept into the [[Car tailfin|tailfin]]s instead of terminating at the C-pillar. [[Scotchlite]] reflectors were also added to the rear of the tailfins to increase visibility at night. Front and rear bumpers were over 20% thicker, and featured recessed center sections to protect [[license plates]]. Adjustable headrests were now available as an option for the front seats, an industry first. [[American Motors Corporation|AMC]] touted the added comfort the headrests provided, as well as their potential for reducing [[whiplash (medicine)|whiplash]] injuries in the event of a rear-end collision. Other changes included the activation of the starter through the neutral pushbutton (on automatic transmission equipped cars), and the addition of an optional \"Powr-Saver\" engine fan, which featured a [[Fan clutch|fluid-filled clutch]] for quieter high-speed operation.\n\nThe 1959 model year also saw the addition of an optional \"Air-Coil Ride\" [[air suspension]] system, utilizing air bags installed within the rear coil springs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1959_AMC/1959_Rambler_Wagons/1959-Rambler-Wagons-05 |title=1959 Rambler Wagons brochure |publisher=oldcarbrochures.org |accessdate=23 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522175749/http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1959_AMC/1959_Rambler_Wagons/1959-Rambler-Wagons-05 |archivedate=May 22, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref> An engine-driven [[Gas compressor|compressor]], reservoir, and ride-height control valve comprised the rest of the system, but as other automakers discovered, the troublesome nature of air-suspension outweighed its benefits. [[American Motors Corporation|AMC]] discontinued the unpopular option at the end of the model year.\n\nAmbassador sales improved considerably over 1958, reaching an output of 23,769; nearly half of which were '''Custom''' four-door sedans. Much rarer was the hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were built.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Second generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image        = 1960 AMC Rambler Ambassador sedan green NJ.jpg\n| caption      = 1960 Ambassador V8 by Rambler\n| model_years  = 1960\u20131961\n| aka          = Rambler Ambassador\n| name         = Second generation\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[hardtop]] sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 4-door [[hardtop]] station wagon }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|117|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]]\n}}\n\n=== 1960 ===\n1960 saw the Ambassador lineup totally reskinned, wearing new fenders, hood, deck lid, door skins, roofline, grille, taillights, bumpers, windshield, and backlight. Significant were the lower hood line, lower windshield cowl, simplified side trim, egg crate grill, while the tailfins were reduced in height and were canted to either side making for a modern and integrated appearance. The overall effect was rather fresh, as the new roof had a lower, lighter look, to complement the lower fins and grille.\n\nAll Ambassadors came equipped with the American Motors {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]], but for the first time it was available in two versions. First was the original {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}, {{convert|360|lb\u00b7ft|N\u00b7m|abbr=on}} of torque, performance version equipped with the 4-barrel carburetor and a 9.7:1 compression ratio, which required premium fuel, and a second economy version running on regular gasoline making {{convert|250|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}, {{convert|340|lb\u00b7ft|N\u00b7m|abbr=on}} of torque, equipped with a 2-barrel carburetor and an 8.7:1 compression ratio.\n\nAmbassadors now came with a unique compound curved windshield that cut into the roof. This improved visibility, did away with the \u201cknee knocker\u201d dogleg design of AMC's first generation wrap-around windshield, and resulted in an even stiffer unitized structure. The 1960 Ambassador had a low cowl which with the compound windshield afforded excellent visibility. The Ambassador was offered in higher end Custom or entry level Super trim levels. All 1960 Ambassadors came with a new instrument cluster under a padded cowl, as well as illuminated controls for lights, wipers, fan, and defrost functions. The 1960 Ambassadors continued with an enclosed drive shaft (torque tube) and coil springs at all four corners, although the suspension was revised resulting in better handling. The top-of-the-line Ambassador models came standard with individual \"airliner\" reclining front seats that now had even more luxurious fabrics than in previous years.\n\nThe Ambassador was the only American midsize, luxury high-performance car offered in 1960. The 1960 Ambassador came in 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]], 4-door pillarless hardtop, 4-door [[station wagon]], and a 4-door pillarless ([[hardtop]]) station wagon. Equipped with the 270&nbsp;horsepower 327&nbsp;cu&nbsp;in V8, and the Borg Warner pushbutton-operated 3-speed planetary gear and torque converter automatic transmission, the Ambassadors reached {{convert|60|mph|km/h|0}} in just over 9 seconds and passed the quarter-mile in 17 seconds.\n\n=== 1961 ===\n[[File:1961 Rambler Ambassador Custom blue-fl.jpg|thumb|left|1961 Rambler Ambassador Custom]]\n[[File:1961 AMC Rambler Ambassador 4-door pink rear.JPG|thumb|right|1961 Rambler Ambassador sedan]]\n\nThe 1961 Ambassador continued the previous year's {{convert|117|in|mm|0|adj=on}} basic [[Unit body|unitized platform]], but received an unusual new front-end styling that was overseen by AMC's in-house design department headed by [[Edmund E. Anderson|Edmund Anderson]]. The new face consisted of a trapezoid grille and headlights that floated in a body-colored panel, while the front fenders arched downward and forward of the leading edge of the hood. Different from anything else on the market, AMC's marketing department promoted the look as \"European.\" While the new look was meant to distinguish the Ambassador from the lower-priced Ramblers, it was neither a consumer success nor well received in the automotive press. Overall sales fell as the entire industry was experiencing a [[recession]]. The hardtop sedan and wagon models did not return for 1961.\n\nStandard was the {{convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 with a [[Manual transmission#Synchronized transmission|synchromesh manual transmission]]. Optional was the {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} \"power pack\" version with dual exhaust system featuring new ceramic-coated [[muffler]]s guaranteed for the life of the car.<ref>{{cite journal| title=Ambassador V-8 has changed appearance|journal=Popular Mechanics |volume=114 |issue=5 |page=90 |date=November 1960 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=9tsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA88-IA1&lpg=PA88-IA1&dq=Ambassador+shows+a+considerably+face+smaller+grille+curved-down+1961 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Third generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image        = 1962 Rambler Ambassador 2-door sedan Kenosha green-f.jpg\n| caption      = 1962 Rambler Ambassador\n| model_years  = 1962\n| aka          = Rambler Ambassador\n| name         = Third generation\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 2-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|108|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]]\n}}\n\n=== 1962 ===\nBy the 1962 model year, the Ambassador's chassis was in its fifth season on the market. And while Rambler sales had been good enough for third place in industry sales (behind [[Chevrolet]] and [[Ford]]), AMC's management was working on a revolutionary and somewhat costly design set to debut for the 1963 model year. In the meantime, American Motors needed to save money, and since the Ambassador's sales had fallen in 1961, it was decided that the car would be downsized for 1962 to share its body, windshield and {{convert|108|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase with its [[Rambler Classic|Classic]] line mate. Accordingly, the car was marketed as a '''Rambler Ambassador'''.\n\nThe 1962 Ambassador received a new front end that was very similar to the 1961\u201362 Classic's, but with a crosshatch design, recessed center section, and '''Ambassador''' lettering. New, rectangular taillights were seen at the ends of restyled rear fenders, which lost their fins entirely. Exterior trim was reshuffled, and a new 2-door pillared sedan debuted. A new '400' trim line was added at the top of the line, with Super and Custom models remaining. The Ambassador offered even more luxurious interiors, perhaps to make up for the fact that it now shared its wheelbase with the Rambler Classic. The 400 could be had with vinyl [[bucket seat]]s, headrests, and color coordinated shag carpets.\n\nThe only available engine was AMC's {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} OHV V8, in either the regular fuel, 2-barrel carburetor and 8.7:1 compression ratio, {{convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} version or the premium gasoline, 4-barrel version with 9.7:1 compression ratio, {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} version. The 1962 Ambassador came with a dual chamber [[master brake cylinder]] that separated the front and rear brakes so that in the event of the failure of one chamber some braking function would remain. This design was offered by only a few cars at that time. The 1962 models were equipped with \"Walker\" (brand) flow-through mufflers. The {{convert|108|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase 1962 Ambassador was lighter than its {{convert|117|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase predecessors and when equipped with the {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8, it was a spirited performer.\n\nThe 1962, {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 Ambassador for the first time used the same {{convert|108|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase structure as did the 1957 Rambler Rebel which was also equipped with an earlier solid lifter version of the AMC 327. The 1957 Rambler Rebel equipped with a 3-speed column mounted manual transmission, was the quickest 4-door sedan made in the United States, achieving {{convert|0|to|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} [[acceleration]] in just over 7 seconds, making it faster than the Hemi [[Chrysler 300 letter series|Chrysler 300C]], the [[DeSoto Adventurer]], the Dodge D500, the Plymouth Fury, and the Chevrolet fuel-injected 283.<ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide''|title=1957-1960 Rambler Rebel |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1957-1960-rambler-rebel1.htm |date=22 August 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The 1962 Ambassador was available with a 3-speed manual transmission and being basically the same vehicle, should also reach 60&nbsp;mph about as quickly as did the 1957 Rambler Rebel.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Fourth generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1963\u20131964\n| image        = File:1963 Rambler Ambassador 880 sedan gold-white K-f.jpg\n| caption      = 1963 Rambler Ambassador 880 Sedan\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 2-door [[coupe]] (1963) | 4-door sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 2-door [[hardtop]] (1964) }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|112|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|188.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width        = {{convert|71.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height       = {{convert|55.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]]\n| name         = Fourth generation\n}}\n\n=== 1963 ===\n[[File:1963 Rambler Ambassador 990 Sedan.jpg|thumb|left|1963 Rambler Ambassador 990 Sedan]]\nIn 1962 Romney left AMC to run for [[Governor of Michigan|Governor]] of [[Michigan]], a position that he won. The automaker's new president, [[Roy Abernethy]], who was responsible for the increasing sales under Romney, reacted to the mounting competition (in 1963 AMC built as many cars as they had in 1960, but overall total car sales had increased so much that it gave AMC only sixth place in production; the same output in 1960 had put them third) in a logical way: \"Let's get rid of this Romney image.\"<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964\">{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1963-1964 AMC/Rambler Ambassador & Classic, page 1|date=21 November 2007 |publisher=HowStuffWorks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1963-1964-amc-rambler-ambassador-classic.htm |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nA completely redesigned larger Rambler lineup appeared. The new cars continued the philosophy in building smaller cars than its larger \"Big Three\" competitors that also had a high degree of interchangeability in parts to keep tooling costs and production complexity to a minimum. The company, which pioneered \"styling continuity\", introduced all-new styling for the 1963 model year Ambassadors and claimed that these were \"functional changes .... not change just for the sake of change.\"<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\">{{cite journal|url= http://www.automotive-fleet.com/channel/operations/article/story/1962/10/styling-conformity-marks-the-1963s-last-year-s-functional-changes-expanded.aspx |title=Styling Conformity Marks the 1963s; Last Year's Functional Changes Expanded |date=October 1962 |journal=Automotive Fleet |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The Ambassadors featured a {{convert|4|in|mm|0|adj=on}} longer wheelbase, but were {{convert|1.2|in|mm|0|adj=on}} shorter due to reduced front and rear body overhangs, as well as a {{convert|3|in|mm|0|adj=on}} drop in overall height.\n\nDesigned by [[Richard A. Teague]], the 1963 Ambassador's shape was much tighter, cleaner, and smoother, with almost all of its parts interchangeable between it and the new Classic.<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964_1\">{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1963-1964 AMC/Rambler Ambassador & Classic, page 2 |date=21 November 2007 |publisher=HowStuffWorks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1963-1964-amc-rambler-ambassador-classic1.htm |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> All Ambassadors used unitized structure instead of the more rattl-prone, traditional body-on-frame construction which was still the industry standard.<ref name=\"DrivingGeorgeRomney\">{{cite magazine|url= http://www.motortrend.com/classic/features/1402_driving_george_romney_1964_rambler_classic_550/mercedes_benz_sedan.html |title=Driving George Romney's 1964 Rambler Classic 550 Two-Door Sedan - Michigan Governor George Romney Stayed Humble in his 1964 Rambler |first=Richard |last=Truesdell |date=14 February 2014 |magazine=Motor Trend |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> In 1963, AMC's new {{convert|112|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} wheelbase cars (Ambassadors and Classics) used a revolutionary method of unit construction which has since been almost universally adopted by automobile manufacturers. AMC Ambassador and Classics used outerpanels stamped from single sheet metal panels which included both door frames and outer rocker panels. This resulted in an extremely rigid and rattle-free structure, better fit of doors into frames, production cost savings and reduced noise, vibration and harshness. The \"uniside\" structure was superior to the conventional production methods in which multiple smaller pieces were welded together.<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://amcrc.com/aug05feature.html |last=Isbrandt |first=Ralph H. |title=Rambler Engineering |journal=Motor Trend |date=February 1963 |publisher=AMCRC |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> There were 30% fewer parts and the result was greater structural rigidity, quieter car operation, and an overall weight reduction of about {{convert|150|lb|kg|0|abbr=off}}.<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\"/>\n\nCurved side glass and [[push-button]] door handles were new and costly upgrades, but contributed to the new Rambler's handsome, elegant, and modern Mercedes-like bodyside styling, by adding greater elegance in detail. At the time, curved side glass was used only in much more expensive luxury cars, but increased interior room and visibility, as well as reducing wind noise and improved proportions and styling of the cars.<ref name=\"DrivingGeorgeRomney\"/> The Ambassador also featured a squared-off [[Ford Thunderbird|Thunderbird]]-type roofline.<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\"/> The front end featured a forward-thrusting upper and lower ends with a vertical bar \"electric shaver\" chrome grille insert. The Ambassador's grille was differentiated from the Classic's grille by its use of the Ambassador name in script in the small horizontal bar between the upper and lower grille sections. Round quad headlights were slightly recessed in chrome bezels mounted side-by-side within the grille at its outermost edges. Overall, the new Ambassadors were described by the staff of ''Automotive Fleet'' magazine as \"probably the finest looking cars ever produced by American Motors.\"<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\"/>\n\nAmbassadors once again came in 2-door [[coupe]], 4-door sedan, and 4-door wagon body styles, but new trim lines debuted. A \"Mercedes-like three-number model designation was developed\" with the '''800''' as the Ambassador's base line (replacing the previous year's Super model) for the police, taxi, and fleet market, a '''880''' model (in place of the Custom), and the up level '''990''' trim (replacing the previous 400 models).<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964_1\"/>\n\nThe 1963 Ambassadors were offered only with the {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8, in either {{convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} 2-barrel or {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} 4-barrel versions. AMC's smaller {{convert|287|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine was only offered in the Classic line. The automatic transmission was controlled by a steering column mounted lever, replacing the previous pushbutton system. Maintenance was reduced with service intervals of the front wheel bearings increased from {{convert|12000|-|25000|mi|km|0|abbr=off}}, the recommended engine oil change was at {{convert|4000|mi|km|0|abbr=off}}, and all Ambassador models included an [[Alternator (automotive)|alternator]] and an [[Voltage regulator|electronic voltage regulator]] as standard equipment.<ref name=\"automotive-fleet-63\"/>\n\nSales were brisk, and the redesign was billed a success, with ''[[Motor Trend]]'' Magazine bestowing '''[[Motor Trend Car of the Year|Car of the Year]]''' status on the entire 1963 Rambler line, including the Ambassador. The marketing formula for the Ambassador generated record sales for the model with buyers favoring more luxury and features as evidenced by the Ambassador 990 models outselling the 880 versions by nearly 2-to-1, while the base 800 model had a total of only 43 two-door sedans built.<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964_1\"/> The automaker did not have the resources of GM, Ford, and Chrysler, nor the sales volume to spread out its new model tooling and advertising costs over large production volumes; however, Richard Teague \"turned these economical cars into smooth, streamlined beauties with tons of options and V-8 pep.\"<ref name=\"howstuffworks1963-1964\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1963-1964 AMC/Rambler Ambassador & Classic Specifications |date=21 November 2007 |publisher=HowStuffWorks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1963-1964-amc-rambler-ambassador-classic2.htm |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 1964 ===\nThe 1964 model year introduced minor trim changes and new options. The \"electric-shaver\" grille on the 1963 model was replaced with a flush-mounted design, and the engine and transmission options were widened. A two-door [[hardtop]] body style called '''990-H''' was added for the first time since 1957. Base 880 and the 880 models were dropped from the line.\n\nThe 1964 Ambassadors featured the {{convert|250|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} 2-barrel {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 as standard, with the 4-barrel {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} version as optional. The automaker did not offer a 4-speed manual transmission to compete with the sporty mid-size V8 offerings from Ford or GM. Instead, AMC offered its innovative \u201cTwin-Stick\u201d manual transmission. The \"Twin stick\" option consisted a three-speed manual transmission, operated by one of the two console mounted \"sticks\" in conjunction with an overdrive unit that was controlled by the second \"stick\" in both 2nd and 3rd gears. This gave the driver the option of using five forward gears. One magazine noted the Twin-Stick, {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} Ambassador was heading for a sub 16-second quarter-mile when they blew up the clutch.\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:1964 Ambassador 2-d white f.jpg|1964 Rambler Ambassador\nFile:1964 Ambassador 2-d white r.jpg|1964 Rambler Ambassador\nFile:1964 Ambassador 2-d white i.jpg|1964 Rambler Ambassador interior with \"Twin-Stick\" transmission\n</gallery>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Fifth generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1965\u20131966\n| image        = 1965 AMC Ambassador black 2door-HT in NJ.JPG\n| caption      = 1965 Rambler Ambassador 990 2-door hardtop\n| aka          = Rambler Ambassador<br/>AMC Ambassador\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 2-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door sedan | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 2-door [[hardtop]] | 2-door [[convertible]] }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|116|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|200|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC Straight-6 engine|I6]] | {{convert|287|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] | {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 }}\n| name         = Fifth generation\n| transmission = {{unbulleted list | 3-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 3-speed with [[Overdrive (mechanics)|overdrive]] | \"Twin-Stick\" on console (1965) | 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] (1966) | 3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] | 3-speed \u201cShift-Command\u201d on console }}\n}}\n\n=== 1965 ===\n\nNo matter how much success the new Ramblers achieved in the marketplace, Roy Abernethy was not completely satisfied. Using the experience he gained as an outstanding salesman as a guide, Abernethy closely looked at the direction that American Motors' competition was going and decided that the company would be much more successful if its products competed more directly with the Big Three. He would achieve this by pushing all AMC vehicles further upmarket among the various [[market segment]]s, shaking off the company's economy car image, and offering vehicles once again in all three major American car size classes: compact, intermediate, and full-size. The American and Classic were strong competitors in the former two segments, so for the 1965 model year, he set his sights on turning the Ambassador into a proper full-size car by stretching the Classic's wheelbase and giving it much different styling. The general sizes of automobiles at that time were based on industry standard wheelbase lengths, rather than on the vehicle's interior and cargo space. The 1965 Ambassador represented a fundamental shift in corporate ideology, a shift away from primarily fuel-efficient vehicles, to bigger, faster, and potentially more profitable cars.<ref name=\"gunn65-66\">{{cite web |last=Gunn |first=Malcolm |title=Fine Lines: 1965\u20131966 AMC Ambassador |publisher=auto123 |url= http://www.auto123.com/en/car-reviews/used/fine-lines-1965-1966-amc-ambassador?model=AMBASSADOR&artid=66071&pg=1 |date=23 July 2008 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Ambassador rode the same platform as its 1963\u201364 forebears, the 1965 models looked all-new. American Motors' designer [[Richard A. Teague]] styled the 1965 Ambassador with panache and gave the car an overall integrated look.<ref name=\"Vance65-66\">{{cite web |last=Vance |first=Bill |title=Motoring Memories: AMC Ambassador, 1965\u20131966 |publisher=Autos Canada |url= http://www.autos.ca/classic-cars/motoring-memories-amc-ambassador-1965-1966 |date=17 March 2006 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> ''[[Motor Trend]]'' magazine agreed, calling it a \"strikingly handsome automobile.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' | title=Design of the 1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador2.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Built on a {{convert|116|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase {{convert|4|in|mm|spell=in}} longer than the Classic, Teague extended the beltline level from the stacked quad headlights to the vertical taillights. The new Ambassadors were as attractive as anything built by AMC's Detroit-based competitors, and with a list price of around $3,000, few could quibble about the cost of ownership.<ref name=\"gunn65-66\"/> New disc brakes with a power brakes were optional.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/AMC/1965_AMC/1965_Rambler_Ambassador_Brochure/1965%20Rambler%20Ambassador-12.html|title=1965 Rambler Ambassador brochure |publisher=Oldcarbrochures.com |date= |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Ambassador received longer, squared-off rear fenders with vertical wrap-around taillights, taller [[decklid]], squared off rear bumper mounted low, and squarer rear wheel arches. At the front, the Ambassador again sparked minor controversy with its new vertically stacked quad headlights, which were slightly recessed in their bezels, as they flanked an all-new horizontal bar grille. This new wall-to-wall grille projected forward, horizontally, in the center, to create an effect somewhat opposite to 1963's grille treatment. The front end design provided a bold, rugged appearance.<ref name=\"Vance65-66\"/>\n\nOnce again, the Ambassador\u2019s entire extra wheelbase was ahead of the cowl, meaning that interior volume was the same as the intermediate-sized Classic. Another new body style debuted in the Ambassador lineup for 1965: an attractive new convertible offered as part of the 990 series. This was the first time a [[convertible (car)|convertible]] was offered in the Ambassador line since 1948. All Ambassador body styles (except the 990-H coupe) offered seating for six passengers, with coupes and convertibles having the option of buckets seats with center console and floor shifter. The Ambassador 990-H was an up-scale two-door hardtop model, available only in 5-passenger form.\n[[File:1965 Ambassador 990 convertible yellow pb-rr.jpg|thumb|left|1965 Ambassador 990 convertible]]\nAmbassadors also saw an expanded list of trim lines, convenience options, and engine choices. The 990 and 990-H models were back, while 880 models were the new economy leaders in the 1965 Ambassador line, but even the $2,512 price for the two-door sedan was not attractive compared to the models with better trim, buckets seats, and special interiors.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador: Creating the early Rambler Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador1.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Ambassadors came standard with AMC's new {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC Straight-6 engine|Inline-6 engine]], which was the first time since 1956 that an Ambassador was available with six cylinders. Far more popular in the Ambassador, however, were the two time-tested {{convert|287|and|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine]]s.<ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador: The 1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador's amenities |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url = http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador3.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Motors' management decided that the Ambassador could once again accept a standard six-cylinder engine, since its full-size competitors (e. g. [[Chevrolet|Bel Air]] and [[Chevrolet Impala|Impala]], Ford Custom 500 and [[Ford Galaxie|Galaxie]], as well as [[Plymouth Fury]]) came with six-cylinder engines as standard equipment. They therefore appealed to a wider range of customers than the Ambassador was getting. Also, since the Classic was now smaller and styled differently, the Ambassador [[Straight-6|six-cylinder]] would not threaten to cannibalize Classic 6 sales, which were the company's sales volume leaders. The changes were on target as sales of the repositioned Ambassador more than tripled.\n\n''Motor Trend'' magazine tested an Ambassador convertible with a Twin-Stick overdrive transmission and found it commendably economical, averaging {{convert|16.4|mpgus|L/100 km mpgimp|abbr=on}} over {{convert|1000|mi}} run, and noting that ... \"Traveling comfort was the Ambassador's biggest selling point, along with its exceptionally powerful [[Bendix Corporation|Bendix]] duo-servo drum brakes ...With the thin bucket seats that recline, driver and passengers can enjoy a high degree of riding comfort... Many passers-by commented on the car's good looks... Our summary: a nice, comfortable, quiet, well built family automobile that rather neglects the performance market.\"<ref name=page4>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador4.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n=== 1966 ===\n[[File:1966 AMC Ambassador DPL NJ-show.jpg|thumb|1966 hardtops featured a formal roof design \u2013 DPL model]]\n[[File:1966 AMC Ambassador red convertible in MD.JPG|thumb|1966 AMC Ambassador 990 convertible]]\n[[File:1966 Ambassador 990 wagon azrr.jpg|thumb|1966 Ambassador 990 Cross Country wagon]]\n\nFor 1966, minor changes greeted the Ambassador range. The V-shaped horizontal louver spanned unbroken between the headlamps and the effect was continued with twin rectangular trim pieces attached to the side of the front fenders at their leading edges by the headlamps. The effect was repeated in the new vertical wraparound taillamps with the top-line models receiving a twin set of horizontal ribbed moldings across the back of the trunk lid that simulated the look of the front grille. Hardtop coupes received a redesigned roofline that was angular in appearance with an angle cut rear side windows and rectangular rear window. The backlight no longer curved and wrapped slightly around the C-pillars. The changes made for a more \"formal\" [[notchback]] look that was popular at the time.\n\nStation wagons also received a new roof (that did not have as pronounced dip over the rear cargo area) as well as a redesigned tailgate and optional [[Woodie (car body style)#Simulated woodgrain|simulated woodgrain]] exterior side panels. Available with two-rows of seats with a standard bottom hinged tailgate with electric, fully retracting rear window or with an optional rear-facing third row that featured a left side hinged rear door, with a regular exterior door handle on the right side. All station wagons carried a '''Cross Country''' badge.\n\nThe 880 served as the base model line. The two-door sedan was the price leader at $2,404, but finished with the least sales for the model year.<ref name=\"stuff-performance\">{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1965\u20131966 Rambler Ambassador Performance Statistics |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1966-rambler-ambassador5.htm |date=23 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The more popular and better trimmed 990 models were available in sedan, wagon, hardtop, and convertible versions.<ref name=\"stuff-performance\"/> Options included a vinyl roof, wire wheel covers, AM/FM radio, adjustable steering wheel, and cruise control. A new luxury '''DPL''' (short for \"Diplomat\"<ref name=page4/>) two-door hardtop debuted at the top of the range.\n\nThe DPL included special lower body side trim, numerous standard convenience items such as reclining [[bucket seat]]s upholstered in brocade fabrics or optional vinyl. An optional interior trim featured [[houndstooth]] fabric and included two throw pillows. The DPL model was aimed to compete with the new, more upscale trimmed [[Plymouth Fury|Plymouth VIP]], [[Ford LTD (North America)|Ford LTD]], [[Chevrolet Caprice]] and [[Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme]].<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=4SUDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=Caprice+LTD+VIP+DPL |page=79 |title=The 1966 cars |journal=Popular Science |first=Jan P. |last=Norbye |date=October 1965 |volume=187 |issue=4 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} I6, as well as the {{convert|287|and|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8s remained in the line, but transmission selections now included a new console mounted four-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]. Most Ambassadors continued to be ordered with [[automatic transmission]]s.\n\n''Motor Trend'' magazine tested a 1966 DPL equipped with a 327 engine that \"definitely has snap we hadn't felt before\" and even with an automatic transmission experienced \"healthy wheelspin from both rear wheels [because of the Twin-Grip limited slip differential]... Subtle changes in this year's suspension, which include longer shocks and different springs, have a pronounced effect on the way the car feels and handles. Most welcome is the improved steering response. The car has a new feet-on-the-ground feeling, and body lean seems to have been reduced. The ride remains very good... As before, the interior's the outstanding feature of the Ambassador. Its quality is such that other luxury cars, even higher priced ones, could well imitate it...\"<ref name=page4/>\n\nPerhaps the biggest change, however, was that the Ambassador lost its historic Rambler nameplate, as the car was now marketed as the \"American Motors Ambassador\" or \"AMC Ambassador\". Abernethy was again responsible for this marketing move, as he attempted to move the stylish new Ambassador even further upmarket. To him, that meant that the Rambler name, and its economy car image would be eschewed to give the car a clean slate in a market that was turning away from economy and toward V8 performance. The evidence suggests that Abernethy was on the right track with moving the Ambassador upscale to compete with other manufacturers' luxury models as sales of the AMC's flagship jumped from 18,647 in 1964 to over 64,000 in 1965, and then in 1966 they went to more than 71,000.<ref name=\"Vance65-66\"/> Although the Ambassador accounted for a mere fraction of total passenger car sales in the U.S., it was an important step in bringing the AMC's products in line with what the consumer of the day wanted.<ref name=\"gunn65-66\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Sixth generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1967\u20131968\n| image        = 1967 Ambassador DPL conv top-up-winter-WV.jpg\n| caption      = 1967 AMC Ambassador DPL convertible\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 2-door [[sedan (automobile)]] (1967 only) | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 2-door [[hardtop]] [[coup\u00e9|coupe]] | 2-door [[convertible]] (1967 only) }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|118|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|202.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC Straight-6 engine|I6]] | {{convert|290|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] | {{convert|343|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 }}\n| transmission = {{unbulleted list | 3-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 3-speed with [[Overdrive (mechanics)|overdrive]] | 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 3-speed [[BorgWarner]] [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] | 3-speed \u201cShift-Command\u201d on center floor console }}\n| name         = Sixth generation\n}}\n\n=== 1967 ===\nAmerican Motors introduced a completely restyled longer, lower, and wider Ambassador for the 1967 model year, now riding on a {{convert|118|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase, or {{convert|2|in|mm|spell=in}} longer than before. The Ambassador's platform was {{convert|4|in|mm|spell=in}} longer than the new [[AMC Rebel|Rambler Rebel's]] {{convert|114|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase. The Ambassador was positioned in the standard-size category, against traditional big cars such as [[Ford Galaxie]], [[Chevrolet Impala]], and [[Plymouth Fury]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador1.htm|title=1967\u20131968 AMC Ambassador|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |date=11 October 2007 |publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The convertible was offered again\u2014this time in DPL trim\u2014for 1967; but it would be the final year with only 1,260 built. It featured an all new \"split stack\" folding mechanism with concealed side rails that did not intrude into the backseat area, thus offering room for three adult passengers in the rear.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967_AMC_Data_Book/1967-AMC-Data-Book-048 |title=1967 AMC Data Book |page=48 |publisher=oldcarbrochures.org |accessdate=23 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140427010415/http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967_AMC_Data_Book/1967-AMC-Data-Book-048 |archivedate=April 27, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe car once again looked completely new, with a more rounded appearance that sported sweeping rooflines, \"[[Coke bottle styling|coke-bottle]]\" fenders, greater glass area, and a recessed grille that bowed forward less than that of the 1965\u201366 models. Taillights were wider, rectangular, and divided by one central vertical bar. ''Motor Trend'' magazine described the all-new styling of the new Ambassador as \u201cattractive\u201d and \u201cmore graceful and easier on the eye in \u201967.\u201d<ref name=\"full\">{{cite journal |title=Full-Size American Motors |journal=Motor Trend |date=November 1966 |page=90 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:1967 Ambassador 990 4-d aqua pa-i.jpg|thumb|left|1967 Ambassador 990 standard interior]]\n[[File:1967 AMC Ambassador DPL yellow.JPG|thumb|left|1967 Ambassador DPL hardtop with satin chrome trim]]\nThe 880 two-door sedans featured the identical roofline as the [[hardtop]]s, but had slim [[Pillar (car)|B-pillars]] that gave them a more open-air coupe appearance and were marketed as \"Sports Sedans.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=1967 Ambassador brochure |url= http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967%20Ambassador%20Brochure/image11.html |website=Old Car Brochures |accessdate=4 November 2019 |page=11}}</ref> The 880 was also available in 4-door sedan and station wagon version, but more popular were the better equipped and more upscale 990 models in 4-door sedan, station wagon, and 2-door hardtop body styles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Car of the Week: 1967 AMC Ambassador convertible |url=https://www.oldcarsweekly.com/collector-cars/60s-cars/car-of-the-week-1967-amc-ambassador-convertible |publisher=Old Cars Weekly |date=21 December 2010 |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> Adding more elegance to DPL two-door hardtops and convertibles was an optional was a \"Satin-Chrome\" finish (paint code P-42) for the lower body side replacing the standard full-length stainless steel rocker moldings. A black or white vinyl cover was optional on 990 and DPL sedans and hardtops. The 990 '''Cross Country''' station wagons were available with [[3M]]'s \"dinoc\" simulated wood-grain body side panels trimmed in a slim stainless steel frame.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967_AMC_Data_Book/1967-AMC-Data-Book-073 |title=1967 AMC Data Book |page=73 |publisher=oldcarbrochures.org |accessdate=23 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114344/http://oldcarbrochures.org/NA/AMC/1967_AMC/1967_AMC_Data_Book/1967-AMC-Data-Book-073 |archivedate=August 26, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[fastback]] [[AMC Marlin|Marlin]] two-door [[hardtop]] that was previously built on the Rambler Classic platform in 1965 and 1966, was continued for 1967, but was now based on the larger Ambassador platform.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=McCourt |first=Mark J. |title=1967 AMC Marlin |url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/article/1967-amc-marlin-2/ |magazine=Hemmings Motor News |date=July 2013 |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> It featured the Ambassador's front end, longer hood, and luxury appointments with an even longer fastback roofline than the previous version.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strohl |first1=Daniel |title=Trawling for Success \u2013 1967 AMC Marlin |url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/article/trawling-for-success-1967-amc-marlin/ |publisher=Hemmings Classic Car |date=August 2007 |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe full-sized Ambassador featured a lengthy list of standard features and options.<ref>{{cite web |last=Litwin |first=Matthew |title=1967 AMC Ambassador DPL |url= https://www.hemmings.com/blog/article/1967-amc-ambassador-dpl/ |website=www.hemmings.com |publisher=Hemmings Motor News |date=January 2008 |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> The interiors \"rival more expensive cars for luxury and quality, yet are durable enough to take years of normal wear.\"<ref name=\"full\" /> The premium materials and fittings included wood-grain trim, and even an optional \"Custom\" package with special upholstery and two matching pillows. Ambassador DPL hardtops included reclining [[bucket seat]]s with a center armrest between them (with a center cushion for a third occupant or a floor console with gear selector), as well as a foldaway center armrest for the rear seat. The new safety-oriented instrument panel grouped all gauges and controls in front of the driver, with the rest of the [[dashboard]] pushed forward and away from the passengers. Focusing on safety, there were now no protruding knobs, the steering column was designed to collapse under impact, and the steering wheel was smaller than previous Ambassadors.<ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1967 AMC Ambassador Styling |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador2.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe long-lived \"GEN-1\" family of [[AMC V8 engine]]s was replaced by an all-new line of {{convert|290|and|343|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} engines that debuted for 1966 in the [[Rambler American]]. These V8s were an all-new design featuring thin-wall-casting block, heads, and manifold.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sessler |first=Peter C. |title=Ultimate American V-8 Engine Data Book, 2nd Edition |date=2010 |publisher=MotorBooks International |isbn=9781610592321 |page=227 |edition=Second |chapter-url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eT7LT69STO0C&pg=PA227 |accessdate=4 November 2019 |chapter=24}}</ref> With a 4-barrel [[carburetor]] and dual exhaust, the 343&nbsp;V8 produced {{convert|280|bhp|abbr=on}} at 4800 rpm and {{convert|365|lb.ft|N\u00b7m|0}} of torque at 3000 rpm. The old [[torque tube]] design was eliminated by a new four-link, trailing-arm rear suspension system providing a more comfortable [[coil spring]] ride.<ref>{{cite web|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' | title=1967 AMC Ambassador Engineering |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador3.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Motors promoted the new 1967 Ambassador as an \"uncompromising automobile with the [[red carpet]] ride\" in print advertisements,<ref>{{cite journal|author=American Motors|title=Ambassador, The Red Carpet Ride|journal=Life|date=February 10, 1967|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eFYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA57&dq=uncompromising+automobile+with+the+red+carpet+ride&q |page=57 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> as well as in an innovative TV commercial.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ross |first=Wallace A. |title=Best TV Commercials of the Year, Volume 2 |publisher=Hastings House |year=1967 |page=13 }}</ref> Unfortunately, sales of the redesigned models were disappointing, due to customer confusion caused by the entire company's abrupt upmarket push, which seemed uncomfortably \"me too\" to the traditional domestic [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three]]'s customers, and they also alienated American Motors' loyal buyer base. Abernethy's ideas of entering new markets were not working.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' | title=1967\u20131968 AMC Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> These strategy changes resulted in a new round of financial problems for American Motors. Because of this, Abernathy was released from AMC by its board of directors later that year, and was replaced by William V. Luneberg and [[Roy D. Chapin, Jr.]]\n\n=== 1968 ===\n[[File:1968 Ambassador SST 4-d green pa-s.jpg|thumb|right|1968 AMC Ambassador SST sedan]]\n[[File:1968 AMC Ambassador yellow 2-door.jpg|thumb|right|1968 AMC Ambassador hardtop coupel]]\n\nFor the 1968 model year, a new SST trim line was placed above the now mid-line DPL trim for the Ambassador. American Motors was a pioneer in the field of [[air conditioning]] through its Kelvinator refrigerator division, and AMC's marketing chief Bill McNealy wanted to make the Ambassador stand out in a crowded market segment and decided to add greater distinction to the Ambassador line by making the [[Weather Eye#All-Weather Eye|All Weather]] [[Automobile air conditioning|A/C system]] as standard equipment.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=_Vb0AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=marketing+chief+Bill+McNealy+was+searching+for+a+way+to+make+Ambassador+stand+out+in+a+crowded+market |page=99 |title=American Motors Corporation: the rise and fall of America's last independent automaker |first=Patrick R. |last=Foster |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2013 |accessdate=3 November 2014|isbn=9781610588584 }}</ref> This was the first time any volume car manufacturer had done so, something that even [[Cadillac]] and [[Lincoln (automobile)|Lincoln]] had not offered on their luxury cars \u2013 although some of them were priced at more than twice as much as Ambassador. While all Ambassadors came with air conditioning as standard, consumers could order the car without air as a \"delete option\" and decrease the price by $218.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=VAcEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25&dq=1968+Ambassador+air+conditioning+standard |page=25 |title=The 1968 cars |journal=Changing Times - Kiplinger's Personal Finance |date=December 1967 |volume=21 |issue=12 |accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> As AMC pointed out in their advertising campaign for the Ambassador, the only other major automaker that offered air conditioning as standard equipment in 1968 was [[Rolls-Royce (car)|Rolls-Royce]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z0ReBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA221&lpg=PA221&dq=1968,+American+Motors+rocked+the+industry+by+offering+air+conditioning+as+standard+equipment+on+its+Ambassador |page=221 |title=Cool: how air conditioning changed everything |first=Salvatore |last=Basile |publisher=Fordham University Press |year=2014 |isbn=9780823261765 |quote= 1968, American Motors rocked the industry by offering air conditioning as standard equipment on its Ambassador... |accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nDue to slow sales, both the convertible and the pillared coupe models were dropped from the line, leaving the 990 hardtop coupe and sedan, DPL hardtop coupe, sedan, and wagon, and new '''SST''' hardtop coupe and sedan in the Ambassador line. The [[Personal luxury car|personal luxury]] fastback Marlin was also discontinued to make way for the smaller new [[AMC Javelin]] in the [[pony car]] segment. The top-of-the line 1968 Ambassador SST version was \"especially appealing\" and \"a very luxurious package\" with standard V8 power, air conditioning, expensive upholstery, individual reclining front seats, wood-look interior trim, upgraded exterior trim, as well as numerous conveniences such as an electric clock and a headlights-on buzzer.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1968 AMC Ambassador |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador5.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:1968 AMC Ambassador DPL station wagon FL-fl.jpg|thumb|left|1968 AMC Ambassador DPL wagon]]\nStyling changes were minor. Taillights were now recessed in body-color bezels that were divided by a single central horizontal bar. Front headlight bezels were now made of nylon and similarly body colored.<ref name=\"ps-october67\">{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1SoDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA118&lpg=PA118&dq=What's+new+at+American+Motors+outside+door+handles |page=118 |title=What's new at American Motors |journal=Popular Science |date=October 1967 |volume=191 |issue=4 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> A new injection molded ABS plastic grille was dominated by a horizontal bar that extended forward in the center from the sides, while its outline had squared off edges that wrapped forward into the inner headlight extensions.<ref name=\"ps-october67\"/> Fender-mounted marker lights were added at the front and rear as standard equipment, as the U.S. [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA) regulations mandated their application (along with seat belts beginning January 1, 1968) to all passenger cars sold in the United States for 1968.\n\nHowever, AMC's most enduring styling feature debuted on the Ambassador for 1968, as flush-mounted paddle-style door handles replaced the former push-button units on all American Motors cars, save the [[Rambler American]].<ref name=\"ps-october67\"/> The practical and \"disarmingly simple design\" predated safety-related mandates and industry norms.<ref name=\"paddling\">{{cite magazine|url= http://www.hemmings.com/hmn/stories/2010/07/01/hmn_feature21.html |title=Paddling for Life Itself - a timeless American Motors part that outlasted its maker |magazine=Hemmings Motor News |date=July 2010 |first=Jim |last=Donnelly |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The interior locking was no longer by the traditional windowsill pushbutton, but a lever set into the armrest.<ref name=\"paddling\"/>\n\nFront-wheel alignment was made easier with and with greater accuracy by moving the camber adjustment from the upper to the lower control arm on the [[double wishbone suspension]], and the [[caster angle]] adjustments also moved from the upper control arm to the drag strut. At midyear, AMC's new top engine, the [[AMC AMX|AMX]] {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} {{convert|315|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] became an option in the Ambassador line, bringing the total engine options up to four.\n\nIn June 1967, American Motors started a new advertising campaign created by [[Mary Wells Lawrence]] of Wells, Rich, and Greene marketing agency. The US$12 million AMC account was high-profile assignment and helped established the agency as innovative and daring in its approach.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Irreverence at American | journal=Time |date=22 November 1967 |url= http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,837337,00.html |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The new advertising violated the convention of not attacking the competition, and AMC's campaigns became highly controversial.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Belliveau |first=Nancy | title=Sledge-hammer Sell |journal=Life |date=27 October 1967 |pages=104\u2013106 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SEkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA101&dq=AMC+Wells,+Rich,+and+Greene |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The publicity worked with AMC's total retail sales improving 13% for the fiscal year, but 1968 Ambassador numbers were slightly down.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1967\u20131968 AMC Ambassador Specifications |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1968-amc-ambassador6.htm |date=11 October 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Seventh generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1969\u20131973\n| image        = 1969 AMC Ambassador SST sedan green-e.jpg\n| caption      = 1969 AMC Ambassador SST 4-door sedan\n| class        = [[Full-size car|Full-size]]\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[station wagon]] | 2-door hardtop [[coupe]] }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|122|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|206.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} (1969) | {{convert|208|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} (1970) | {{convert|210.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} (1971\u201372) | {{convert|212.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} (1973) }}\n| engine       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|232|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[Straight-six engine|I6]] | {{convert|258|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} I6 | {{convert|290|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] | {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|343|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 }}\n| name         = Seventh generation\n| aka          = {{unbulleted list | American Motors Ambassador <ref name=\"1970_brochure\"/> | Rambler Ambassador <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/American-Motors-Rambler-Rebel-Ambassador-1970-UK-Market-Sales-Brochure-/181058740695?pt%3DUK_CarParts_Vehicles_Manuals_Litterature_ET%26hash%3Ditem2a27f121d7 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6SNNzBa3m?url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/American-Motors-Rambler-Rebel-Ambassador-1970-UK-Market-Sales-Brochure-/181058740695?pt=UK_CarParts_Vehicles_Manuals_Litterature_ET&hash=item2a27f121d7 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 6, 2014 |title=Rambler Rebel & Ambassador 1970 UK Market Sales Brochure |publisher=ebay.com |accessdate=15 September 2014 }}</ref> }}\n}}\n\n=== 1969 ===\n[[File:AMC Ambassador Hardtop ca 1969 in Vlaams-Brabant.JPG|thumb|left|1969 Ambassador hardtop in Belgium]]\n[[File:1969 AMC Ambassador SST sedan green-i.jpg|thumb|left|1969 Ambassador sedan standard interior]]\n\nIn 1969, the Ambassador received a major restyling, with a {{convert|4|in|0|adj=on}} gain in overall length and wheelbase. The {{convert|122|in|0|adj=on}} wheelbase was accompanied by an increase in front and rear track from {{convert|58.5|to|60|in|mm|0|}}.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=G9QDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=Styling+changes+fore+and+aft+mark+the+new+Ambassador |pages=99 & 101 |title=Family cars: the '69 cars |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=October 1968 |volume=130 |issue=4 |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The front end appearance was revised with new quad headlight clusters mounted horizontally in a new molded plastic grille. The grille itself was blackout with a chrome horizontal bar that connected the headlight clusters. The hood was redesigned to accommodate the grille's raised center portion, and it faintly recalled [[Packard|Packard's]] classic grille/hood combination. [[Richard A. Teague]], AMC's Vice President of Styling, had worked at the luxury car manufacturer before joining AMC. Parking lights were rectangular and mounted horizontally in recessed wells in the front bumper, just beneath each set of headlights. The entire front fascia leaned forward slightly to lend an air of forward motion to the car's appearance.\n\nAt the rear, ribbed rectangular taillights were mounted inboard the Ambassadors rearward-thrusting rear fenders. Square ribbed marker lights of similar height were mounted at the trailing edge of each fender side. The deck lid had a slightly higher lift over. The base and DPL models had no decorative panel connecting the taillights while the top-line SST versions featured a panel painted red to match the taillights. Station wagons saw vertical wraparound taillights replacing the previous \"hooded\" units, which were not visible from the side. The 1969 AMC Ambassador was a smooth, powerful, well-proportioned sedan that did not look like anything else on the road.<ref>{{cite web |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |title=1967, 1968, 1969 AMC Ambassador Specifications \u2013 page 2 |publisher=howstuffworks.com |url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1969-amc-ambassador2.htm |date=26 November 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe interiors were upgraded and a new deeply hooded dashboard clustered instruments and controls in front of the driver. There was an increased emphasis on luxury-type trim and features. The base model two-door hardtop was dropped for 1969.\n\nThe 1969 Ambassador stressed luxury, with the marketing tagline developed by [[Mary Wells Lawrence]] at the Wells Rich Greene agency, tying the car's value, \"It will remind you of the days when money really bought something.\"<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CyBFAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA102&dq=1969+Ambassador+It+will+remind+you+of+the+days+when+money+really+bought+something |page=102 |title=American Motors Corporation: The Rise and Fall of America's Last Independent |first=Patrick R. |last=Foster |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2013 |isbn=9780760344255 |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The combination of rich velour upholstery, individually adjustable reclining seats, standard air conditioning, and the longer wheelbase were highlighted in advertisements with Ambassador's posh\"[[limousine]]\" ride at an economical price. One aspect of this new advertising theme included many AMC dealers inviting prospective customers to call and request a \"demonstration ride\", in which a uniformed chauffeur would arrive at the prospect's home and drive them around in an Ambassador SST sedan. AMC's efforts worked, and Ambassador sales shot up again.\n\n[[File:1969 AMC Ambassador limousine in Wisconsin sideR.JPG|thumb|left|1969 Ambassador Royale Stretch Limo by Armbruster/Stageway. Car wears Ambassador SST trim.]]\nNot only did AMC promote the 1969 Ambassador as having a \"limousine\" ride and deluxe appointments, but Chicago [[Vehicle leasing|auto leasing]] executive, Robert Estes, had the Armbruster/Stageway Company<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.coachbuilt.com/bui/a/armbruster/armbruster.htm |last=Theobald |first=Mark|title=Armbruster & Co.; Armbruster / Stageway |publisher=Coachbuilt.com |year=2004 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> convert Ambassadors into real {{convert|24|ft|m|adj=on}} limousines riding on a {{convert|158|in|mm|0|adj=on}} wheelbase. Known as the '''Royale Stretch Limo''', one was owned by the State of [[Wisconsin]] as the official vehicle for Governor [[Warren Knowles]]. The conversions were unusual in that they did not keep the stock rear doors\u2014as is typical in most limos. The back doors were welded shut and the Ambassadors were lengthened by inserting a section just behind the original [[Pillar (car)|B-pillar]] that had an entirely new central door in this center making a large opening for entry and egress. {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on|spell=In}} steel \"I-beams\" bridge the expanse created by stretch. Power comes from the \"[[AMC AMX|AMX]]\" {{convert|315|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine backed with the BorgWarner automatic transmission and a \"Twin-Grip\" [[limited-slip differential]] with 3.15 gears.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Strohl |first=Daniel |title=1969 AMC Ambassador Limousine |journal=Hemmings Classic Car |url= http://www.hemmings.com/hcc/stories/2008/10/01/hmn_feature15.html |date=October 2008 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom their experience with supplying the U.S Postal Service with over 3700 right-hand drive Ambassadors in 1968, American Motors thereafter exported fully assembled RHD Ambassadors from the United States to right-hand drive foreign markets, including the United Kingdom, Australia, and New Zealand.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== 1970 ===\n[[File:1970 AMC Ambassador SST hardtop yellow-black K-s.jpg|thumb|1970 Ambassador SST 2-door hardtop]]\nFor the 1970 model year, the rear half of Ambassador hardtop coupes and sedans was treated to an overhaul that was also shared by the intermediate 1970 [[AMC Rebel]]. On hardtop coupes, this restyling resulted in a sloping roofline that saw upswept reverse-angle quarter windows. The belt line kicked up at the point the hardtop's rear windows swept upward, and tapered back to the fender end, meeting a new loop-type rear bumper.\n\nOn sedans, the roof line showed a slimmer C-pillar, squared-off rear door windows, and met a belt line that kicked up beneath the trailing edge of each rear door window. The belt line tapered back to the same rear fascia as the hardtop coupe's. This rear fascia contained a new ribbed taillight lens that stretched wall-to-wall and included twin square white reverse light lenses in its center.\n\nStation wagons received no change to their rooflines, doors, and rear fascias. However, all Ambassadors received a new extruded aluminum grille at the front, featuring several widely spaced bright horizontal bars with one wide, body colored horizontal grille bar extending to each headlight cluster. The {{convert|290|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 was replaced for 1970 by a new {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine. This {{convert|210|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 4400 rpm and {{convert|305|lb.ft|N\u00b7m|0}} of torque at 2800 rpm was the standard engine on all DPL and SST models. The {{convert|343|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 was also supplanted by a {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} engine available in either 2-barrel, regular gasoline, or high-output, 4-barrel, premium fuel versions. The 4-barrel \"AMX\" {{convert|390|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine was optional, producing {{convert|325|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 3200 rpm and {{convert|420|lb.ft|N\u00b7m|0}} of torque at 3200 rpm.\n\n=== 1971 ===\n[[File:1971 AMC Ambassador 2-door hardtop coupe.JPG|thumb|left|1971 Ambassador hardtop with TurboCast II wheels from 1979\u201383]]\n[[File:1971 AMC Ambassador station wagon red with woodgrain side panels.JPG|thumb|left|1971 Ambassador station wagon]]\n\nFollowing the previous year's redesign, the 1971 Ambassadors received only minor changes and improvements. The marketing tag line for the year was the [[Underdog (competition)|underdog]] asking, \"If you had to compete with GM, Ford and Chrysler, what would you do?\"\u2014that was answered by AMC including more features, advantages, and benefits for buyers of its cars compared to the models from its much larger competitors. This was reflected by shuffling the Ambassador models for 1971 and by including more equipment in the standard feature list. The previously nameless base models were dropped, as the sedan-only DPL trim line was relegated to base model status, and a new top-line '''Brougham''' trim line was added above mid-line SST models. Both SST and Brougham models came as hardtop coupes, sedans, and wagons.\n\nThe DPL came with AMC's new {{convert|258|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} {{convert|150|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} Inline-6 with seven main bearings. All the SSTs and Broughams featured the {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine with {{convert|210|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} as standard. BorgWarner's \"Shift-Command\" automatic transmissions were standard equipment across the line. Two of AMC's {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} were optional; an 8.5:1 compression version with a two-barrel carburetor or a high-compression four-barrel V8 that required premium-fuel. The previous \"AMX 390\" V8 gave way to a new {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} {{convert|335|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} V8 as the top engine option.\n\nStyling changes consisted of a new fascia up front. It featured headlights contained in their own chrome pods separate from, but flanking the new grille with a bright rectangular surround, with rounded edges. The \"natural\" cast [[pot metal]] grille insert was recessed and featured a bright vertical bar pattern. A second set of parking lights was added outboard of the headlight clusters, and they were integrated into the fender extension to eliminate the need for separate front marker lights.\n\nTaillights on hardtop coupes and sedans still ran wall-to-wall, but the twin backup lights were moved from the center to further outboard\u2014approximately eight inches in from either fender side. Once again, the wagon received few changes at the rear, but added a new design for its optional woodgrain side trim, which filled in its upper bodysides. Its lower edge flowed downward aft of its peak at the leading edge above each front wheelhouse, in similar fashion to the [[Buick Skylark]]'s side \"sweepspear\" styling cue.\n\nAmbassador base models were offered to fleet buyers with various police, [[taxicab]], and other heavy-duty packages. Governments and police departments in the U.S. historically used standard-size, low-price line four-door sedans. Equipped with the 360 or 401<ref>{{cite web |last=Missouri State Highway Patrol |title=History of the Motor Equipment Division |year=2006 |url= http://www.mshp.dps.mo.gov/MSHPWeb/PatrolDivisions/MED/documents/HistoryofMED.pdf |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527114129/http://www.mshp.dps.mo.gov/MSHPWeb/PatrolDivisions/MED/documents/HistoryofMED.pdf |archivedate=May 27, 2010 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://greenfieldpolice.org/Patrol/Fleet/1971_Squad/1971_squad.html |title=1971 Greenfield Police patrol Ambassador |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20040704215728/http://www.greenfieldpolice.org/Patrol/Fleet/1971_Squad/1971_squad.html |archivedate=July 4, 2004 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> engines, the base Ambassadors saw use as [[Police vehicles in the United States and Canada|police cruisers]] and support vehicles.\n\n=== 1972 ===\n[[File:1972 AMC Ambassador Brougham sedan in burgundy at 2015 AMO meet-2.jpg|thumb|right|1972 Ambassador Brougham sedan]]\nMinor changes greeted 1972 Ambassadors, as AMC's biggest news for the year was the addition of the innovative '''AMC Buyer Protection Plan''', that included the industry's first 12-month or {{convert|12000|mi|km|adj=on}} bumper-to-bumper [[warranty]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Boone |first=Louis E. |last2=Kurtz |first2=David L. |title=Contemporary Business |publisher=Dryden Press |year=1976 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/contemporarybusi0000boon_h9i8/page/223 223\u2013224] |isbn=978-0-03-013651-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarybusi0000boon_h9i8/page/223 }}</ref> This was the first time an automaker promised to repair anything wrong with the car (except for [[tire]]s) and owners were provided with a [[toll-free telephone number]] to the company, as well as a free loaner car if a warranty repair took overnight. This backing also included mechanical upgrades to increase durability and quality, such as the standardization of electric windshield wipers on all model lines, replacing AMC's vacuum-powered units, as well as better interior trims. By focusing on quality, the smallest domestic automaker was profitable for 1972, earning US$30.2 million (the highest net profit achieved by AMC since 1964) on $4 billion in sales.\n\nThe base Ambassador DPL model was canceled, with three body styles now available in SST and Brougham trim. Fleet purchasers could order plain Ambassadors in Police Pursuit Vehicle (PPV) or Special Service Package (SSP) versions. A six-cylinder engine was no longer available; thus, Ambassador became a V8-only car for the first time since 1964. This made the Ambassador the only volume-produced American car that included air conditioning, power brakes, automatic transmission, and a V8 engine as standard equipment; all while being priced less than the Big Three's full-sized cars.<ref name=\"1972AMCphotos\">{{cite web|url= http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/AMC/1972_AMC/1972_Ambassador_Promo/1972%20Ambassador%20Promo-01.html |title=1972 AMC Ambassador press photos |date=1 September 1971 |work=The Old Car Manual Project |accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> The base engine was the {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} with two {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} or a {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} versions optional. The engines were designed to operate on regular grade, low-lead, or unleaded gasolines.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/AMC/1972_AMC/1972%20AMC%20Full%20Line%20Brochure/image13.html |title=1972 AMC Full Line brochure |page=25 |work=The Old Car Manual Project |accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> All were based on the engine designs responsible for AMC winning the 1971\u20131972 Trans-Am Series.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=eT7LT69STO0C&pg=PA227&lpg=PA227&dq=That+basic+engine,+which+was+responsible+for+AMC+winning+the+1971\u20131972+Trans-Am+Series,+became+the+backbone+of |page=227 |title=Ultimate American V-8 Engine Data Book |edition=Second |first=Peter C. |last=Sessler |year=2010 |publisher=MBI Publishing |isbn=978-0-7603-3681-6 |accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> The Borg-Warner transmission was replaced by the \"Torque-Command\" ([[TorqueFlite]]) three-speed automatic sourced from [[Chrysler]].\n\nStyling changes on the 1972 Ambassador were limited to a new crosshatch [[Casting (metalworking)|cast metal]] grille with bright trim and new integrated fender extension mounted side marker lamps on the front. Brougham station wagons included a roof rack, rear air deflector, as well as 3M \"dinoc\" woodgrain trim on body sides and tailgate.<ref name=\"1972AMCphotos\"/>\n\nA ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'' magazine survey after driving a total of {{convert|1000000|mi|km|0}} found Ambassador owners were pleased with their cars, describing them to be \"very comfortable to drive and ride in\" with handling listed as a top \"specific like\" by half of the drivers.<ref name=\"1972amb\">{{cite journal| last=Lamm |first=Michael |title=American Motors' Guaranteed Car |journal=Popular Mechanics |pages=94\u2013194 |date=May 1972 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=StQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA94&dq=1972+AMC+Ambassador&q=1972%20AMC%20Ambassador |volume=137 |issue=5 |accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> A very high percentage (92%) would buy one again.<ref name=\"1972amb\"/> Although the Buyer Protection Plan was listed by only 8.5% as a reason to buy an Ambassador, owners valued the smaller AMC dealers that \"had more time to be courteous and to pay personal attention to customers.\"<ref name=\"1972amb\"/>\n\n=== 1973 ===\n[[File:1973 Ambassador 4-d 401.JPG|thumb|250px|1973 Ambassador Brougham sedan with {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8]]\nThe SST models were dropped from the line, as all 1973 Ambassadors now came in one high-level \"Brougham\" trim. Ten popular items including an [[AM broadcasting|AM]] radio, power disk brakes, tinted glass, and [[whitewall tire]]s were added to the already extensive standard equipment list that included air conditioning, V8 engine, and automatic transmission. The Ambassador line \"maintains its reputation as one of the industry's most completely equipped cars.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=vQEUAQAAMAAJ&q=1973,+AMC's+Ambassador+Brougham+series+maintains+its+reputation+as+one+of+the+industry's+most+completely+equipped+cars |page=80 |title=13 Models Offered by AMC for 1973 |journal=Michigan Manufacturer and Financial Record |date=1972 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Multiple improvements in quality were designed to reinforce the new \"Extended Buyer Protection Plan\" exclusive to AMC cars that provided complete maintenance coverage for two years or {{convert|24000|mi|km|0|}}.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=cKSqa8u3EIoC&pg=PA83&dq=American+Motors+1973+cars |pages=82\u201383 |title=American Motors Introduces the Extended Buyer Protection Plan\n|journal=Popular Science |date=March 1973 |volume=202 |issue=3 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> The automaker's marketing campaign shifted to stress quality in a \"we back them better because we build them better\" advertising with particular emphasis into the Hornet, Matador and Gremlin promotion, while the Ambassador received got individual support with the tagline \"you get standard equipment, the luxuries you'd normally have to pay extra for.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/?id=w7UqAQAAMAAJ&q=73+AMC+Marketing+to+stress+Quality,+Identity,+Image&dq=73+AMC+Marketing+to+stress+Quality,+Identity,+Image |page=18 |title=AMC Marketing to stress Quality, Identity, Image |date=2 August 1972 |journal=Automotive News |publisher=Crain Automotive Group |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=YAvgAAAAMAAJ&q=The+1973+Ambassador+is+the+only+full-size+car+that+comes+standard+with+air+conditioning,+automatic+transmissions+radio,+power+steering,+front+powerdisc+brakes,+tinted |page=76 |journal=Time |volume=101 |date=1973 |title=1973 Ambassador is the only full-size car that comes standard with (advertisement) |accessdate=6 July 2017|last1=Hadden |first1=Briton |last2=Luce |first2=Henry Robinson }}</ref> Model year production for AMC increased 25 percent, outperforming the industry average production increase by 75 percent, with only a slightly changed product in the showrooms.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/?id=PV1uzCfmJDgC&pg=PA24&dq=American+Motors+1973+cars |pages=24\u201330 |title=American Cars, 1973-1980: Every Model, Year by Year |first=J. Kelly |last=Flory |publisher=McFarland |year=2012 |isbn=9780786456369 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn range rationalization to a single trim available in two-door hardtop, four-door sedan, and station wagon body versions, the styling changes for the 1973 Ambassadors were minimal. Heftier front and rear [[Bumper (automobile)|bumpers]] were included to comply with new U.S. [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA) regulations that required all passenger cars to withstand a {{convert|5|mph|0|adj=on}} front and a {{convert|2.5|mph|0|adj=on}} rear impacts without damage to the engine, lights, and safety equipment. Ambassadors complied with the regulation by incorporating a stronger front bumper equipped with self-restoring telescoping shock-absorbers.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Lamm |first=Michael |title=AMC: Hornet hatchback leads the lineup |journal=Popular Mechanics |volume=138 |issue=4 |pages=118\u2013202 |date=October 1972 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=VNQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA118&dq=1973+AMC+Ambassador |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Designed to \"give\" as much as {{convert|3.5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}, it jutted slightly forward from the front fascia and incorporated flexible trim matching the body paint. This bumper also featured a more prominent horizontal rubber guard at its upper portion near the grille, thus eliminating the need for a pair of vertical chrome bumper guards that was optional before. The rear bumper gained vertical black rubber bumper guards that also replaced a pair of similar and previously optional chrome bumper guards. The grille gained heavier horizontal bars and headlight bezels took on blackout trim in their recessed portions.\n\n== Eighth generation ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| model_years  = 1974\n| image        = 1974 AMC Ambassador Brougham 4-door sedan beige.JPG\n| caption      = 1974 Ambassador Brougham sedan\n| class        = [[Full-size car|Full-size]]\n| body_style   = {{unbulleted list | 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] | 4-door [[station wagon]] }}\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|122|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length       = {{convert|217.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| engine       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|304|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]] | {{convert|360|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 | {{convert|401|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 }}\n| transmission = 3-speed ''[[Torqueflite|Torque Command]]'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| name         = Eighth generation\n}}\n\n=== 1974 ===\n[[File:1974 AMC Ambassador sedan blue-white Kenosha-r.jpg|thumb|left|1974 AMC Ambassador sedan]]\n[[File:1974 AMC Ambassador sedan blue-white Kenosha-a.jpg|thumb|left|1974 AMC Ambassador sedan]]\n\nAmbassador sales had remained steady since 1970, despite the lack of major changes to the vehicle. 1974 models were stretched, {{convert|7|in|mm|spell=in}}, just as the 1973 [[1973 oil crisis|Arab Oil Embargo]] sparked nationwide gasoline rationing to accommodate energy absorbing bumpers.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Norbye |first=Jan P. |title=New bumpers have uniform height, take angle impacts |journal=Popular Science |pages=90\u201391 |date=October 1973 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lpiMSzja6W4C&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=New+bumpers+have+uniform+Ambassador |volume=203 |issue=4 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe 1974 Ambassador Brougham was no longer available as a 2-door (pillar-less) [[hardtop]], leaving the 4-door sedan and station wagon body styles. The hardtop's cancellation was due in part to low sales volume of the Ambassador 2-door versions, as well as the introduction of an all-new 1974 [[AMC Matador|Matador coupe]] that featured a long hood and short rear deck. The coupe received the \"Best Styled Car of 1974\" by the editors of ''[[Car and Driver]]'' magazine and did not feature typical period styling hallmarks, e.g., upright grille, [[notchback]] roof, and imitation \"landau bars\" or opera lights.<ref>{{cite journal |title=none|journal=Car and Driver |date=November 1973 }}</ref>\n\nStyling changes for the sedan and wagon included revised front fender caps on the same fenders used since 1969, and hood, grille, bumpers, rear fascia, instrument panel, interior trim, hood ornament, and a new font for the Ambassador nameplate. The grille showed off a new squared-off loop-type design surrounding the circular recessed quad headlights, and featured a forward-protruding center. The insert held a crosshatch pattern dominated by two thick horizontal bars that connected the headlight bezels and contained new parking lights between them. These parking lights had amber lenses, followed the grille protrusion forward, and were overlaid by the grille's crosshatch trim. Headlamp bezels were once again blacked out in their recessed areas. The new hood and front bumper followed the grille's central protrusion forward, giving the car a slight \"coffin nose\" look. The revised [[AMC Matador|Matador]] sedan saw a similar frontal treatment in 1974, but with a much more pronounced effect and with different single headlamp clusters, hood, and grille insert.\n\nAs with the new Matador sedan, the new rear bumper was much larger and backed by shock absorbers, as it was beefed up to comply with new [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] regulations for standardized front and rear bumpers on passenger cars that could sustain a {{convert|5|mph|0|adj=on}} impact with no damage. Fiberglass end caps were added to the ends of each rear fender on sedans. They wrapped inward to create a recessed space that met a carryover [[decklid]]. In this space was mounted the new rectangular taillight housings, which featured taller white backup lights mounted inboard of the new taillights. The license plate moved from the rear bumper to the area between the new taillight assemblies, and the whole taillight and license plate system on the sedans was surrounded its own loop of chrome trim. Both Ambassador and Matador sedans shared the same rear end style. \n\nThe cargo area and the rear design of station wagons remained similar to previous Ambassadors, save for a massive new bumper and revised taillamps. The wagon was available with two-row bench seats for six passengers or with a rear-facing third row for a total eight seat-belted passengers. All came with numerous practical, appearance, and comfort items as standard. These included a two-way opening tail gate: (1) hinged at the bottom for convenient loading or hauling long cargo and (2) hinged at the side to open as door for ease of entry and exit for passengers or cargo; wood grained [[Transparency (optics)|semi-transparent]] vinyl side and rear trim, a full-length [[roof rack]]; as well as a chrome and wood grain roof air deflector to help keep the tailgate window clean.\n\nPowertrain selections remained the same as in 1973, with only [[AMC V8 engine|V8 engines]] and automatic transmissions available. When ordered with a trailer package (special wiring harness with heavy-duty flasher and heavy-duty suspension with rear sway bar), the Ambassador was rated for up to {{convert|5000|lb|0|adj=on}} towing capacity.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schultz |first=Mort |title=Cars to take your rig in tow |journal=Popular Mechanics |pages=156\u2013157 |date=March 1974 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ddQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA156&dq=1974+AMC+Ambassador |volume=141 |issue=3 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Other increases for 1974 included a larger capacity fuel tank, {{convert|24.9|usgal|L impgal|0|abbr=on}}, and an alternator producing 62 [[ampere]]s. New sound insulation made the Ambassador even quieter. All came with a very lengthy list of standard equipment that was typically optional on competing makes. These included comfort items such as air conditioning, an AM radio, and vanity mirror to appearance enhancements such as [[pin striping]] and [[whitewall tire]]s.\n\nSales of all full-size vehicles, regardless of the automaker, fell significantly in 1974 as America's focus shifted to smaller cars. Ambassador sales were no different, and in June 1974, the final AMC Ambassador rolled off the [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]] assembly line, ending a nameplate that had been in continuous production in some form for 48 years.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==International markets==\n\n===Argentina===\n[[File:AutoantiguodesfileMDP5-9jul2016.jpg|thumb|right|Fifth U.S. generation Ambassador 990 built by IKA from 1965 to 1972]] \n'''Industrias Kaiser Argentina''' [[Industrias Kaiser Argentina|(IKA)]] produced the U.S. third, fourth, and fifth generation Ambassadors in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina]] from 1962 to 1972, and later available by special order through 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cocheargentino.com.ar/r/rambler.htm |title=IKA - Caracter\u00edsticas Classic Custom - Classic Custom De Luxe - Ambassador 440 |date=18 May 2009 |publisher=Coche Argentino |language=Spanish |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAssembly of IKA Ramblers began in 1962, with the Argentinean cars being the 1961 U.S. versions, but equipped with {{convert|226|cuin|L|2|abbr=on}} [[Continental Motors Company|Continental]] I6 engines producing {{convert|119|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 4000 rpm, along with a steering column mounted manual three-speed transmission. The Ambassador 440 was the top trim IKA model available only as a four-door sedan.\n\nThe completely new generation models by AMC in the U.S. for the 1963 model year was also replicated by IKA. The Ambassador sedan came only in 990 trim and it revolutionized the Argentine automotive market by introducing innovations that included power steering, power windows, and factory installed air conditioning.\n\n[[File:Presidential Rambler Ambassador.jpg|thumb|right|Presidential Rambler Ambassadors, produced in 1968 by [[Industrias Kaiser Argentina|IKA]] ]]\n\nThe Ambassador line was redesigned for 1965 in the U.S., as well as for Argentina. All IKA Rambler models now featured the {{convert|230.5|cuin|L|2|abbr=on}} [[overhead camshaft]] (OHC) straight-six \"[[Jeep Tornado engine|Tornado Interceptor]]\" engines producing {{convert|145|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 4200 rpm. They were originally developed by [[Kaiser Motors]] in the U.S. for the 1963 [[Jeep Gladiator]] pickups and [[Jeep Wagoneer|Wagoneer]] vehicles. The engine was now produced in Argentina and it increased the domestic (local sourced) content of IKA automobiles to lower taxes (tariffs).\n\nThe new IKA Ambassador 990 sedans were further upgraded to steering column mounted [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] four-speed manual transmissions, front disk brakes, front reclining bucket seats with center cushion and armrest, as well as the luxury features that included power windows and air conditioning.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://oldcarandtruckpictures.com/Argentina/Argentinajamc.html |title=Old Cars of Argentina Manufactured by Industrias Kaiser Argentina S.A. (IKA) |work=oldcarandtruckpictures.com |accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref> A road test by ''Revista Parabrisas'' described the 1965 IKA Rambler Ambassador 990 as \"soft, opulent, and smooth ride at all speeds... something big, luxurious and complete... the highest expression of comfort tested so far by the magazine.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://www.testdelayer.com.ar/pruebas/ika-rambler-ambassador.htm |title=IKA Rambler Ambassador 990 - 1965 - La m\u00e1s alta expresi\u00f3n del confort |journal=Revista Parabrisas |issue=59 |date=October 1965 |language=Spanish |publisher=testdelayer.com.ar |accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nStretch versions of the IKA Rambler Ambassador were used as official government [[limousine]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LfMk3dWPtDM |title=Per\u00f3n asume la presidencia 12 de octubre de 1973 |publisher=youtube |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> The \"Presidential\" models featured a longer rear door and side window, as well as broader [[Pillar (car)|C-pillar]] with padded [[vinyl roof]] cover and a small rear window.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Australia===\n[[File:1970 AMC Ambassador Hardtop Coupe (21938581090).jpg|thumb|One of only 16 two-door hardtop factory-RHD Ambassadors brought into Australia in 1970]]\n[[Australian Motor Industries]] (AMI) obtained the rights to assemble and distribute Ramblers in 1960, and the 1961, 1962, and 1963 model year Ambassadors were built in [[Australia]].<ref>Rambler Models ''[[Truck & Bus Transportation]]'' August 1961 page 10</ref> The 1961 sedan, which was powered by a {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} [[AMC V8 engine|V8]], was the most powerful car being assembled in Australia at that time.<ref name=\"Neasmith\"/> [[Knock-down kit]]s featuring [[right-hand drive]] were shipped from Kenosha to AMI's facilities in [[Port Melbourne]]. The Australian-built Ambassadors included a significant percentage of \"local content\" to gain import [[tariff]] (tax) concessions by using parts and components (such as interiors and upholstery) that were sourced from Australian manufacturers. AMI's first year of production resulted in 65 registrations for 1961. Registrations of the 1963 model continued into 1964 for a total of 21 Ambassadors registered for 1964.\n\nAlthough not documented in any AMI records, according to Australian Rambler afficionados 20 right-hand drive 1970 Ambassadors were fully imported from Canada, apparently 16 two-door hardtops and 4 four-door sedans. One possible reason for this was that it may have been a holding action while AMI was preparing for assembly of the new 1970 Rebel. AMC had assembled over 3,700 RHD Rambler Ambassadors for the U.S Postal Service in 1967, so they were well experienced in making completed right-hand drive vehicles. All Australian factory-RHD 1970 Ambassadors came with automatic transmission with floor shift.<ref>https://www.gumtree.com.au/s-ad/benaraby/cars-vans-utes/rambler-ambassador/1242484069</ref>\n\nThe dash and instrument pack of the 1967 Ambassador which had been converted and used in the RHD Ambassadors assembled for the U.S Postal Service was thereafter used in all Australian and New Zealand-assembled Rambler Rebel and Matador models, and all RHD, U.S-built Rebel and Matadors for the United Kingdom.\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[File:1970 AMC Ambassador SST (14379718872).jpg|thumb|right|One of 12 factory-RHD 1970 Ambassadors for the New Zealand market ]]\n\nAmerican Motors motor vehicles were assembled in New Zealand by '''VW Motors''' at their Volkswagen plant in Otahuhu, Auckland from 1958 until 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/motoring/107503496/the-empty-halls-of-new-zealands-car-assembly-industry |title=The empty halls of New Zealand's car assembly industry |first=Todd |last=Niall |website=Stuff |date=6 October 2018 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> From 1964, AMC vehicles were assembled by '''Campbell Motor Industries''' (CMI) in Thames, [[North Island]]. CMI assembled the Rambler Classic and Rebel models from knock-down kits and also imported fully assembled factory-right-hand-drive vehicles direct from AMC. Although no Ambassadors were locally assembled by CMI, it is believed twelve 1970 factory-right-hand-drive Ambassadors were fully imported.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2011/10/12/boomerang-the-only-gremlin-exported-to-australia-returns-to-the-united-states/ |title=Boomerang: The only Gremlin exported to Australia returns to the United States (comments) |first=Lindsay |last=Mckenzie |date= July 2017 |publisher=Hemmings |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Costa Rica===\nRambler vehicles were marketed in [[Costa Rica]] since 1959 through '''Purdy Motor'''.<ref name=\"CostaRica\">{{cite web|url= http://amc.co.cr/index.htm |title=AMC American Motors Corporation, Costa Rica |publisher=amc.co.cr |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Ruhi\">{{cite web|url= http://kaizen-factor.com/ultimate-toyota-restoration-backstory/ |title=The Ultimate Toyota Restoration: The Backstory |first=Joaqu\u00edn |last=Ruhi |date=10 May 2014 |publisher=Kaizen Factor |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> New local content regulations enacted during the 1960s effectively required vehicles sold in those markets to be assembled from [[knock-down kit]]s.<ref name=\"Ruhi\"/> An assembly plant for Rambler and Toyota vehicles was established, '''ECASA''', and the first Ramblers were produced in Costa Rica by the end of 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://amc.co.cr/amc_costarica.htm |title= Timeline of American Motors in Costa Rica |publisher=amc.co.cr |accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> The company built Ambassadors and other AMC models through 1970, with Toyota increasing ownership of ECASA.<ref name=\"CostaRica\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.toyota-global.com/company/history_of_toyota/75years/data/automotive_business/sales/activity/latin_america/index.html |title=Activities by RegionLatin America |publisher=Toyota Motor |accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\nAmerican Motors first-generation Ambassadors were exported to Mexico in the first half of 1958 and assembled locally in the second half of the same year and 1959 under '''Planta Reo de M\u00e9xico''' based in Monterrey, Nuevo Le\u00f3n. The model was virtually restricted to the four-door hardtop sedan only. It was powered by the four-barrel {{convert|327|CID|L|1|abbr=on}} V8 engine producing {{convert|270|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} coupled to a three-speed automatic transmission. The model became the marque's top-of-the-line product alongside the three versions of the midsize Rambler and Rambler American models. \n\nHowever, low sales figures alongside a deteriorating relationship between AMC and Planta REO lead to the cancellation of the contract in the second half of 1959. <ref>{{cite book|first=Douglas C. |last=Bennett |first2=Kenneth E. |last2=Sharpe |title=Transnational Corporations versus the State: The Political Economy of the Mexican Auto Industry |publisher=Princeton University Press |date=2014 |isbn=9780691022376}}</ref> American Motors once again exported its products into Mexico and a new local partner, Willys Mexicana that eventually would become '''Vehiculos Automotores Mexicanos''' [[Vehiculos Automotores Mexicanos|(VAM)]]. The agreement was signed in March 1960 and production began in Mexico City. \n\nThis meant the discontinuation of the Ambassador line in Mexico as the new operation had several priorities above offering a top-end luxury full-size car line. Aside from offering the already existing Jeep line, Willys Mexicana focused efforts on the compact Rambler American, which obtained a generation change just the next year, meaning a complete retooling of the Vallejo plant. In 1962, legal and industrial requirements in the country became stronger with the auto industry integration decree issued by president [[Adolfo L\u00f3pez Mateos]] in 1962. Among its mandates, it fully banned the importation of automobile engines. Willys Mexicana began building its own engine plant, which was achieved in November 1964. Once the Rambler American was consolidated in the Mexican market, Willys Mexicana opted to expand the product line by introducing the brand-new second generation Rambler Classic midsize model as a larger luxury counterpart to the economy compact American. Also in 1963, due to problems with WM's parent company (the SOMEX bank) as well as further requirements of the government auto industry decree, Willys Mexicana was reorganized into an entirely new company with expanded capital and direct investment from the Mexican government, Kaiser Willys, and American Motors. This resulted in the formation of Veh\u00edculos Automotores Mexicanos S.A. \n\nAfter the corporate transition process between 1960 and 1964 concluded, in which the Rambler marque under VAM surpassed the commercial results of its local predecessors Armadora Mexicana and Planta REO combined between 1950 and 1959, the company opted not to offer the Ambassador model. The Mexican market of the era was still relatively small and since the Ambassador shared mostly the same styling as the contemporary midsize model of the company, it was considered that internal competition would affect the sales of a simultaneous Rambler Classic/Ambassador line-up. Unlike the United States, which had a much larger and diverse market for two different car lines with the same styling, AMC could offer a strong difference between both models with the exclusive V8 engine for the Ambassador and the Classic being restricted to six cylinders only. This advantage did not exist in Mexico since VAM could only produce six cylinder engines in its Lerma plant and V8 engines could not be imported from AMC due to the ban of the 1962 decree. Instead, VAM opted to use the Rambler Classic as its most luxurious and flagship model, giving it the same treatment AMC put in the Ambassador model in the US and Canada. This would be passed on to the subsequent equivalent Rebel and Matador models produced under VAM. \n\nThe 1958\u20131959 Ambassador models represent the only chapter in this model's history to be present in Mexico. These were the only full-size American Motors products sold in the country alongside the second generation VAM Classic (Matador) models. Even more unique was the fact that it was a factory V8 model, the only one of its kind to ever be sold in Mexico belonging to American Motors.\n\n===United Kingdom===\nRambler Ambassadors were exported in limited numbers to the United Kingdom in factory right-hand-drive direct from AMC during the 1960s and up to its final year of 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/File:Im196610MotSC-RamblerMots.jpg |title=Image of Rambler Motors (AMC) Ltd. advertisement |website=www.gracesguide.co.uk |date=1967 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> They were imported by '''Rambler Motors (A.M.C) Ltd''' of Chiswick in West London which became a subsidiary of AMC in 1961.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Rambler_Motors |title=Rambler Motors |website=www.gracesguide.co.uk |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> The location had previously been used since 1926 for British assembly of Hudson, Essex, and Terraplane vehicles<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/april-1968/44/us-car-concessionaires-great-britain|title=U.S. Car Concessionaires in Great Britain |date=April 1968 |website=Motor Sport Magazine (Archive) |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> and later AMC's post-1954 Hudson, Nash and Rambler models. Ambassador models marketed in the UK were the Ambassador saloon (sedan), SST coupe, and station wagon. AMC vehicles were distributed by London distributors Clarke and Simpson Limited and were marketed as \"the only American car built with RHD.\"<ref>http://www.classiccarcatalogue.com/RAMBLER%201968.html</ref> As with all export markets UK models were marketed as \"Rambler\" even after the Rambler marque was dropped in the USA.\n\n== Epilogue ==\nBecause AMC was focusing its attentions on their newly acquired [[Jeep]] line, the redesigned 1974 Matador coupe, and the [[AMC Pacer]], which would debut in 1975, the company would not put forth the investment to continue the full-size Ambassador line after its 1974 redesign. Instead, the automaker upgraded the Matador sedan and wagon counterparts starting with the 1975 model year. The basic [[automobile platform]] was used by AMC since the 1967 model year, and the full-size automobile market segment was declining. American Motors strategy now aimed at smaller cars and sport-utility vehicles.\n\nHowever, the Ambassador basically continued as the similarly sized and styled [[AMC Matador|Matador]] sedans and wagons. From 1975 they became available in uplevel \"Brougham\" trim and assumed the model numbers of the previously equivalent Ambassadors.<ref>{{cite book |last=Flory, Jr. |first=J. \u201cKelly\u201d |title=American Cars, 1973-1980: Every Model, Year by Year |date=2012 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786456369 |page=223 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=yPwcDJ10TtAC&pg=PA223&dq=AMC+discontinued+the+Ambassador+line |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> The Matador was also offered in a unique top-of-the-line '''Barcelona''' four-door in its final year of production, 1978.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lamm |first1=Michael |title=Driving the '78 cars from American Motors |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=October 1977 |volume=148 |issue=4 |page=106, 178 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6uEDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA106&dq=Matador+Barcelona+sedan |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1978 AMC Full Line Brochure |url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.org/United%20States/AMC/1978_AMC/1978_AMC_Brochure/slides/1978_AMC-28.html |website=Old Car Brochures Project |pages=28\u201329, 32 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Foster |first=Patrick R. |title=AMC Cars: 1954\u20131987 An Illustrated History |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-58388-112-5 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Foster |first=Patrick R. |title=AMC Performance Cars: 1951\u20131983 Photo Archive |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-58388-127-9 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Foster |first=Patrick R. |title=American Motors \u2013 The Last Independent |publisher=Krause Publications |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-87341-240-7}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Foster |first=Patrick R. |title=1958\u20131962 Ambassador: A Rambler By Any Other Name |journal=Collectible Automobile |date=December 1992 |volume=9 |issue=6 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first=John |title=The Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946\u20131975 |publisher=Krause Publications |year=1987 | isbn=978-0-87341-096-0 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Mitchell |first=Larry G. |title=Illustrated AMC Buyer's Guide |publisher=Motorbooks |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-87938-891-1 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|AMC Ambassador}}\n* [http://www.AMCRC.com/ AMC Rambler Club]\n* [http://www.amonational.com/ American Motors Owners Association]\n* [http://www.nashcarclub.org/ Nash Car Club]\n* [http://www.americansportscars.com/healey.html Nash Healey History]\n* [http://www.nash-gb.com/ Nash in the UK]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101106220820/http://homepage.mac.com/christopher.z/hobby/67-Amb-1.html 1967 Ambassador information]\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=Rambler|model=Ambassador|Rambler Ambassador}}\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=AMC|model=Ambassador|AMC Ambassador}}\n\n{{American Motors}}\n{{amc Timeline}}\n\n[[Category:AMC vehicles|Ambassador]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Convertibles]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:Mid-size cars]]\n[[Category:Full-size vehicles]]\n[[Category:Limousines]]\n[[Category:Police vehicles]]\n[[Category:Taxicab vehicles]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:1960s cars]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1958]]\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEighth generation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AMC_Ambassador"}
{"title_page": "Ana de Armas", "text_new": "{{short description|Cuban actress}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{spanish name 2|de Armas|Caso}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Ana de Armas by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption      = De Armas at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name   = Ana Celia de Armas Caso\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|4|30}}\n| birth_place  = [[Havana]], Cuba\n| citizenship  = {{hlist|Cuban}} Spanish\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2006\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Marc Clotet]]|2011|2013|reason=divorced}}\n}}\n'''Ana Celia de Armas Caso''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8ana \u02c8selja de \u02c8armas \u02c8kaso|}}; born 30 April 1988) is a Cuban actress. She began her career as a teenager in her native Cuba and most notably had a leading role in the romantic drama ''[[Manuel Guti\u00e9rrez Arag\u00f3n|Una rosa de Francia]]'' (2006). At the age of 18, she moved to [[Madrid, Spain]] and starred in the popular teen drama ''[[El Internado]]'' for six seasons from 2007 to 2010. After moving to Los Angeles, de Armas had English-speaking roles in the horror film ''[[Knock Knock (2015 film)|Knock Knock]]'' (2015) and the crime drama ''[[War Dogs (2016 film)|War Dogs]]'' (2016). She had a supporting role in the sports biopic ''[[Hands of Stone]]'' (2016).\n\nDe Armas rose to prominence with her role as a holographic [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] projection in the science fiction film ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]'' (2017). Her performance as a nurse in the 2019 mystery film ''[[Knives Out]]'' was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress]].\n\n==Early life==\nAna Celia de Armas Caso was born on 30 April 1988 in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]].<ref name=voguees>{{cite news |url=https://www.vogue.es/living/articulos/ana-de-armas-entrevista-vogue-abril-2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> When she was an infant, her family moved to the seaside town of [[Santa Cruz del Norte]].<ref name=voguees/> Her father, Ram\u00f3n, worked in different positions including as a bank manager, a teacher, a school principal, and the deputy mayor of a town.<ref name=mujerhoy>{{cite news |last1=Navarro |first1=por Isabel |title=Ana de Armas: \"Mi punto fuerte es que no hay otra como yo\" |url=https://www.mujerhoy.com/vivir/protagonistas/201709/09/armas-punto-fuerte-otra-20170907092030.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=mujerhoy |date=17 March 2020 |language=es}}</ref> He had previously studied philosophy at a [[Russia]]n university.<ref name=magazinec>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas Is Conquering Hollywood in Record Time |url=https://magazinec.com/style/ana-de-armas-is-conquering-hollywood-in-record-time/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=C Magazine |date=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=mujerhoy/> Her mother, Ana, worked in the human resources section of the Ministry of Education.<ref name=vogue.es>{{cite news |title=De Cuba a Madrid, y hasta los cielos de Hollywood: la historia de Ana de Armas |url=https://www.vogue.es/living/articulos/ana-de-armas-entrevista-vogue-abril-2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=Vogue Espa\u00f1a |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref name=oncuba>[http://oncubamagazine.com/culture/ana-de-armas-a-cuban-woman-out-to-conquer-hollywood/ A Cuban Women Out To Conquer Hollywood] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105161041/http://oncubamagazine.com/culture/ana-de-armas-a-cuban-woman-out-to-conquer-hollywood/ |date=5 November 2016 }} On Cuba magazine</ref><ref>[https://magazinec.com/style/ana-de-armas-is-conquering-hollywood-in-record-time Ana de Armas is conquering Hollywood in record time]</ref> She has one older brother, Javier, a [[New York City|New York]]-based photographer<ref name=mujerhoy/><ref>{{cite web|title=When my brother finds a photo of me, he took back in 2015.|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BeGp3vwjDLN/|accessdate=18 January 2018|work=Instagram}}</ref> who, in 2020, was questioned by Cuban police due to his links to independent artists on the island and his critical stance on Decree 349.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Noticias |first1=Asere |title=Javier Caso, hermano de Ana de Armas, es interrogado por la Seguridad del Estado |url=https://www.asere.com/javier-caso-hermano-de-ana-de-armas-es-interrogado-por-la-seguridad-del-estado-en-cuba/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Asere Noticias |date=16 January 2020 |language=es}}</ref> While de Armas grew up with [[Rationing in Cuba|food rationing]], fuel shortages and electricity blackouts during Cuba's [[Special Period]],<ref name=mujerhoy/><ref name=\"vanityfair.es\"/> she has described her childhood as happy.<ref name=vogue.es/>\n\nAs a child and teenager, de Armas had no internet access and had limited knowledge of popular culture beyond Cuba.<ref name=\"El Pa\u00eds\">{{cite news |last1=Crespo |first1=Irene |title=Ana de Armas: \"Antes de 'Blade Runner' no me sal\u00eda nada, por el acento\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/09/19/tentaciones/1505831920_388735.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=28 September 2017 |language=es}}</ref> She was allowed to watch \"20 minutes of cartoons on Saturday and the Sunday movie matinee.\"<ref name=\"NET-A-PORTER\">{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas talks James Bond & playing Marilyn Monroe |url=https://www.net-a-porter.com/gb/en/porter/article-a838dd936e0153af/cover-stories/cover-stories/ana-de-armas |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=NET-A-PORTER}}</ref> Her family did not own a \"video or DVD player\" and she watched Hollywood movies in her neighbour's apartment.<ref name=\"La Vanguardia\">{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas, la novia virtual del nuevo \u2018Blade Runner\u2019 |url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/gente/20171014/432031439621/entrevista-ana-de-armas-blade-runner-cuba.html |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=La Vanguardia |date=13 October 2017 |language=es}}</ref> She memorised and practised monologues in front of the mirror,<ref>{{cite news |title=Hollywood's Next Big Thing: 'Blade Runner 2049' Breakout Ana de Armas |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hollywoods-next-big-thing-blade-runner-2049-breakout-ana-de-armas-1044837 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Crespo |first1=Irene |title=Ana de Armas: \"Antes de 'Blade Runner' no me sal\u00eda nada, por el acento\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/09/19/tentaciones/1505831920_388735.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=28 September 2017 |language=es}}</ref> and decided to become an actress when she was 12.<ref name=\"ideal\">{{cite news|title=Los ojos verdes de Hollywood no ten\u00edan trabajo en Espa\u00f1a|url=http://www.ideal.es/gente-estilo/201605/16/ojos-verdes-hollywood-20160514162736.html|accessdate=5 September 2016|work=Ideal|date=16 May 2016|language=es-ES}}</ref> In 2002, at the age of 14, she successfully auditioned to join the [[National Theatre of Cuba|National Theater School of Cuba]].<ref name=vogue.es/><ref name=mirror>{{cite news |last1=Simpson |first1=Richard |last2=Costello |first2=Eugene |title=Bond girl Ana de Armas 'escaped Cuba at first opportunity' to pursue soap fame |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/celebrity-news/bond-girl-ana-de-armas-16201516 |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=irishmirror |date=25 May 2019}}</ref> She hitchhiked or travelled by bus each day to attend the \"rigorous\" course in Havana.<ref name=\"A seis grados de Marilyn Monroe\">{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Rub\u00e9n Romero |title=A seis grados de Marilyn Monroe |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2014/05/07/icon/1399458158_612811.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=7 May 2014 |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Crosley |first1=Sloane |title=All About Ana |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/all-about-ana-march-2020-cover-story |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |language=en}}</ref> While a student there, she filmed three movies.<ref name=oncuba/><ref name=mujerhoy/> She left the four-year drama course months before presenting her final thesis because Cuban graduates are forbidden from leaving the country without completing three years of mandatory service to the state.<ref name=oncuba/><ref name=\"Havana Times\">{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Circles |title=Interview with Cuban actress Ana de Armas |url=https://havanatimes.org/interviews/interview-with-cuban-actress-ana-de-armas/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Havana Times |date=22 January 2011}}</ref> At the age of 18, with \u20ac200 in savings and Spanish citizenship through her maternal grandparents,<ref name=vanityfair.es>{{cite news |title=En mi primera pel\u00edcula me enamor\u00e9 de varias personas, eso ahora no me pasar\u00e1 |url=https://www.revistavanityfair.es/la-revista/articulos/entrevista-con-ana-de-armas-blade-runner-2049-fecha-estreno/23251 |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |date=9 December 2019 |language=es}}</ref> de Armas moved to [[Madrid|Madrid, Spain]] to pursue an acting career.<ref name=oncuba/>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 2006\u20132014: Spanish stardom ===\nAs a teenager in her native Cuba, de Armas had a starring role opposite [[\u00c1lex Gonz\u00e1lez (actor)|\u00c1lex Gonz\u00e1lez]] in [[Manuel Guti\u00e9rrez Arag\u00f3n]]'s romantic drama ''Una rosa de Francia'' (2006).<ref name=vanityfair.es/> While attending a birthday party with the daughters of Cuban actor [[Jorge Perugorr\u00eda]], she learned that auditions for the project were being held in Havana.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanguino |first1=Juan |title=Ana de Armas: la actriz que Espa\u00f1a infravalor\u00f3 y Hollywood abraz\u00f3 |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/10/28/icon/1572267101_072687.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=4 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> The director interrupted the sixteen-year-old during her audition to inform her that the role was hers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105161041/http://oncubamagazine.com/culture/ana-de-armas-a-cuban-woman-out-to-conquer-hollywood/ |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> She then starred in the movie ''El ed\u00e9n perdido'' (2007) and had a supporting role in [[Fernando P\u00e9rez (director)|Fernando P\u00e9rez]]'s ''Madrigal'' (2007), filmed at night without the permission of her drama school tutors.<ref name=oncuba/>\n\nAt the age of 18, de Armas moved to Madrid, Spain. Within two weeks of arriving, she met with casting director Luis San Narciso, who had seen her in ''Una rosa de Francia''.<ref name=\"El Pa\u00eds\"/> He cast her as Carolina in the teen drama ''[[El Internado]]'',<ref name=oncuba/> in which she starred for six seasons from 2007 to 2010. The television show, set in a boarding school, became popular with viewers and made de Armas a celebrity figure in Spain.<ref name=oncuba/> In a break from filming, she starred in the successful coming-of-age comedy ''[[Mentiras y Gordas]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite news |last1=BELINCH\u00d3N |first1=GREGORIO |title=Un estupendo fin de semana para el cine espa\u00f1ol |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2009/03/30/actualidad/1238364015_850215.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=30 March 2009 |language=es}}</ref> Despite the popularity of ''El Internado'', de Armas felt typecast and was mainly offered roles for teenagers.<ref name=\"El Pa\u00eds\"/> She asked to be written out of the show in its second last season.<ref name=\"elpais.com\">{{cite news |last1=Sanguino |first1=Juan |title=Ana de Armas: la actriz que Espa\u00f1a infravalor\u00f3 y Hollywood abraz\u00f3 |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/10/28/icon/1572267101_072687.html |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=4 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> After spending a few months living in New York to learn English,<ref name=\"Havana Times\"/> de Armas was persuaded to return to Spain to star in seventeen episodes of the historical drama ''Hispania'' (2010\u20132011).<ref name=\"voguees\"/> She then starred in [[Antonio Trashorras]]'s horror films ''El callej\u00f3n'' (2011) and ''Anabel'' (2015),<ref>{{cite news |last1=Costa |first1=Jordi |title=Opini\u00f3n {{!}} Una coreograf\u00eda s\u00e1dica |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2013/02/28/actualidad/1362084592_653965.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=1 March 2013 |language=es}}</ref> and in the drama ''Por un pu\u00f1ado de besos'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oca\u00f1a |first1=Javier |title=Opini\u00f3n {{!}} Romanticismo de \u2018Superpop\u2019 |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2014/05/15/actualidad/1400173366_065368.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=16 May 2014 |language=es}}</ref> During a long period without acting work,<ref name=\"A seis grados de Marilyn Monroe\"/> de Armas participated in workshops at [[Tomaz Pandur]]'s Madrid theatre company<ref name=mujerhoy/> and felt \"very anxious\" about the lack of momentum in her career.<ref name=\"NET-A-PORTER\"/> With encouragement from her newly-hired Hollywood agent, she decided to move to Los Angeles.<ref name=\"El Pa\u00eds\"/>\n\n=== 2015\u20132019: Move to Hollywood===\nWhen de Armas first arrived in Los Angeles in 2014,<ref name=hollywoodreporter>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hollywoods-next-big-thing-blade-runner-2049-breakout-ana-de-armas-1044837|title=Hollywood's Next Big Thing: 'Blade Runner 2049' Breakout Ana de Armas|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> she had to start her career again \"from scratch.\"<ref name=\"La Vanguardia\"/> She spoke very little English and, during early auditions, she often \"didn\u2019t even know what [she] was saying.\"<ref name=magazinec/> She took intensive English lessons,<ref name=\"elpais.com\"/> not wanting to be confined to playing roles specifically written for Latina actresses.<ref name=oncuba/> She starred opposite [[Keanu Reeves]] in her first Hollywood release - [[Eli Roth]]'s erotic horror thriller ''[[Knock Knock (2015 film)|Knock Knock]]'' (2015) - and learned her lines phonetically.<ref name=thrbond>{{cite news |title=Bond Women: How Rising Stars Lashana Lynch and Ana de Armas Are Helping Modernize 007 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/how-lashana-lynch-ana-de-armas-are-helping-modernize-james-bond-1252345 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref> Reeves then telephoned de Armas to invite her to star in a Spanish-language role in the thriller ''[[Exposed (2016 film)|Exposed]]'' (2016), which he acted in and produced.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mA7EzRYoRzc |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> De Armas had a supporting role in [[Todd Phillips]]'s ''[[War Dogs (2016 film)|War Dogs]]'' (2016), acting opposite [[Miles Teller]] as the wife of an arms dealer, and again learned her lines phonetically.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crosley |first1=Sloane |title=All About Ana |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/all-about-ana-march-2020-cover-story |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |language=en}}</ref> David Ehrlich of ''Indiewire'' found her \"memorable in a thankless role\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ehrlich |first1=David |last2=Ehrlich |first2=David |title=\u2018War Dogs\u2019 Review: Jonah Hill Is On Target, But This Gunrunner Comedy Shoots Blanks |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/08/war-dogs-review-jonah-hill-miles-teller-todd-phillips-1201717253/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=IndieWire |date=16 August 2016 |language=en}}</ref> She starred opposite [[\u00c9dgar Ram\u00edrez]] in the biopic ''[[Hands of Stone]]'' (2016) as the wife of Panamanian boxer [[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]]. Despite its delayed release, ''Hands of Stone'' was the first Hollywood movie de Armas filmed. She had been contacted by director [[Jonathan Jakubowicz]] while still living in Madrid; he had seen her in ''El Internado''<ref name=\"elpais.com\"/> and asked her to travel to Los Angeles to audition for the Spanish-language part.<ref name=\"vanityfair.es\"/> In reviewing the film, Christy Lemire of ''[[RogerEbert.com]]'' described de Armas as \"a hugely charismatic presence. But except for a couple of showy moments, she gets little to do besides function as the dutiful wife.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lemire |first1=Christy |title=Hands of Stone movie review & film summary (2016) {{!}} Roger Ebert |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/hands-of-stone-2016 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=rogerebert.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:KnivesOutToronto.png|thumb|upright|left|Ana de Armas attends the world premiere of ''[[Knives Out]]'' in 2019]]\n\nIn [[Denis Villeneuve]]'s futuristic thriller ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]'' (2017), de Armas had a supporting role as Joi, the [[Hologram|holographic]] [[AI]] girlfriend of [[Ryan Gosling]]'s character. Mark Kermode of ''The Guardian'' said she \"brings three-dimensional warmth to a character who is essentially a digital projection.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kermode |first1=Mark |last2=critic |first2=Observer film |title=Blade Runner 2049 review \u2013 a future classic |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/oct/08/blade-runner-2049-review-a-future-classic |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=8 October 2017}}</ref> Anthony Lane of the ''New Yorker'' found her \"wondrous\": \"Whenever Joi appears, the movie\u2019s imaginative heart begins to race.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lane |first1=Anthony |title=\u201cBlade Runner 2049\u201d: The Mysteries Deepen |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/16/blade-runner-2049-the-mysteries-deepen |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The New Yorker |language=en}}</ref> While the performance was initially discussed as a breakthrough role,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/10/blade-runner-2049-supporting-cast-ana-de-armas-carla-juri-1201884020/|title='Blade Runner 2049': Where You've Seen Standout Supporting Cast Before - IndieWire|first=Kate|last=Erbland|website=Indiewire.com|accessdate=2 December 2017|date=9 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=hollywoodreporter/> the film underperformed commercially, and de Armas spent much of the following year in her native Cuba, where she bought a house.<ref name=thrbond/> Also in 2017, she had a supporting role in the action thriller ''[[Overdrive (2017 film)|Overdrive]]'' as the love interest of [[Scott Eastwood]]'s character.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title='Knock Knock' Actress Ana de Armas Joining Scott Eastwood in 'Overdrive' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/knock-knock-actress-ana-de-823094|accessdate=5 June 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=14 September 2015}}</ref> Stephen Dalton of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' said she \"radiates more kick-ass charisma than her thankless sidekick role might suggest.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Overdrive': Film Review |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/overdrive-review-1029281 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref> In 2018, de Armas starred opposite [[Demi\u00e1n Bichir]] in [[John Hillcoat]]'s medical drama ''Coraz\u00f3n''. She played a Dominican woman with heart failure in the short film, funded by [[Montefiore Medical Center]] to raise awareness of organ donation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hammond |first1=Pete |last2=Hammond |first2=Pete |title=Tribeca Film Festival World Premiere Of \u2018Corazon\u2019 Aims To Save Lives \u2013 Watch The Trailer |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/corazon-trailer-tribeca-film-festival-john-hillcoat-demian-bichir-1202367589/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Deadline |date=19 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDe Armas's role as an immigrant nurse in the ensemble murder mystery film ''[[Knives Out]]'' (2019), directed by [[Rian Johnson]], was widely praised and marked a breakthrough for the actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/|title=Toronto Film Festival: 'Joker,' 'Ford v Ferrari,' 'Hustlers' Among Big Premieres|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=July 23, 2019|accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref> When first approached about the project, she was unenthusiastic about the idea of playing a stereotypical \u201cLatina caretaker\u201d but soon realised that her character was \"so much more than that.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Knives Out' Star Ana de Armas on Declining to Audition and 'Bond' Chemistry with Daniel Craig |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/why-knives-star-ana-de-armas-declined-audition-at-first-1258369 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref> Tom Shone of ''The Times'' remarked: \"The film\u2019s standout performance comes from its least well-known member, the Cuban de Armas, who manages the difficult task of making goodness interesting.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shone |first1=Tom |title=Film reviews: Knives Out; The Two Popes |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/magazine/culture/film-reviews-knives-out-the-two-popes-p3v7bg666 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=thetimes.co.uk |language=en}}</ref> Benjamin Lee of ''The Guardian'' said her \"striking\" performance left a \"lasting impression.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/08/knives-out-review-rian-johnson-crafts-a-devious-meta-whodunnit |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The film was a major box office success.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rubin |first1=Rebecca |last2=Rubin |first2=Rebecca |title=Box Office: \u2018Knives Out\u2019 Carves Out $300 Million Worldwide |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/box-office/box-office-knives-out-milestone-1203501247/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=11 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> De Armas was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical]]<ref>{{cite news |title=\"Knives Out\" actress Ana de Armas is nominated for a Golden Globe |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/knives-out-actress-ana-de-armas-nominated-golden-globe-n1098191 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=NBC News |language=en}}</ref> and the cast won the [[National Board of Review Award for Best Cast]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Matt |last2=Donnelly |first2=Matt |title=National Board of Review Names \u2018The Irishman\u2019 Best Movie of the Year |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/national-board-of-review-irishman-best-movie-1203422503/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=3 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> While de Armas's scenes opposite [[Himesh Patel]] in the 2019 romantic comedy ''[[Yesterday (2019 film)|Yesterday]]'' were included in the movie's trailer, they were deleted from the final cut. The director [[Danny Boyle]] said that, while de Armas was \"really radiant\" in her scenes, the introduction of a love triangle subplot did not test well with audiences.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yesterday Cut An Entire Character From The Film That Would Have Changed The Plot |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2475654/yesterday-cut-an-entire-character-from-the-film-that-would-have-changed-the-plot |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=CINEMABLEND |date=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020: Seven film roles===\nDe Armas has seven films scheduled for release in the United States in 2020. She had a supporting role in the crime thriller ''[[The Informer (2019 film)|The Informer]]'' as the wife of [[Joel Kinnaman]]'s character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/ana-de-armas-joel-kinnaman-rosamund-pike-three-seconds-andrea-di-stefano-common-clive-owen-thunder-road-pictures-the-fyzz-facility-1202126156/|title=Ana De Armas Joins Joel Kinnaman & Rosamund Pike For \u2018Three Seconds\u2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Diana|last=Lodderhose|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> Guy Lodge of ''Variety'' found \"her thin role all the more glaring in the wake of her ''Knives Out'' stardom.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lodge |first1=Guy |last2=Lodge |first2=Guy |title=\u2018The Informer\u2019: Film Review |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/the-informer-review-1203453865/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> She appeared as a [[femme fatale]] in the noir crime drama ''[[The Night Clerk]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/helen-hunt-ana-de-armas-john-leguizamo-the-night-clerk-movie-1202396672/|title=Helen Hunt, Ana de Armas & John Leguizamo Join 'The Night Clerk' Thriller|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|date=2018-05-23|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2018-12-15}}</ref> Brian Tallerico of ''RobertEbert.com'' said the movie had \"no idea\" what to do with her \"blinding charisma\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tallerico |first1=Brian |title=The Night Clerk movie review & film summary (2020) {{!}} Roger Ebert |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-night-clerk-movie-review-2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=rogerebert.com |language=en}}</ref> while Katie Rife of ''The AV Club'' remarked that it would be remembered, \"if at all, as a movie de Armas was way too good for.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas is way too good for the lousy, sub-De Palma thriller The Night Clerk |url=https://film.avclub.com/ana-de-armas-is-way-too-good-for-the-lousy-sub-de-palm-1841776487 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Film |language=en-us}}</ref> De Armas starred opposite [[Wagner Moura]] in the Netflix biopic ''[[Sergio (upcoming film)|Sergio]]'' (2020) as Carolina Larriera, a U.N. official and the partner of diplomat [[S\u00e9rgio Vieira de Mello]]. John DeFore of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' found her \"magnetic\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Sergio': Film Review {{!}} Sundance 2020 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/sergio-1274882 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref> while Jessica Kiang of ''Variety'' said she imbued the part \"with an intelligence and will that makes her more than just de Mello\u2019s romantic foil.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kiang |first1=Jessica |last2=Kiang |first2=Jessica |title=\u2018Sergio\u2019: Film Review |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/uncategorized/sergio-review-1203473960/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=30 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDe Armas will star in three films in late 2020. She will reunite with her ''Knives Out'' co-star [[Daniel Craig]] to play a [[Bond girl]] in [[Cary Joji Fukunaga]]'s ''[[No Time to Die]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/how-lashana-lynch-ana-de-armas-are-helping-modernize-james-bond-1252345|title=Bond Women: How Rising Stars Lashana Lynch and Ana de Armas Are Helping Modernize 007|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Rebecca|last=Ford|date=November 6, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/james-bond-25-live-reveal-rami-malek-daniel-craig-jamaica-1202601779/|title=Bond 25 Live Reveal From Jamaica: Rami Malek, Ana De Armas, Billy Magnussen, Lashana Lynch & Dali Benssalah Among Confirmed Cast|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman|date=November 28, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Fukunaga wrote the role of a Cuban CIA agent specifically for de Armas<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crosley |first1=Sloane |title=All About Ana |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/all-about-ana-march-2020-cover-story |work=Vanity Fair |language=en}}</ref> and a replica of downtown Havana was built at London's Pinewood Studios.<ref name=\"NET-A-PORTER\"/> She will star in [[Adrian Lyne]]'s erotic thriller ''[[Deep Water (2020 film)|Deep Water]]'', based upon the [[Deep Water (Highsmith novel)|novel]] by [[Patricia Highsmith]]. She and [[Ben Affleck]] play a couple in an adulterous marriage.<ref>[https://deadline.com/2019/08/adrian-lyne-deep-water-ben-affleck-ana-de-armas-patricia-highsmith-adaptation-new-regency-1202658671/ New Regency Bringing Adrian Lyne Back To Directing With \u2018Deep Water;\u2019 Ben Affleck, Ana de Armas In Talks For Patricia Highsmith Adaptation]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/disney-fox-release-schedule-the-last-duel-the-kings-man-nimona-1202787773/|title=Disney Dates A Ton Of Pics Into 2023 & Juggles Fox Releases With Ridley Scott\u2019s \u2018The Last Duel\u2019 To Open Christmas 2020, \u2018The King\u2019s Man\u2019 Next Fall \u2013 Update|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> In her final role of 2020, de Armas will portray [[Marilyn Monroe]] in the Netflix biopic ''[[Blonde (upcoming film)|Blonde]]'', based on the novel by [[Joyce Carol Oates]].<ref>[https://collider.com/ana-de-armas-marilyn-monroe-blonde-movie/ Exclusive: Ana de Armas Eyed to Play Marilyn Monroe in Andrew Dominik\u2019s \u2018Blonde\u2019]</ref> Director [[Andrew Dominik]] noticed de Armas's performance in ''Knock Knock''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.net-a-porter.com/gb/en/porter/article-a838dd936e0153af/cover-stories/cover-stories/ana-de-armas |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> and, while she went through a long casting process, Dominik promised her the role was hers after the first audition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crosley |first1=Sloane |title=All About Ana |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/all-about-ana-march-2020-cover-story |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |language=en}}</ref> In preparation for the part, de Armas worked with a dialect coach for a year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bahr |first1=Lindsey |last2=Press |first2=The Associated |title=New year is the year for actress Ana de Armas' break |url=https://www.berkshireeagle.com/stories/new-year-is-the-year-for-actress-ana-de-armas-break,591280 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Berkshire Eagle |language=en}}</ref><ref name=magazinec/><ref name=\"voguees\"/>\n\nDe Armas will reunite with her ''Sergio'' co-star Wagner Moura to play the wife of one of the [[Cuban Five]] in [[Olivier Assayas]]'s spy thriller ''[[Wasp Network (film)|Wasp Network]]''.<ref name=waspnetwork>{{cite news |last1=Keslassy |first1=Elsa |last2=Keslassy |first2=Elsa |title=Netflix Scoops Olivier Assayas\u2019s \u2018Wasp Network\u2019 With Penelope Cruz, Edgar Ramirez (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/global/netflix-wasp-network-olivier-assayas-penelope-cruz-edgar-ramirez-1203470566/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=17 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The movie was shot on location in Cuba; it was de Armas's first time to work in her home country since leaving as a teenager.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keslassy |first1=Elsa |last2=Keslassy |first2=Elsa |title=Olivier Assayas on Making \u2018Wasp Network\u2019 in Cuba \u2018During a Very Tense Time\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/penelope-cruz-edgar-ramirez-olivier-assayas-wasp-network-cuba-venice-1203319151/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=31 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> After the film's world premiere at the [[Venice Film Festival]], Jay Weissberg of ''Variety'' said de Armas \"easily\" held her own in the \"impressive cast\", describing her as \"a joyous, bewitching presence whose career seems destined for the big time.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weissberg |first1=Jay |last2=Weissberg |first2=Jay |title=Venice Film Review: \u2018Wasp Network\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/wasp-network-review-1203320589/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=1 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Netflix have acquired the rights to ''Wasp Network'' but have yet to announce a release date.<ref name=waspnetwork/>\n\n==Personal life==\nDe Armas began a relationship with Spanish actor [[Marc Clotet]] in mid-2010; they married in [[Costa Brava]], Spain in July 2011 and divorced in early 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas, de \u2018Hispania\u2019 y Marc Clotet, de \u2018F\u00edsica o qu\u00edmica\u2019 se han casado en la Costa Brava |url=https://www.hola.com/cine/2011072053728/boda-anadearmas-marcclotet/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=20 July 2011 |language=es-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Marc Clotet confirma su separaci\u00f3n de Ana de Armas: 'Ha sido de mutuo acuerdo' |url=https://premiosgoya.hola.com/los-goya-2013/201302172270/marcclotet-anaarmas-separacion-goya2013/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA |date=17 February 2013}}</ref> She dated Spanish director and screenwriter David Victori from mid-2013 to mid-2014,<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas encuentra de nuevo el amor |url=https://www.hola.com/cine/2013082266697/ana-de-armas-enamorada-david-victori/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=22 August 2013 |language=es-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=El secreto de la belleza y la sonrisa de Ana de Armas tiene nombre y es David Victori |url=https://www.hola.com/cine/2014032770435/anaarmas-davidvictori-malaga/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=27 March 2014 |language=es}}</ref> was briefly engaged to American talent agent Franklin Latt during a relationship from 2015 to 2016,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armas |first1=Ana de |title=Forever.... @franklinlatt  https://www.instagram.com/p/BG0eFTxjNBU/ |url=https://twitter.com/Ana_d_Armas/status/744361058400350208 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=@Ana_d_Armas |date=18 June 2016 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas encuentra nuevo amor y cumple su sue\u00f1o americano en Hollywood |url=https://www.diezminutos.es/famosos-corazon/famosos-extranjeros/news/g9163/ana-de-armas-encuentra-nuevo-amor-y-cumple-su-sueno-americano-en-hollywood/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Diez Minutos |date=5 August 2015 |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u00bfA qui\u00e9n besa Ana de Armas? |url=http://www.zeleb.es/n/a-quien-besa-ana-de-armas-023436 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=zeleb.es |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas se 'codea' con Beyonc\u00e9 en Hollywood |url=https://www.hola.com/cine/2016082587953/ana-armas-con-beyonce-deniro/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=25 August 2016 |language=es-US}}</ref> and dated Cuban painter Alejandro Pi\u00f1eiro Bello from 2017 to 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas apoya a su chico y se muestra ' muy orgullosa' de su exposici\u00f3n |url=https://www.hola.com/actualidad/20180223120789/ana-de-armas-orgullosa-alejandro-pineiro-deco/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=23 February 2018 |language=es-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Este es Alejandro Pineiro, el joven que rob\u00f3 el coraz\u00f3n de la cubana Ana de Armas |url=https://www.cibercuba.com/noticias/2018-04-23-u194224-e198483-s27065-este-alejandro-pineiro-joven-robo-corazon-cubana-ana |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=CiberCuba |date=23 April 2018 |language=es}}</ref> De Armas is in a relationship with American actor and filmmaker [[Ben Affleck]], whom she met in the fall of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Affleck and Ana de Armas Spotted in Her Native Cuba After Wrapping Thriller Together |url=https://people.com/movies/ben-affleck-and-ana-de-armas-spotted-in-her-native-cuba-after-wrapping-thriller-together/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=PEOPLE.com |language=EN}}</ref>\n\nOn social media, de Armas has voiced support for the [[Ele N\u00e3o movement]],<ref>{{cite news |title=A N A D E A R M A S on Instagram: \"Women of Brazil, I stand with you, I also say #elenao ! We want our leaders to protect HUMAN RIGHTS, to say NO to violence, NO to racism,\u2026\" |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BoIZ0ZrjHKP/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Instagram |language=en}}</ref> the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement,<ref>{{cite news |title=A N A D E A R M A S on Instagram: \"#altonsterling\ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffe #philandocastile \ud83d\udc94\" |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BHkwFWDDhOB/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Instagram |language=en}}</ref> the [[equal pay for equal work]] movement,<ref>{{cite news |title=A N A D E A R M A S on Instagram: \"Equal work. Equal pay. #equalpayday\" |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhaCvxRjEpv/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Instagram |language=en}}</ref> and the fight for [[same-sex marriage in the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |title=A N A D E A R M A S on Instagram: \"#lovewins \ud83d\udc97\ud83d\udc9b\ud83d\udc9a\ud83d\udc99\ud83d\udc9c\" |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/4Zi9xeDNM9/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Instagram |language=en}}</ref> She criticised the \"injustice\" of the [[Trump administration family separation policy]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armas |first1=Ana de |title=Please, read this message from  my friend and amazing artist @DemianBichir ! We all have the responsibility to change this injustice. Thanks Demian!https://deadline.com/2018/06/demian-bichir-criticizes-forced-separation-illegal-immigrant-children-human-shields-donald-trump-1202413610/&nbsp;\u2026 |url=https://twitter.com/Ana_d_Armas/status/1009200209681739777 |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=@Ana_d_Armas |date=19 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT use \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Una rosa de Francia''\n| Marie\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Madrigal''\n| Stella Maris\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Mentiras y Gordas]]''\n| Carola\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Y de postre, qu\u00e9''\n| Girl\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''\u00c1nima''\n| Julieta\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''El callej\u00f3n''\n| Rosa / Laura\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Perrito chino''\n| Sabina\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Faraday''\n| Inma Murga\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Por un pu\u00f1ado de besos''\n| Sol\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Anabel''\n| Cris\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Knock Knock (2015 film)|Knock Knock]]''\n| Bel\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Exposed (2016 film)|Exposed]]''\n| Isabel de la Cruz\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[War Dogs (2016 film)|War Dogs]]''\n| Iz\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Hands of Stone]]''\n| Felicidad Dur\u00e1n\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Overdrive (film)|Overdrive]]''\n| Stephanie\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]''\n| Joi\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Coraz\u00f3n''\n| Elena Ram\u00edrez\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Yesterday (2019 film)|Yesterday]]''\n| Roxanne\n| Deleted scenes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Knives Out]]''\n| Marta Cabrera\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Informer (2019 film)|The Informer]]''\n| Sofia Hoffman\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Wasp Network (film)|Wasp Network]]''\n| Ana Magarita Martinez\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[The Night Clerk]]''\n| Andrea Rivera\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Sergio (2020 film)|Sergio]]''\n| Carolina\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Deep Water (2020 film)|Deep Water]]''\n| Melinda Van Allen\n| Post-production\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[No Time to Die]]''\n| Paloma\n| Post-production\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Blonde (upcoming film)|Blonde]]''\n| [[Marilyn Monroe|Norma Jeane \"Marilyn Monroe\" Mortenson]]\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''El ed\u00e9n perdido''\n| Gloria\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2007\u20132010\n| ''[[El Internado]]''\n| Carolina Leal Sol\u00eds\n| 56 episodes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Revelados''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2010\u20132012\n| ''Hispania, la leyenda''\n| Nerea\n| 17 episodes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Actrices''\n| Herself\n| 2 episodes\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Everyday''\n| Orishas\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated work\n! Award\n! Category\n! Result\n|-\n| [[44th Saturn Awards|2018]]\n| ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]''\n| [[Saturn Awards]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Board of Review Awards 2019|2019]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"| ''[[Knives Out (film)|Knives Out]]''\n| [[National Board of Review]]\n| [[National Board of Review Award for Best Cast|Best Cast]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[77th Golden Globe Awards|2020]]\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[24th Satellite Awards|2020]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Cast \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Cast \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n||2020\n|[[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics' Choice Awards]]\n|| [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Acting Ensemble|Best Acting Ensemble]]\n|{{nom}} \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|1869101}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armas, Ana De}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Cuban actresses]]\n[[Category:Citizens of Spain through descent]]\n[[Category:Cuban expatriates in Spain]]\n[[Category:Cuban expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cuban film actresses]]\n[[Category:Cuban people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Cuban television actresses]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cuban actress}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{spanish name 2|de Armas|Caso}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Ana de Armas by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption      = De Armas at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name   = Ana Celia de Armas Caso\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|4|30}}\n| birth_place  = [[Havana]], Cuba\n| citizenship  = {{hlist|Cuban}} Spanish\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2006\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Marc Clotet]]|2011|2013|reason=divorced}}\n}}\n'''Ana Celia de Armas Caso''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8ana \u02c8selja de \u02c8armas \u02c8kaso|}}; born 30 April 1988) is a Cuban actress. She began her career as a teenager in her native Cuba and most notably had a leading role in the romantic drama ''[[Manuel Guti\u00e9rrez Arag\u00f3n|Una rosa de Francia]]'' (2006). At the age of 18, she moved to [[Madrid, Spain]] and starred in the popular teen drama ''[[El Internado]]'' for six seasons from 2007 to 2010. After moving to Los Angeles, de Armas had English-speaking roles in the horror film ''[[Knock Knock (2015 film)|Knock Knock]]'' (2015) and the crime drama ''[[War Dogs (2016 film)|War Dogs]]'' (2016). She had a supporting role in the sports biopic ''[[Hands of Stone]]'' (2016).\n\nDe Armas rose to prominence with her role as a holographic [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] projection in the science fiction film ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]'' (2017). Her performance as a nurse in the 2019 mystery film ''[[Knives Out]]'' was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress]].\n\n==Early life==\nAna Celia de Armas Caso was born on 30 April 1988 in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]].<ref name=voguees>{{cite news |url=https://www.vogue.es/living/articulos/ana-de-armas-entrevista-vogue-abril-2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> When she was an infant, her family moved to the seaside town of [[Santa Cruz del Norte]].<ref name=voguees/> Her father, Ram\u00f3n, worked in different positions including as a bank manager, a teacher, a school principal, and the deputy mayor of a town.<ref name=mujerhoy>{{cite news |last1=Navarro |first1=por Isabel |title=Ana de Armas: \"Mi punto fuerte es que no hay otra como yo\" |url=https://www.mujerhoy.com/vivir/protagonistas/201709/09/armas-punto-fuerte-otra-20170907092030.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=mujerhoy |date=17 March 2020 |language=es}}</ref> He had previously studied philosophy at a [[Russia|Russian]] university.<ref name=magazinec>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas Is Conquering Hollywood in Record Time |url=https://magazinec.com/style/ana-de-armas-is-conquering-hollywood-in-record-time/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=C Magazine |date=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=mujerhoy/> Her mother, Ana, worked in the human resources section of the Ministry of Education.<ref name=vogue.es>{{cite news |title=De Cuba a Madrid, y hasta los cielos de Hollywood: la historia de Ana de Armas |url=https://www.vogue.es/living/articulos/ana-de-armas-entrevista-vogue-abril-2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=Vogue Espa\u00f1a |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref name=oncuba>[http://oncubamagazine.com/culture/ana-de-armas-a-cuban-woman-out-to-conquer-hollywood/ A Cuban Women Out To Conquer Hollywood] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105161041/http://oncubamagazine.com/culture/ana-de-armas-a-cuban-woman-out-to-conquer-hollywood/ |date=5 November 2016 }} On Cuba magazine</ref><ref>[https://magazinec.com/style/ana-de-armas-is-conquering-hollywood-in-record-time Ana de Armas is conquering Hollywood in record time]</ref> She has one older brother, Javier, a [[New York City|New York]]-based photographer<ref name=mujerhoy/><ref>{{cite web|title=When my brother finds a photo of me, he took back in 2015.|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BeGp3vwjDLN/|accessdate=18 January 2018|work=Instagram}}</ref> who, in 2020, was questioned by Cuban police due to his links to independent artists on the island and his critical stance on Decree 349.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Noticias |first1=Asere |title=Javier Caso, hermano de Ana de Armas, es interrogado por la Seguridad del Estado |url=https://www.asere.com/javier-caso-hermano-de-ana-de-armas-es-interrogado-por-la-seguridad-del-estado-en-cuba/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Asere Noticias |date=16 January 2020 |language=es}}</ref> While de Armas grew up with [[Rationing in Cuba|food rationing]], fuel shortages and electricity blackouts during Cuba's [[Special Period]],<ref name=mujerhoy/><ref>{{cite news |title=En mi primera pel\u00edcula me enamor\u00e9 de varias personas, eso ahora no me pasar\u00e1 |url=https://www.revistavanityfair.es/la-revista/articulos/entrevista-con-ana-de-armas-blade-runner-2049-fecha-estreno/23251 |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |date=9 December 2019 |language=es}}</ref> she has described her childhood as happy.<ref name=vogue.es/>\n\nAs a child and teenager, de Armas had no internet access and had limited knowledge of popular culture beyond Cuba.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crespo |first1=Irene |title=Ana de Armas: \"Antes de 'Blade Runner' no me sal\u00eda nada, por el acento\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/09/19/tentaciones/1505831920_388735.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=28 September 2017 |language=es}}</ref> She was allowed to watch \"20 minutes of cartoons on Saturday and the Sunday movie matinee.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas talks James Bond & playing Marilyn Monroe |url=https://www.net-a-porter.com/gb/en/porter/article-a838dd936e0153af/cover-stories/cover-stories/ana-de-armas |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=NET-A-PORTER}}</ref> Her family did not own a \"video or DVD player\" and she watched Hollywood movies in her neighbour's apartment.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas, la novia virtual del nuevo \u2018Blade Runner\u2019 |url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/gente/20171014/432031439621/entrevista-ana-de-armas-blade-runner-cuba.html |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=La Vanguardia |date=13 October 2017 |language=es}}</ref> She memorised and practised monologues in front of the mirror,<ref>{{cite news |title=Hollywood's Next Big Thing: 'Blade Runner 2049' Breakout Ana de Armas |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hollywoods-next-big-thing-blade-runner-2049-breakout-ana-de-armas-1044837 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Crespo |first1=Irene |title=Ana de Armas: \"Antes de 'Blade Runner' no me sal\u00eda nada, por el acento\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/09/19/tentaciones/1505831920_388735.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=28 September 2017 |language=es}}</ref> and decided to become an actress when she was 12.<ref name=\"ideal\">{{cite news|title=Los ojos verdes de Hollywood no ten\u00edan trabajo en Espa\u00f1a|url=http://www.ideal.es/gente-estilo/201605/16/ojos-verdes-hollywood-20160514162736.html|accessdate=5 September 2016|work=Ideal|date=16 May 2016|language=es-ES}}</ref> In 2002, at the age of 14, she successfully auditioned to join the [[National Theatre of Cuba|National Theater School of Cuba]].<ref name=vogue.es/><ref name=mirror>{{cite news |last1=Simpson |first1=Richard |last2=Costello |first2=Eugene |title=Bond girl Ana de Armas 'escaped Cuba at first opportunity' to pursue soap fame |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/celebrity-news/bond-girl-ana-de-armas-16201516 |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=irishmirror |date=25 May 2019}}</ref> She hitchhiked or travelled by bus each day to attend the \"rigorous\" course in Havana.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Rub\u00e9n Romero |title=A seis grados de Marilyn Monroe |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2014/05/07/icon/1399458158_612811.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=7 May 2014 |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Crosley |first1=Sloane |title=All About Ana |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/all-about-ana-march-2020-cover-story |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |language=en}}</ref> While a student there, she filmed three movies.<ref name=oncuba/><ref name=mujerhoy/> She left the four-year drama course months before presenting her final thesis because Cuban graduates are forbidden from leaving the country without completing three years of mandatory service to the state.<ref name=oncuba/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Circles |title=Interview with Cuban actress Ana de Armas |url=https://havanatimes.org/interviews/interview-with-cuban-actress-ana-de-armas/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Havana Times |date=22 January 2011}}</ref> At the age of 18, with \u20ac200 in savings and Spanish citizenship through her maternal grandparents,<ref name=vanityfair.es>{{cite news |title=En mi primera pel\u00edcula me enamor\u00e9 de varias personas, eso ahora no me pasar\u00e1 |url=https://www.revistavanityfair.es/la-revista/articulos/entrevista-con-ana-de-armas-blade-runner-2049-fecha-estreno/23251 |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |date=9 December 2019 |language=es}}</ref> de Armas moved to [[Madrid|Madrid, Spain]] to pursue an acting career.<ref name=oncuba/>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 2006\u20132014: Spanish stardom ===\nAs a teenager in her native Cuba, de Armas had a starring role opposite [[\u00c1lex Gonz\u00e1lez (actor)|\u00c1lex Gonz\u00e1lez ]] in [[Manuel Guti\u00e9rrez Arag\u00f3n]]'s romantic drama ''Una rosa de Francia'' (2006).<ref name=vanityfair.es/> While attending a birthday party with the daughters of Cuban actor [[Jorge Perugorr\u00eda]], she learned that auditions for the project were being held in Havana.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanguino |first1=Juan |title=Ana de Armas: la actriz que Espa\u00f1a infravalor\u00f3 y Hollywood abraz\u00f3 |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/10/28/icon/1572267101_072687.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=4 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> The director interrupted the sixteen-year-old during her audition to inform her that the role was hers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105161041/http://oncubamagazine.com/culture/ana-de-armas-a-cuban-woman-out-to-conquer-hollywood/ |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> She then starred in the movie ''El ed\u00e9n perdido'' (2007) and had a supporting role in [[Fernando P\u00e9rez (director)|Fernando P\u00e9rez]]'s ''Madrigal'' (2007), filmed at night without the permission of her drama school tutors.<ref name=oncuba/> \n\nAt the age of 18, de Armas moved to Madrid, Spain. Within two weeks of arriving, she met with casting director Luis San Narciso, who had seen her in ''Una rosa de Francia''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crespo |first1=Irene |title=Ana de Armas: \"Antes de 'Blade Runner' no me sal\u00eda nada, por el acento\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/09/19/tentaciones/1505831920_388735.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=28 September 2017 |language=es}}</ref> He cast her as Carolina in the teen drama ''[[El Internado]]'',<ref name=oncuba/> in which she starred for six seasons from 2007 to 2010. The television show, set in a boarding school, became popular with viewers and made de Armas a celebrity figure in Spain.<ref name=oncuba/> In a break from filming, she starred in the successful coming-of-age comedy ''[[Mentiras y Gordas]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite news |last1=BELINCH\u00d3N |first1=GREGORIO |title=Un estupendo fin de semana para el cine espa\u00f1ol |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2009/03/30/actualidad/1238364015_850215.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=30 March 2009 |language=es}}</ref> Despite the popularity of ''El Internado'', de Armas felt typecast and was mainly offered roles for teenagers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crespo |first1=Irene |title=Ana de Armas: \"Antes de 'Blade Runner' no me sal\u00eda nada, por el acento\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/09/19/tentaciones/1505831920_388735.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=28 September 2017 |language=es}}</ref> She asked to be written out of the show in its second last season.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanguino |first1=Juan |title=Ana de Armas: la actriz que Espa\u00f1a infravalor\u00f3 y Hollywood abraz\u00f3 |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/10/28/icon/1572267101_072687.html |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=4 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> After spending a few months living in New York to learn English,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Circles |title=Interview with Cuban actress Ana de Armas |url=https://havanatimes.org/interviews/interview-with-cuban-actress-ana-de-armas/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Havana Times |date=22 January 2011}}</ref> de Armas was persuaded to return to Spain to star in seventeen episodes of the historical drama ''Hispania'' (2010\u20132011).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vogue.es/living/articulos/ana-de-armas-entrevista-vogue-abril-2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> She then starred in [[Antonio Trashorras]]'s horror films ''El callej\u00f3n'' (2011) and ''Anabel'' (2015),<ref>{{cite news |last1=Costa |first1=Jordi |title=Opini\u00f3n {{!}} Una coreograf\u00eda s\u00e1dica |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2013/02/28/actualidad/1362084592_653965.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=1 March 2013 |language=es}}</ref> and in the drama ''Por un pu\u00f1ado de besos'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oca\u00f1a |first1=Javier |title=Opini\u00f3n {{!}} Romanticismo de \u2018Superpop\u2019 |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2014/05/15/actualidad/1400173366_065368.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=16 May 2014 |language=es}}</ref> During a long period without acting work,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Rub\u00e9n Romero |title=A seis grados de Marilyn Monroe |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2014/05/07/icon/1399458158_612811.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=7 May 2014 |language=es}}</ref> de Armas participated in workshops at [[Tomaz Pandur]]'s Madrid theatre company<ref name=mujerhoy/> and felt \"very anxious\" about the lack of momentum in her career.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas talks James Bond & playing Marilyn Monroe |url=https://www.net-a-porter.com/gb/en/porter/article-a838dd936e0153af/cover-stories/cover-stories/ana-de-armas |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=NET-A-PORTER}}</ref> With encouragement from her newly-hired Hollywood agent, she decided to move to Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crespo |first1=Irene |title=Ana de Armas: \"Antes de 'Blade Runner' no me sal\u00eda nada, por el acento\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2017/09/19/tentaciones/1505831920_388735.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=28 September 2017 |language=es}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015\u20132019: Move to Hollywood===\nWhen de Armas first arrived in Los Angeles in 2014,<ref name=hollywoodreporter>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hollywoods-next-big-thing-blade-runner-2049-breakout-ana-de-armas-1044837|title=Hollywood's Next Big Thing: 'Blade Runner 2049' Breakout Ana de Armas|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> she had to start her career again \"from scratch.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas, la novia virtual del nuevo \u2018Blade Runner\u2019 |url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/gente/20171014/432031439621/entrevista-ana-de-armas-blade-runner-cuba.html |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=La Vanguardia |date=13 October 2017 |language=es}}</ref> She spoke very little English and, during early auditions, she often \"didn\u2019t even know what [she] was saying.\"<ref name=magazinec/> She took intensive English lessons,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanguino |first1=Juan |title=Ana de Armas: la actriz que Espa\u00f1a infravalor\u00f3 y Hollywood abraz\u00f3 |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/10/28/icon/1572267101_072687.html |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=4 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> not wanting to be confined to playing roles specifically written for Latina actresses.<ref name=oncuba/> She starred opposite [[Keanu Reeves]] in her first Hollywood release - [[Eli Roth]]'s erotic horror thriller ''[[Knock Knock (2015 film)|Knock Knock]]'' (2015) - and learned her lines phonetically.<ref name=thrbond>{{cite news |title=Bond Women: How Rising Stars Lashana Lynch and Ana de Armas Are Helping Modernize 007 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/how-lashana-lynch-ana-de-armas-are-helping-modernize-james-bond-1252345 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref> Reeves then telephoned de Armas to invite her to star in a Spanish-language role in the thriller ''[[Exposed (2016 film)|Exposed]]'' (2016), which he acted in and produced.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mA7EzRYoRzc |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> De Armas had a supporting role in [[Todd Phillips]]'s ''[[War Dogs (2016 film)|War Dogs]]'' (2016), acting opposite [[Miles Teller]] as the wife of an arms dealer, and again learned her lines phonetically.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crosley |first1=Sloane |title=All About Ana |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/all-about-ana-march-2020-cover-story |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |language=en}}</ref> David Ehrlich of ''Indiewire'' found her \"memorable in a thankless role\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ehrlich |first1=David |last2=Ehrlich |first2=David |title=\u2018War Dogs\u2019 Review: Jonah Hill Is On Target, But This Gunrunner Comedy Shoots Blanks |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/08/war-dogs-review-jonah-hill-miles-teller-todd-phillips-1201717253/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=IndieWire |date=16 August 2016 |language=en}}</ref> She starred opposite [[\u00c9dgar Ram\u00edrez]] in the biopic ''[[Hands of Stone]]'' (2016) as the wife of Panamanian boxer [[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]]. Despite its delayed release, ''Hands of Stone'' was the first Hollywood movie de Armas filmed. She had been contacted by director [[Jonathan Jakubowicz]] while still living in Madrid; he had seen her in ''El Internado''<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanguino |first1=Juan |title=Ana de Armas: la actriz que Espa\u00f1a infravalor\u00f3 y Hollywood abraz\u00f3 |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/10/28/icon/1572267101_072687.html |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=4 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> and asked her to travel to Los Angeles to audition for the Spanish-language part.<ref>{{cite news |title=En mi primera pel\u00edcula me enamor\u00e9 de varias personas, eso ahora no me pasar\u00e1 |url=https://www.revistavanityfair.es/la-revista/articulos/entrevista-con-ana-de-armas-blade-runner-2049-fecha-estreno/23251 |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |date=9 December 2019 |language=es}}</ref> In reviewing the film, Christy Lemire of ''[[RogerEbert.com]]'' described de Armas as \"a hugely charismatic presence. But except for a couple of showy moments, she gets little to do besides function as the dutiful wife.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lemire |first1=Christy |title=Hands of Stone movie review & film summary (2016) {{!}} Roger Ebert |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/hands-of-stone-2016 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=www.rogerebert.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:KnivesOutToronto.png|thumb|upright|left|Ana de Armas attends the world premiere of ''[[Knives Out]]'' in 2019]]\n\nIn [[Denis Villeneuve]]'s futuristic thriller ''[[Blade Runner 2049]]'' (2017), de Armas had a supporting role as Joi, the [[Hologram|holographic]] [[AI]] girlfriend of [[Ryan Gosling]]'s character. Mark Kermode of ''The Guardian'' said she \"brings three-dimensional warmth to a character who is essentially a digital projection.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kermode |first1=Mark |last2=critic |first2=Observer film |title=Blade Runner 2049 review \u2013 a future classic |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/oct/08/blade-runner-2049-review-a-future-classic |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=8 October 2017}}</ref> Anthony Lane of the ''New Yorker'' found her \"wondrous\": \"Whenever Joi appears, the movie\u2019s imaginative heart begins to race.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lane |first1=Anthony |title=\u201cBlade Runner 2049\u201d: The Mysteries Deepen |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/16/blade-runner-2049-the-mysteries-deepen |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The New Yorker |language=en}}</ref> While the performance was initially discussed as a breakthrough role,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/10/blade-runner-2049-supporting-cast-ana-de-armas-carla-juri-1201884020/|title='Blade Runner 2049': Where You've Seen Standout Supporting Cast Before - IndieWire|first=Kate|last=Erbland|website=Indiewire.com|accessdate=2 December 2017|date=9 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=hollywoodreporter/> the film underperformed commercially, and de Armas spent much of the following year in her native Cuba, where she bought a house.<ref name=thrbond/> Also in 2017, she had a supporting role in the action thriller ''[[Overdrive (2017 film)|Overdrive]]'' as the love interest of [[Scott Eastwood]]'s character.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title='Knock Knock' Actress Ana de Armas Joining Scott Eastwood in 'Overdrive' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/knock-knock-actress-ana-de-823094|accessdate=5 June 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=14 September 2015}}</ref> Stephen Dalton of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' said she \"radiates more kick-ass charisma than her thankless sidekick role might suggest.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Overdrive': Film Review |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/overdrive-review-1029281 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref> In 2018, de Armas starred opposite [[Demi\u00e1n Bichir]] in [[John Hillcoat]]'s medical drama ''Coraz\u00f3n''. She played a Dominican woman with heart failure in the short film, funded by [[Montefiore Medical Center]] to raise awareness of organ donation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hammond |first1=Pete |last2=Hammond |first2=Pete |title=Tribeca Film Festival World Premiere Of \u2018Corazon\u2019 Aims To Save Lives \u2013 Watch The Trailer |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/corazon-trailer-tribeca-film-festival-john-hillcoat-demian-bichir-1202367589/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Deadline |date=19 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDe Armas's role as an immigrant nurse in the ensemble murder mystery film ''[[Knives Out]]'' (2019), directed by [[Rian Johnson]], was widely praised and marked a breakthrough for the actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/|title=Toronto Film Festival: 'Joker,' 'Ford v Ferrari,' 'Hustlers' Among Big Premieres|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=July 23, 2019|accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref> When first approached about the project, she was unenthusiastic about the idea of playing a stereotypical \u201cLatina caretaker\u201d but soon realised that her character was \"so much more than that.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Knives Out' Star Ana de Armas on Declining to Audition and 'Bond' Chemistry with Daniel Craig |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/why-knives-star-ana-de-armas-declined-audition-at-first-1258369 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref> Tom Shone of ''The Times'' remarked: \"The film\u2019s standout performance comes from its least well-known member, the Cuban de Armas, who manages the difficult task of making goodness interesting.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shone |first1=Tom |title=Film reviews: Knives Out; The Two Popes |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/magazine/culture/film-reviews-knives-out-the-two-popes-p3v7bg666 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=www.thetimes.co.uk |language=en}}</ref> Benjamin Lee of ''The Guardian'' said her \"striking\" performance left a \"lasting impression.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/08/knives-out-review-rian-johnson-crafts-a-devious-meta-whodunnit |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The film was a major box office success.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rubin |first1=Rebecca |last2=Rubin |first2=Rebecca |title=Box Office: \u2018Knives Out\u2019 Carves Out $300 Million Worldwide |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/box-office/box-office-knives-out-milestone-1203501247/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=11 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> De Armas was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical]]<ref>{{cite news |title=\"Knives Out\" actress Ana de Armas is nominated for a Golden Globe |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/knives-out-actress-ana-de-armas-nominated-golden-globe-n1098191 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=NBC News |language=en}}</ref> and the cast won the [[National Board of Review Award for Best Cast]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Matt |last2=Donnelly |first2=Matt |title=National Board of Review Names \u2018The Irishman\u2019 Best Movie of the Year |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/national-board-of-review-irishman-best-movie-1203422503/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=3 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> While de Armas's scenes opposite [[Himesh Patel]] in the 2019 romantic comedy ''[[Yesterday (2019 film)|Yesterday]]'' were included in the movie's trailer, they were deleted from the final cut. The director [[Danny Boyle]] said that, while de Armas was \"really radiant\" in her scenes, the introduction of a love triangle subplot did not test well with audiences.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yesterday Cut An Entire Character From The Film That Would Have Changed The Plot |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2475654/yesterday-cut-an-entire-character-from-the-film-that-would-have-changed-the-plot |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=CINEMABLEND |date=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020: Seven film roles===\nDe Armas has seven films scheduled for release in the United States in 2020. She had a supporting role in the crime thriller ''[[The Informer (2019 film)|The Informer]]'' as the wife of [[Joel Kinnaman]]'s character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/ana-de-armas-joel-kinnaman-rosamund-pike-three-seconds-andrea-di-stefano-common-clive-owen-thunder-road-pictures-the-fyzz-facility-1202126156/|title=Ana De Armas Joins Joel Kinnaman & Rosamund Pike For \u2018Three Seconds\u2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Diana|last=Lodderhose|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> Guy Lodge of ''Variety'' found \"her thin role all the more glaring in the wake of her ''Knives Out'' stardom.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lodge |first1=Guy |last2=Lodge |first2=Guy |title=\u2018The Informer\u2019: Film Review |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/the-informer-review-1203453865/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> She appeared as a [[femme fatale]] in the noir crime drama ''[[The Night Clerk]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/helen-hunt-ana-de-armas-john-leguizamo-the-night-clerk-movie-1202396672/|title=Helen Hunt, Ana de Armas & John Leguizamo Join 'The Night Clerk' Thriller|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|date=2018-05-23|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2018-12-15}}</ref> Brian Tallerico of ''RobertEbert.com'' said the movie had \"no idea\" what to do with her \"blinding charisma\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tallerico |first1=Brian |title=The Night Clerk movie review & film summary (2020) {{!}} Roger Ebert |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-night-clerk-movie-review-2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=www.rogerebert.com |language=en}}</ref> while Katie Rife of ''The AV Club'' remarked that it would be remembered, \"if at all, as a movie de Armas was way too good for.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas is way too good for the lousy, sub-De Palma thriller The Night Clerk |url=https://film.avclub.com/ana-de-armas-is-way-too-good-for-the-lousy-sub-de-palm-1841776487 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Film |language=en-us}}</ref> De Armas starred opposite [[Wagner Moura]] in the Netflix biopic ''[[Sergio (upcoming film)|Sergio]]'' (2020) as Carolina Larriera, a U.N. official and the partner of diplomat [[S\u00e9rgio Vieira de Mello]]. John DeFore of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' found her \"magnetic\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Sergio': Film Review {{!}} Sundance 2020 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/sergio-1274882 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref> while Jessica Kiang of ''Variety'' said she imbued the part \"with an intelligence and will that makes her more than just de Mello\u2019s romantic foil.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kiang |first1=Jessica |last2=Kiang |first2=Jessica |title=\u2018Sergio\u2019: Film Review |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/uncategorized/sergio-review-1203473960/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=30 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nDe Armas will star in three films in late 2020. She will reunite with her ''Knives Out'' co-star [[Daniel Craig]] to play a [[Bond girl]] in [[Cary Joji Fukunaga]]'s ''[[No Time to Die]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/how-lashana-lynch-ana-de-armas-are-helping-modernize-james-bond-1252345|title=Bond Women: How Rising Stars Lashana Lynch and Ana de Armas Are Helping Modernize 007|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Rebecca|last=Ford|date=November 6, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/james-bond-25-live-reveal-rami-malek-daniel-craig-jamaica-1202601779/|title=Bond 25 Live Reveal From Jamaica: Rami Malek, Ana De Armas, Billy Magnussen, Lashana Lynch & Dali Benssalah Among Confirmed Cast|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman|date=November 28, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Fukunaga wrote the role of a Cuban CIA agent specifically for de Armas<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crosley |first1=Sloane |title=All About Ana |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/all-about-ana-march-2020-cover-story |work=Vanity Fair |language=en}}</ref> and a replica of downtown Havana was built at London's Pinewood Studios.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas talks James Bond & playing Marilyn Monroe |url=https://www.net-a-porter.com/gb/en/porter/article-a838dd936e0153af/cover-stories/cover-stories/ana-de-armas |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=NET-A-PORTER}}</ref> She will star in [[Adrian Lyne]]'s erotic thriller ''[[Deep Water (2020 film)|Deep Water]]'', based upon the [[Deep Water (Highsmith novel)|novel]] by [[Patricia Highsmith]]. She and [[Ben Affleck]] play a couple in an adulterous marriage.<ref>[https://deadline.com/2019/08/adrian-lyne-deep-water-ben-affleck-ana-de-armas-patricia-highsmith-adaptation-new-regency-1202658671/ New Regency Bringing Adrian Lyne Back To Directing With \u2018Deep Water;\u2019 Ben Affleck, Ana de Armas In Talks For Patricia Highsmith Adaptation]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/disney-fox-release-schedule-the-last-duel-the-kings-man-nimona-1202787773/|title=Disney Dates A Ton Of Pics Into 2023 & Juggles Fox Releases With Ridley Scott\u2019s \u2018The Last Duel\u2019 To Open Christmas 2020, \u2018The King\u2019s Man\u2019 Next Fall \u2013 Update|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> In her final role of 2020, de Armas will portray [[Marilyn Monroe]] in the Netflix biopic ''[[Blonde (upcoming film)|Blonde]]'', based on the novel by [[Joyce Carol Oates]].<ref>[https://collider.com/ana-de-armas-marilyn-monroe-blonde-movie/ Exclusive: Ana de Armas Eyed to Play Marilyn Monroe in Andrew Dominik\u2019s \u2018Blonde\u2019]</ref> Director [[Andrew Dominik]] noticed de Armas's performance in ''Knock Knock''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.net-a-porter.com/gb/en/porter/article-a838dd936e0153af/cover-stories/cover-stories/ana-de-armas |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> and, while she went through a long casting process, Dominik promised her the role was hers after the first audition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crosley |first1=Sloane |title=All About Ana |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/02/all-about-ana-march-2020-cover-story |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |language=en}}</ref> In preparation for the part, de Armas worked with a dialect coach for a year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bahr |first1=Lindsey |last2=Press |first2=The Associated |title=New year is the year for actress Ana de Armas' break |url=https://www.berkshireeagle.com/stories/new-year-is-the-year-for-actress-ana-de-armas-break,591280 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Berkshire Eagle |language=en}}</ref><ref name=magazinec/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vogue.es/living/articulos/ana-de-armas-entrevista-vogue-abril-2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDe Armas will reunite with her ''Sergio'' co-star Wagner Moura to play the wife of one of the [[Cuban Five]] in [[Olivier Assayas]]'s spy thriller ''[[Wasp Network (film)|Wasp Network]]''.<ref name=waspnetwork>{{cite news |last1=Keslassy |first1=Elsa |last2=Keslassy |first2=Elsa |title=Netflix Scoops Olivier Assayas\u2019s \u2018Wasp Network\u2019 With Penelope Cruz, Edgar Ramirez (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/global/netflix-wasp-network-olivier-assayas-penelope-cruz-edgar-ramirez-1203470566/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=17 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The movie was shot on location in Cuba; it was de Armas's first time to work in her home country since leaving as a teenager.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keslassy |first1=Elsa |last2=Keslassy |first2=Elsa |title=Olivier Assayas on Making \u2018Wasp Network\u2019 in Cuba \u2018During a Very Tense Time\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/penelope-cruz-edgar-ramirez-olivier-assayas-wasp-network-cuba-venice-1203319151/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=31 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> After the film's world premiere at the [[Venice Film Festival]], Jay Weissberg of ''Variety'' said de Armas \"easily\" held her own in the \"impressive cast\", describing her as \"a joyous, bewitching presence whose career seems destined for the big time.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weissberg |first1=Jay |last2=Weissberg |first2=Jay |title=Venice Film Review: \u2018Wasp Network\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/wasp-network-review-1203320589/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Variety |date=1 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Netflix have acquired the rights to ''Wasp Network'' but have yet to announce a release date.<ref name=waspnetwork/>\n\n==Personal life==\nDe Armas began a relationship with Spanish actor [[Marc Clotet]] in mid-2010; they married in [[Costa Brava]], Spain in July 2011 and divorced in early 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas, de \u2018Hispania\u2019 y Marc Clotet, de \u2018F\u00edsica o qu\u00edmica\u2019 se han casado en la Costa Brava |url=https://www.hola.com/cine/2011072053728/boda-anadearmas-marcclotet/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=20 July 2011 |language=es-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Marc Clotet confirma su separaci\u00f3n de Ana de Armas: 'Ha sido de mutuo acuerdo' |url=https://premiosgoya.hola.com/los-goya-2013/201302172270/marcclotet-anaarmas-separacion-goya2013/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA |date=17 February 2013}}</ref> She dated Spanish director and screenwriter David Victori from mid-2013 to mid-2014,<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas encuentra de nuevo el amor |url=https://www.hola.com/cine/2013082266697/ana-de-armas-enamorada-david-victori/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=22 August 2013 |language=es-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=El secreto de la belleza y la sonrisa de Ana de Armas tiene nombre y es David Victori |url=https://www.hola.com/cine/2014032770435/anaarmas-davidvictori-malaga/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=27 March 2014 |language=es}}</ref> was briefly engaged to American talent agent Franklin Latt during a relationship from 2015 to 2016,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armas |first1=Ana de |title=Forever.... @franklinlatt  https://www.instagram.com/p/BG0eFTxjNBU/ |url=https://twitter.com/Ana_d_Armas/status/744361058400350208 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=@Ana_d_Armas |date=18 June 2016 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas encuentra nuevo amor y cumple su sue\u00f1o americano en Hollywood |url=https://www.diezminutos.es/famosos-corazon/famosos-extranjeros/news/g9163/ana-de-armas-encuentra-nuevo-amor-y-cumple-su-sueno-americano-en-hollywood/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Diez Minutos |date=5 August 2015 |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u00bfA qui\u00e9n besa Ana de Armas? |url=http://www.zeleb.es/n/a-quien-besa-ana-de-armas-023436 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=www.zeleb.es |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas se 'codea' con Beyonc\u00e9 en Hollywood |url=https://www.hola.com/cine/2016082587953/ana-armas-con-beyonce-deniro/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=25 August 2016 |language=es-US}}</ref> and dated Cuban painter Alejandro Pi\u00f1eiro Bello from 2017 to 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ana de Armas apoya a su chico y se muestra ' muy orgullosa' de su exposici\u00f3n |url=https://www.hola.com/actualidad/20180223120789/ana-de-armas-orgullosa-alejandro-pineiro-deco/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=HOLA USA |date=23 February 2018 |language=es-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Este es Alejandro Pineiro, el joven que rob\u00f3 el coraz\u00f3n de la cubana Ana de Armas |url=https://www.cibercuba.com/noticias/2018-04-23-u194224-e198483-s27065-este-alejandro-pineiro-joven-robo-corazon-cubana-ana |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=CiberCuba |date=23 April 2018 |language=es}}</ref> De Armas is in a relationship with American actor and filmmaker [[Ben Affleck]], whom she met in the fall of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Affleck and Ana de Armas Spotted in Her Native Cuba After Wrapping Thriller Together |url=https://people.com/movies/ben-affleck-and-ana-de-armas-spotted-in-her-native-cuba-after-wrapping-thriller-together/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=PEOPLE.com |language=EN}}</ref>\n\nOn social media, de Armas has voiced support for the [[Ele N\u00e3o movement]],<ref>{{cite news |title=A N A D E A R M A S on Instagram: \u201cWomen of Brazil, I stand with you, I also say #elenao ! We want our leaders to protect HUMAN RIGHTS, to say NO to violence, NO to racism,\u2026\u201d |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BoIZ0ZrjHKP/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Instagram |language=en}}</ref> the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement,<ref>{{cite news |title=A N A D E A R M A S on Instagram: \u201c#altonsterling\ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffe #philandocastile \ud83d\udc94\u201d |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BHkwFWDDhOB/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Instagram |language=en}}</ref> the [[equal pay for equal work]] movement,<ref>{{cite news |title=A N A D E A R M A S on Instagram: \u201cEqual work. Equal pay. #equalpayday\u201d |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhaCvxRjEpv/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Instagram |language=en}}</ref> and the fight for [[same-sex marriage in the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |title=A N A D E A R M A S on Instagram: \u201c#lovewins \ud83d\udc97\ud83d\udc9b\ud83d\udc9a\ud83d\udc99\ud83d\udc9c\u201d |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/4Zi9xeDNM9/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Instagram |language=en}}</ref> She criticised the \"injustice\" of the [[Trump administration family separation policy]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armas |first1=Ana de |title=Please, read this message from  my friend and amazing artist @DemianBichir ! We all have the responsibility to change this injustice. Thanks Demian!https://deadline.com/2018/06/demian-bichir-criticizes-forced-separation-illegal-immigrant-children-human-shields-donald-trump-1202413610/&nbsp;\u2026 |url=https://twitter.com/Ana_d_Armas/status/1009200209681739777 |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=@Ana_d_Armas |date=19 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT use \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Una rosa de Francia''\n| Marie\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Madrigal''\n| Stella 